<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New, supposedly improved Lobbying Commission underfunded, groups  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Nine people. More than 2,000 agencies. Government
watchdog groups said that, despite the recent political rhetoric, there will be
no increased scrutiny of lobbyists in Albany until the state Lobbying Commission
gets the resources it needs.
<P>
	   The Common Cause and the League of Women Voters want Gov. George Pataki to
increases funding for the commission in the 30-day amendments he will file next
month to his 2000-01 state budget proposal.
</P>
<P>
	   "It cannot be expected to do the job that is expected of it with its current
resources," said Barbara Bartoletti of the League of Women Voters.
</P>
<P>
	   The commission has nine people reviewing more than 2,000 agencies, said
Executive Director David Grandeau. The new law doubles the amount of paperwork
and the commission will need more staffers to review it.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki didn't mention any increase for the commission in last week's budget
proposal.
</P>
<P>
	   Joe Conway, a spokesman for the state's Budget Division, said it was
premature to discuss the contents of the 30-day amendments.
</P>
<P>
	   The need to reform the state's lobbying laws was brought home last fall,
when Sharon Portnoy, lobbyist for tobacco giant Philip Morris, admitted she
manipulated documentation to hide thousands of dollars she had spent wining and
dining lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
	   Her techniques included falsely submitting the names of people attending
receptions and nights out with lawmakers in order to keep individual meal costs
down overall. It is illegal in New York to give lawmakers and officials any
gifts worth more than $75 if they are intended to influence their official
duties.
</P>
<P>
	   Philip Morris was fined $75,000, which the Lobbying Commission said was the
maximum it could impose under state law. Portnoy was also fined, banned from
lobbying in New York for three years and she faces a possible criminal
investigation in Albany County for her activities.
</P>
<P>
	   The highly publicized incident helped spur passage of a law that began Jan.
1.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to random audits, lobbyists are required to file reports far
more frequently and could be subject to fines of up to $25 a day for late
reports.
</P>
<P>
	   Lobbyists are also required to list the bill, rule, or regulation they are
discussing with legislators. In addition to civil penalties, lobbyists who fail
to file timely statements or reports, submit false information, or exceed the
$75 gift limit may be guilty of a Class A misdemeanor charge for the first
offense and a Class E felony for subsequent offenses.
</P>
<P>
	   The law also extends the "temporary" commission's term for eight years,
rather than the two-year reprieves that had been typical during the past two
decades.
</P>
<P>
	   Erik Joerss, a spokesman for Common Cause, said his organization had
advocated a law that covered state agencies such as the Office of General
Services, which issues statewide contracts on items including police cars and
computer systems. The proposal would also cover local governments as well.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, the organization welcomed the changes.
</P>
<P>
	   "But for this to be an effective agency with expanded powers it needs more
money," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, lobbyists are grumbling about some of the new law's requirements.
</P>
<P>
	   "A lot of what we do is not bill related," said Mary Downes, of the
Syracuse-based Dairylea Cooperative. She said a Dairylea lobbyist might be
discussing ways to help the state's agriculture industry that had nothing to do
with a pending bill or regulation. "We won't be able to put that down," she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-17-00 0014 </TRAILER>
