<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Officials call for shutdown of UConn hospital  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   FARMINGTON, Conn. (AP) - Eliminating inpatient care at the University of
Connecticut's John Dempsey Hospital is one way to save the health center's
medical and dental schools, officials say.
<P>
	   The health center has been running up millions of dollars in deficits and
the 204-bed hospital is the open wound.
</P>
<P>
	   Raymond Gorman, commissioner of the state Office of Health Care Access, is
preparing a report for state legislators for next week which lends support to
the idea of closing Dempsey.
</P>
<P>
	   The report follows two months of meetings in which the Hartford area's
hospitals - including Hartford Hospital, St. Francis Hospital and Medical
Center, New Britain General, and Connecticut Children's Medical Center - were
asked by Gov. John G. Rowland to consider ways to safeguard UConn's future in
terms of regional health care.
</P>
<P>
	   "There is a strong sense among the area hospitals that they would not
participate in anything that subsidizes inpatient care at John Dempsey
Hospital," said Gorman.
</P>
<P>
	   However, Gorman said the area hospitals are committed to the survival of
UConn's medical and dental schools and have offered to further subsidize their
academic programs and provide more training opportunities for students.
</P>
<P>
	   "We are now saying we are responsible for the medical school, not the
hospital," said Kevin Kinsella, vice president of Hartford Hospital and a
participant in the talks.
</P>
<P>
	   The medical and dental schools, a research center and John Dempsey Hospital
make up the UConn Health Center.
</P>
<P>
	   Affiliation with another hospital was among several recommendations made by
a consultant last year as one may of helping the health center emerge from a $21
million deficit.
</P>
<P>
	   However, that idea has lost support.
</P>
<P>
	   "Any hospital affiliation with Dempsey to subsidize Dempsey, that's a dead
issue,"' Gorman said.
</P>
<P>
	   Gorman's report will be delivered to leaders of the legislature's public
health committee, where it is expected to set a framework for discussions about
the health center and other hospitals in the region.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm not going to recommend that we close Dempsey this year," said state
Sen. Toni N. Harp, D-New Haven, the committee co-chairwoman.
</P>
<P>
	   Harp and public health co-chairwoman Mary U. Eberle, D-Bloomfield, said they
hope to appoint a panel to map out the future of hospital services and
facilities in the Hartford region.
</P>
<P>
	   Peter J. Deckers, dean of the UConn medical school and interim head of the
health center, said he can foresee Dempsey's mission changing as a result of
regional planning, but not the hospital closing.
</P>
<P>
	   Deckers said the hospital is the only place where faculty members can teach
and students can practice, unconstrained by the financial pressures of managed
care.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't believe for a minute that closing John Dempsey Hospital is a viable
option at all," Deckers said. "In a very short time, you would have a very
mediocre medical school."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-17-00 0056 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
