<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quest for Hardier Chicken  </HEADLINE>
    By JEFFREY BAIR Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Chicken soup might make a person feel better when ill,
but what about the chicken?
</P>
<P>
	   A common parasite found in the birds can make them too scrawny for market,
prompting poultry farmers to spend millions each year in drugs and vaccines.
Now, two companies are trying to build a better chicken.
</P>
<P>
	   Demegen Inc. of Pittsburgh and Avigenics Inc. of Athens, Ga., announced
plans last week for joint research on chickens with a genetic trait that allows
them to resist the parasite coccidiosis.
</P>
<P>
	   The parasite, which does not affect humans, irritates the intestines of
chickens and interferes with the absorption of food. That can hinder growth in
the six to eight weeks from birth to slaughter, said Yvonne Vizzier, a poultry
science professor at Mississippi State University.
</P>
<P>
	   Demegen and Avigenics estimate that $600 million is spent by the poultry
industry annually on penicillin and other antibiotic drugs that keep the bug at
bay. Vizzier said the cost is probably much higher.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's been a chronic problem in the poultry industry, and it would be
wonderful if someone could do something about it," she said Friday. "Anything
that would reduce those costs would have to be looked on favorably."
</P>
<P>
	   Another problem is that the drugs are having less effect as the birds become
resistant to them.
</P>
<P>
	   Several other companies are already in the hunt for hardier chickens, said
Hans Cheng, a U.S. Agriculture Department poultry researcher in East Lansing,
Mich.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's premature to talk about their prospects, but it is good to see
companies developing compounds that would work much quicker than traditional
breeding," Cheng said.
</P>
<P>
	   Scientists say chickens, unlike plants, are difficult to breed naturally to
make them resistant to disease. Early success can easily be reversed, and
erratic mating "makes it hard to keep the gene pool stable," Vizzier said.
</P>
<P>
	   A Michigan scientist, Lyman Crittenden, already has made chickens
genetically resistant to a type of cancer, but Cheng said no one has yet
announced success in fighting off the more common parasite.
</P>
<P>
	   Demegen already has a patent for getting disease-fighting genes into plants
such as tobacco and cotton. Avigenics has been attempting to improve chickens
and eggs and is trying to clone a chicken, said Carl Marhaver, the company's
chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
	   The partners hope to sell their hardier birds to U.S. poultry producers.
</P>
<P>
	   "Chickens are bred for different markets, whether for Kentucky Fried Chicken
or to be sold at the grocery store, but generally the bigger the better," said
Richard Ekstrom, Demegen's president.
</P>
<P>
	   His company's scientists used 200 disease-fighting molecules previously
identified in frogs, bugs and other animals as models. Then they fashioned a
man-made molecule that resists the parasite and can be attached to chicken
genes.
</P>
<P>
	   Ekstrom said coccidiosis (pronounced coc-seh-dee-OH-sis) is the researchers'
priority, but they also want to develop chickens resistant to salmonella and
Campylobacter. Neither germ harms the chicken, but both can sicken humans.
</P>
<P>
	   The germs spread from chicken organs to meat during slaughter and can cause
diarrhea, fever and cramps in humans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 0119 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
