<DOCNO> APW20000117.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Play Offers Political Lesson  </HEADLINE>
   By CARL HARTMAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- What would happen if a hugely successful military figure
wanted to be president but didn't want to go through the indignities of a
political campaign?
</P>
<P>
	   Washington's Shakespeare Theatre is exploring that question in a
modern-dress production of the Bard's rarely staged ``Coriolanus.'' The Roman
general of 2,500 years ago thought he deserved election but hated working for
it, and he came to a bad end. Performances start Tuesday and will run through
March 12.
</P>
<P>
	   Director Michael Kahn calls it an especially appropriate play for the
presidential primary season, although he insists he has no particular candidate
in mind.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's about a candidate's personal and family relations, the changeability
of the mob and how it can be swayed -- all very contemporary issues,'' Kahn said
in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
	   America's top generals haven't wanted the job all that much.
</P>
<P>
	   Colin Powell said before the 1996 election that he didn't have the passion
for politics that he had for soldiering and would not run. William Bennett, who
had been President Reagan's education secretary, commented that Powell didn't
want to endure ``this malarial swamp that we have created.''
</P>
<P>
	   George Washington initially didn't want the presidency either, although he
served two terms.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If I should receive the appointment,'' he wrote, ``and if I should be
prevailed upon to accept it, the acceptance would be attended with more
diffidence and reluctance than I have experienced before in my life.''
</P>
<P>
	   Ulysses S. Grant and Dwight D. Eisenhower had to be pushed into accepting
the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   The GOP convention of 1884 wired an appeal to William Tecumseh Sherman. He
wired back: ``I will not accept if nominated, and will not serve if elected.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Roman general Caius Marcius was less decisive. Fellow aristocrats in the
Senate named him Coriolanus because of his victory over a city called Corioles.
He had plenty of political passion but not much sense.
</P>
<P>
	   A Roman election wasn't exactly like a presidential contest. Instead of a
president, the Senate named two leaders to share executive power. It offered
Coriolanus one of the jobs. But representatives of the lower classes had a veto
over the nomination and they called the general arrogant. He gave them plenty of
ammunition.
</P>
<P>
	   In Shakespeare's opening scene, Coriolanus addresses some Romans
demonstrating against high food prices.
</P>
<P>
	   ``What's the matter, you dissentious rogues ...?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
	   Replies one demonstrator, sarcastically:
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have ever your good word.''
</P>
<P>
	   A.L. Rowse, an historian of the 1500s and 1600s, notes in his edition of
Shakespeare that this isn't helping Coriolanus politically. But the general
still can't get the message.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He that will give good words to thee will flatter beneath abhorring,''
Coriolanus tells the demonstrator.
</P>
<P>
	   That is: Anybody who would say anything nice to you would be a loathsome
flatterer.
</P>
<P>
	   Coriolanus then turns to the other demonstrators:
</P>
<P>
	   ``What would you have, you curs ...?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
	   But he complies with the Roman political custom of donning a white robe,
which makes him a ``candidatus,'' standing in the forum, showing off his wounds
and begging for votes. When the voters change their minds about approving him,
he calls them ``the mutable rank-scented many.''
</P>
<P>
	   The candidate gets so angry that he goes over to the enemy in Corioles and
attacks Rome. Only pleas by his mother, wife and son keep him from destroying
it.
</P>
<P>
	   Back in Corioles, he tries to justify his restraint and -- putting the other
foot in his mouth -- recalls to a crowd how he once conquered their city. They
can't stand him either and stab him to death.
</P>
<P>
	   Coriolanus' dubious political savvy was almost matched by Adm. George Dewey,
who destroyed a Spanish fleet in Manila Bay a century ago. He destroyed his
brief political career with less spectacular results, not with a bang but a
whimper.
</P>
<P>
	   Without disclosing a party or platform, Dewer told a reporter:
</P>
<P>
	   ``Since studying the subject, I am convinced that the office of the
president is not such a very difficult one to fill, his duties being mainly to
execute the laws of Congress.''
</P>
<P>
	   A few weeks later he gave up and told another interviewer:
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't know how I got the idea in the first place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
