<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Seeks Biomedical Funding  </HEADLINE>
   By CURT ANDERSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton will ask Congress for $1 billion more
for biomedical research in his upcoming budget and try to loosen congressional
restrictions on $4.3 billion more in research money, White House officials say.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton will propose $19 billion for the National Institutes of Health in
his fiscal 2001 budget, officials said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It'll mean that the NIH budget will have gone up 80 percent since he's
come into office'' in 1993, Clinton's chief of staff, John Podesta, said on
ABC's ``This Week.'' ``We're at the cusp, I think, of breakthroughs in medical
technology.''
</P>
<P>
	   A White House statement said the increase, if approved, would provide ``new
funding for research on every major disease,'' including AIDS, cancer, heart
disease, diabetes and Alzheimer's. It will continue work on decoding the human
genome and help turn research into real-world practice.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition, a $20 million Center for Research on Minority Health would be
established to examine why some racial and ethnic groups experience high infant
mortality rates, low rates of childhood immunization and greater incidence of
many diseases, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
	   On another issue, Podesta said he would meet Thursday with representatives
of the drug industry to explore its offer for compromise on a prescription drug
benefit for Medicare. Clinton plans to address the issue in his State of the
Union speech Jan. 27.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We hope to push forward with a comprehensive solution to the Medicare
problem, to deal with the baby boom generation,'' Podesta said. ``Front and
center in that will be a prescription drug benefit, which we think the American
people want and the American people need.''
</P>
<P>
	   Last year, the industry ran a television ad campaign sharply critical of the
administration's proposal, which bogged down on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
	   The purpose of Thursday's meeting is ``to see if we can make some progress
on this and see if we can find some common ground,'' Podesta said.
</P>
<P>
	   The drug companies continue to support improved prescription coverage for
the elderly through the private sector. Clinton has proposed having a Medicare
drug benefit run by the government by contracting with companies used by many
private health plans.
</P>
<P>
	   Podesta outlined several other White House legislative priorities as
Congress prepares to return to the Capitol next week. They include:
</P>
<P>
	   --Gun control initiatives, including money in the 2001 budget to develop a
``smart gun'' that only the weapon's owner would be able to use and money for
law enforcement to crack down on a small percentage of gun dealers who sell
large numbers of firearms used in crimes.
</P>
<P>
	   --A balanced budget that would pay off the national debt by 2015 while
providing new spending on Medicare, Social Security, education and the military
-- but may not adhere to previous spending caps.
</P>
<P>
	   The budget agreed to last year by Clinton and congressional Republicans
surpassed those caps, which few of either party believe are realistic in an era
of huge budget surpluses.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm not sure I can tell you what the budget caps are right now,'' Podesta
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 0123 </TRAILER>
