<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Happy Birthday' sung to cardinal by 3,000 at St. Pat's  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Three thousand worshipers sang "Happy Birthday" to
Cardinal John O'Connor as he celebrated Mass the day after turning 80.
<P>
	   "Well, this is wonderful, but does anybody have a job for me?" the cardinal
joked after receiving a standing ovation at St. Patrick's Cathedral on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   Cardinals lose their voting power for new popes once they turn 80, and Pope
John Paul II is expected to name a replacement for O'Connor soon. O'Connor is
also in frail health, unable to stand for long periods as he recovers from
August surgery to remove a brain tumor.
</P>
<P>
	   "At this time, when your illness makes new demands upon your spiritual and
physical resources, I pray that you will press forward, with faith and hope,"
the pope said in a letter read during the Sunday service.
</P>
<P>
	   Traditionally, the Vatican announces new appointments for U.S. posts on
Tuesdays, and O'Connor's successor could be named as early as this week. But the
cardinal's spokesman, Joe Zwilling, noted that the announcement may not be made
that soon.
</P>
<P>
	   "It might happen six months from now," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Zwilling said O'Connor "has left the decision of his future entirely in the
hands of Pope John Paul II."
</P>
<P>
	   Zwilling acknowledged that O'Connor has a role in making a recommendation
about his successor, but he said the final decision is made by the pope.
</P>
<P>
	   On Saturday night, the cardinal attended a birthday party at the
Waldorf-Astoria in his honor. It raised more than $5 million for Catholic
education and other charities. The 1,500 guests included several of the
cardinal's potential replacements, including Edwin O'Brien, archbishop to the
U.S. military; Buffalo's Bishop Henry Mansell, a former top aide to O'Connor;
and Archbishop Justin Rigali of St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
	   Zwilling said O'Connor "was very pleased with the reception he got last
night. He feels very honored, and it meant a lot to him to have the people stand
and sing 'Happy Birthday' to him."
</P>
<P>
	   O'Connor is the spiritual leader of 2.4 million Catholics in Manhattan,
Staten Island, the Bronx and seven upstate counties.
</P>
<P>
	   Sunday's Mass at St. Patrick's included representatives from all 413
parishes and reflected their diversity, with a reading in Spanish and speakers
who included an Asian woman and a black priest.
</P>
<P>
	   The service was briefly disrupted by two men who stood and began shouting
before being escorted out of the church.
</P>
<P>
	   Richard Borelli, 58, of Aurora, Colo., and Brian Byrnes, 41, of Colorado
Springs, Colo., later were charged with disrupting a religious service. They
were blurting out verses from the Bible, police said.
</P>
</TEXT>
