<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Monday, Jan. 17, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cuba Orchestrating Anti-US Protests
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Cuba's government is orchestrating anti-American
demonstrations demanding the return of 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez largely to
protect U.S. property and diplomats in Havana, a top Cuban official says.
Ricardo Alarcon, president of the Cuban National Assembly, said Sunday that
anger over Elian's continued presence in the United States is so real and
widespread among Cubans as to pose a potential danger to American interests. The
Immigration and Naturalization Service has ruled the boy, rescued at sea by the
Coast Guard after his mother drowned Nov. 25 trying to reach the United States,
must be returned to his father in communist Cuba.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
New Restrictions on Biotech Corn
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Environmentalists and farmers alike are praising the
planting restrictions that the government is placing on genetically altered corn
to prevent insects from become resistant to its toxin. About 30 percent of the
corn grown last year was Bt corn, named for the bacteria it contains to kill the
European corn borer. The new restrictions, which the Environmental Protection
Agency worked out with industry, will require farmers to plant at least 20
percent conventional corn in most regions, and 50 percent in areas where cotton
is grown.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
State Department Security Said Lax
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- An inspector general's audit found State Department
security officials failed to sweep scores of rooms for bugging devices and
repeatedly failed to account for highly classified documents, The Washington
Post reported. The IG report said lax security procedures plagued the
department's handling of the government's most sensitive intelligence reports
and that 140 offices handling those materials had never been swept for listening
devices, the paper said in Monday's editions.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Winds Cause Mass Outages in Northwest
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SEATTLE (AP) -- A fierce windstorm swept through the Pacific Northwest
Sunday, killing two people in Washington state and leaving hundreds of thousands
of customers without power. Hien Nguyen, 19, of Lacey, was killed around noon
when a 120-foot fir tree blew down on his pickup truck, crushing the cab, Lt.
Matt Koehler said. A 50-year-old Seattle architect died in an avalanche at the
Crystal Mountain ski resort, about 65 miles southeast of Seattle. Blown-down
trees and limbs caused most of the power outages, utility officials said. The
weather service reported sustained winds of 25 to 35 miles per hour.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Socialist Wins Chile Election
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Socialist Ricardo Lagos narrowly defeated
conservative rival Joaquin Lavin Sunday in a runoff election for president. With
87.5 percent of votes counted, Lagos had 51.3 percent of the vote to Lavin's
48.6 percent, Deputy Interior Minister Guillermo Pickering said. Lavin conceded
defeat, then quickly went to Lagos' campaign headquarters at a downtown hotel to
congratulate him. Economic issues dominated the campaign as voters decided
between Lavin, 46, of the right-wing Alliance for Chile, and Lagos, 61, of the
Concertacion center-left coalition.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ex-CIA Head, Wife Aboard Plane Crash
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) -- Former CIA director Adm. Stansfield Turner was
among 17 people injured in a weekend airplane crash that killed his wife, a U.S.
couple and a Spaniard, Costa Rican authorities said Sunday. Turner, CIA director
under President Carter, was in a San Jose hospital Sunday. No details on his
condition were available. His wife, Karen, was killed Saturday afternoon when
their Taxi Aereo Centroamericano flight crashed into a home shortly after taking
off in San Jose. The plane had been destined for the Tortuguero national park on
Costa Rica's Atlantic coast.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Palestinian Economy Shows Growth
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) -- The Palestinian economy has grown over the past two years,
a U.N. report said Sunday, with higher wages and more people working at home and
in Israel. Investment and exports have stagnated, however, partly due to
concerns abroad about corruption and the Palestinian Authority's political
future. In 1999, more than 47,000 new jobs were created, unemployment fell, and
the average wage rose.
</P>
