<HEADLINE> A Fight for Social Conservatives  </HEADLINE>
   By MIKE GLOVER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   JOHNSTON, Iowa (AP) -- With just a week until Iowa's precinct caucuses
launch the presidential nominating season, there's a still unresolved fight for
the support of social conservatives who are a force in Republican politics.
</P>
<P>
	   To various degrees, four of the six Republican rivals are contending for
that vote, and conceding that the issue has yet to be settled.
</P>
<P>
	   ``You get huge changes in the last seven to 10 days as people really
focus,'' said publisher Steve Forbes, interviewed Sunday on Iowa Public
Television. ``I come from the business sector, where competition is a daily fact
of life.''
</P>
<P>
	   Forbes opened the final week before the caucuses rumbling around the state
in an intense grassroots bus tour sounding sharply conservative themes, but the
ground was not being ceded to him.
</P>
<P>
	   Activists Gary Bauer and Alan Keyes, along with Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch offer
similar conservative themes that have divided the Republican right. One effect
of splitting the conservative vote has been to dilute the impact of
conservatives who have yet to coalesce behind one contender.
</P>
<P>
	   Polls have generally shown Texas Gov. George W. Bush ahead, with Forbes in
second place in Iowa and all the others in single digits. Bauer has hit the
airwaves with new commercials, and is crisscrossing the state in the final days.
</P>
<P>
	   He argues that the commitment his backers display will pay off.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think that with the passion level we've got among our supporters, we're
going to be pleased on caucus night,'' said Bauer.
</P>
<P>
	   He has sought to display some differences with Forbes, and takes care to
remind social conservatives that Forbes hasn't always been with them on issues
like abortion.
</P>
<P>
	   ''... I have a 25-year record on the sanctity of life,'' Bauer said on ``Fox
News Sunday.'' ``I'm not a Johnny-come-lately like Mr. Forbes.''
</P>
<P>
	   But Keyes has his own appeal, with a fiery speaking style and an
in-your-face conservative message. In the latest GOP debate, he declined the
offer to give a closing statement and instead led the candidates in a nationally
televised prayer.
</P>
<P>
	   With almost no organization he got 8 percent of the vote in the last
precinct caucuses.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think people who watch those debates have already decided who is
outstanding,'' said Keyes, also speaking on Fox.
</P>
<P>
	   Hatch has registered as barely a blip in the polling for Iowa's caucuses,
but he aired a 30-minute commercial Saturday night, largely devoted to blasting
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Don't you think it's time that somebody speaks substantially on what's
going on rather than 30-second spots and signs and hoopla ..., really that's
what we've been getting during this campaign,'' said Hatch, who joined Bauer and
Keyes on Fox.
</P>
<P>
	   Arizona Sen. John McCain appeared for a campaign debate in the state, but
isn't competing in the caucuses.
</P>
<P>
	   Polls show Forbes with more success in building backing among the right as
he argues that he has the resources to take the conservative debate to Bush.
</P>
<P>
	   ``You see it in my whole campaign,'' said Forbes. ``They realize I have a
broad-based, principled message that has brought people together.''
</P>
<P>
	   That message was resonating with some as Forbes toured the state.
</P>
<P>
	   Clarence Van Zee of Pella said he looked over the field of conservatives and
had to decide which one actually had a shot at winning.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have to be realistic,'' and that led him to Forbes, Van Zee said. ``He
admits he doesn't have a lot of charisma, but I think he's what you see is what
you get.''
</P>
<P>
	   Van Zee's wife, Trudy, conceded that Bauer is ``a good man, too'' but said
Forbes has a broader appeal.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I believe this man (Forbes) has more answers to more questions,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Rita Wilson of Columbus Junction picked Forbes and said it's a matter of
commitment. Why not the front-running Bush?
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think he's pro-life personally, but I don't know if he'd go out and
fight for it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bauer insists, however, he's poised for a surprise. Using a direct-mail
fund-raising network, he has assembled enough money to stay on the airwaves
during the caucus campaign's closing days. People have often written him off
prematurely, Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Commentators and conventional political analysts thought 10 months ago
that I wouldn't last in the race for three weeks,'' he said. ``Every time there
has been a vote ... we have done substantially better than polling and my
opponents have done substantially worse than the polling.''
</P>
<P>
	   Keyes said he's often dismissed or ignored by the media, but said he can
overcome that.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Given the disadvantages that somebody like me ... labors under, I think
that if I show at all, it's a wonderful performance,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 0205 </TRAILER>
