<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush, McCain Jousting Over Taxes  </HEADLINE>
   By CURT ANDERSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The GOP jousting over taxes continues between Texas Gov.
George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain, who disagree sharply over how the federal
government should use its huge projected budget surplus. Fellow presidential
contender Steve Forbes says both have it wrong.
</P>
<P>
	   ``My only point is, there's a fundamental disagreement between Senator
McCain and me,'' Bush said in a taped interview aired Sunday on CNN's ``Late
Edition.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush said his five-year, $483 billion tax-relief proposal -- which would
consume most of the anticipated surplus not already earmarked for Social
Security -- would help curb bigger government.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The surest way to make sure the budgets aren't bloated is to give the
people their money back,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
	   A five-year, $237 billion tax cut offered by McCain, R-Ariz., would reserve
about $729 billion to keep Social Security and Medicare solvent as the baby boom
generation retires. But Bush said his own plan is ``more realistic'' because it
doesn't depend on Congress to safeguard that money.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain ``trusts money left in Washington, D.C., will be properly spent,''
Bush said. ``I happen to think it's going to be spent on bigger government and
more programs.''
</P>
<P>
	   But the senator, appearing on NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' argued that Bush's
tax cut is too skewed toward the wealthy and does little to protect the
government retirement programs.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm saying it's a matter of priorities,'' McCain said. ``I'm saying we
have obligations, and I'm saying it's conservative to make sure that we make the
promises hold that we made in the form of Social Security, Medicare, and not lay
a huge debt down on future generations of Americans.''
</P>
<P>
	   Forbes, meanwhile, dismissed Bush and McCain as the ``timid twins'' on tax
cuts and touted his proposal for a flat tax and an end to the federal tax code
as being far bolder than anything the governor and senator have advanced.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I get to the heart of the problem: get rid of the code, don't tinker
around the edges,'' Forbes said on ABC's ``This Week.''
</P>
<P>
	   Forbes also began airing a television commercial Sunday in Iowa, site of the
Jan. 24 caucuses that open the presidential nominating season. The ad stresses
character and repeats the millionaire publisher's contention that he isn't
beholden to any special interests. ``He'll keep his word,'' the announcer says.
``Character matters, a lot.''
</P>
<P>
	   The new ad is a follow-up to one running in Iowa and New Hampshire that
accuses Bush of breaking his no-tax pledge as governor.
</P>
<P>
	   On other issues Sunday:
</P>
<P>
	   --Bush, McCain and Forbes agreed that South Carolina voters should determine
whether the Confederate flag continues to fly atop the state capitol and that it
should not be an issue for the presidential campaign. ``That's a legitimate
debate that will be decided by the people of South Carolina,'' said Forbes.
</P>
<P>
	   --Bush said if he were president now he would withhold International
Monetary Fund aid and Export-Import Bank loans from Russia until interim
president Vladimir Putin halted bombing in Chechnya that hits ``innocent women
and children.'' But that would not extend to U.S. aid intended to dismantle
nuclear weapons. ``I think that's a different issue as far as I'm concerned,''
he said. McCain also has said he would withhold such funding from Russia.
</P>
<P>
	   --McCain said he was concerned about industry mergers and that the Senate
Commerce Committee he chairs will hold hearings on the proposed union of America
Online and Time Warner. ``You reach a point at some time where it's not good for
the consumer and it stifles competition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   --Forbes rejected criticism that his TV ads upbraiding Bush over a Texas
tax-cut pledge will hurt the GOP in the November election. ``Do we want an
honest, vigorous debate, or do we want to pretend there are no differences
between the candidates?'' Forbes said. ``This is not going to be a coronation.
This is going to be a real contest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 0207 </TRAILER>
