<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Blasts Gore on Poverty  </HEADLINE>
   By SANDRA SOBIERAJ Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WATERLOO, Iowa (AP) -- Bill Bradley put his indictment of the Clinton-Gore
administration's shortcomings into the words of Martin Luther King Jr.,
imagining the late civil rights leader would declare his dream unfulfilled as
long as 14 million American children live in poverty.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I thought he'd be saying that that's not good enough,'' the Democratic
presidential contender told a community banquet in King's honor Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
	   Today, the federal holiday celebrating King's birthday, both Bradley and his
opponent, Vice President Al Gore, were taking part in commemorations -- Bradley
by dropping in on Iowa's official ceremony and leading a discussion of race at
Drake University; Gore by attending the King family's memorial service at
Atlanta's Ebenezer Baptist Church and then laying a wreath at King's gravesite.
</P>
<P>
	   This evening, Gore and Bradley were meeting at North High School in Des
Moines for a ``Brown-Black'' forum -- the Democrats' last debate before the Jan.
24 Iowa caucuses decide the first test of candidate strength.
</P>
<P>
	   Organized by Rep. Wayne Ford, Iowa's only black state legislator, the forum
is billed an opportunity for black and Hispanic leaders to question presidential
candidates about minority concerns.
</P>
<P>
	   At rallies in school cafeterias and town meetings in country cafes, the
contest between Bradley and Vice President Al Gore has, so far, played out to
almost exclusively white audiences in this state where blacks represent 1.6
percent of the population, and Hispanics just 1.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   America has not solved the problem of racism in the 32 years since King was
assassinated in Memphis, Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
	   He recalled being 11 or 12 years old in his native Missouri and playing
Little League with a black catcher and black left-fielder.
</P>
<P>
	   ``After the game, we would go to a restaurant for hamburgers and we would be
denied service. But because our two African-American players were denied
service, we all left because the team stayed together. That's the way we were,''
Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
	   Racism today ``is more subtle, but no less real,'' Bradley told a small
reception at the Waterloo Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
	   It includes ``not being able to get a loan at the bank to buy that
restaurant and ... doctors in this country, two-thirds of whom won't fully
participate in Medicaid,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley said he has focused his presidential campaign on child poverty and
universal access to health care because 27 percent of black Americans and 30
percent of Latinos don't have health insurance.
</P>
<P>
	   Echoing his familiar theme -- that the economic prosperity touted by Gore
and President Clinton still leaves too many Americans behind -- Bradley said he
tried to imagine what King would say about things today.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I thought that in a country where there are still nearly 14 million
children who still live in poverty, I thought he'd be saying that that's not
good enough. I thought that he would be saying that in a country where there are
44 million Americans without any health insurance that that's not enough,''
Bradley said in a rising voice.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I thought he'd be saying that in a country where families who work hard
and play by the rules but still can't get ahead, that's not enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 0210 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000117.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain, Bradley Lead in N.H.  </HEADLINE>
   By WILL LESTER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- John McCain and Bill Bradley captured the lead in a New
Hampshire poll as likely voters in the nation's first presidential primary began
paying more attention to the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   Republican McCain and Democrat Bradley, who both trail nationally, gained
support from independents and women in New Hampshire in the last two months,
giving both a slight overall edge, according to a Dartmouth College-Associated
Press poll.
</P>
<P>
	   More than four out of five in the January poll said they were paying at
least some attention to the campaign, up from three-fourths in November. And
those who had received a phone call or mail from a candidate's campaign rose 20
percentage points since November.
</P>
<P>
	   The poll Sunday suggested that McCain and Bradley also improved their
standing with registered voters in their own parties in New Hampshire, which has
its primary Feb. 1. Both Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush,
the national Democratic and Republican front-runners, respectively, had the
advantage in a November Dartmouth-AP poll of New Hampshire voters.
</P>
<P>
	   In the latest poll, taken Jan. 9-12, McCain had 42 percent support to 33
percent for Bush in the Republican race; Bradley was at 49 percent to 43 percent
for Gore.
</P>
<P>
	   The previous poll, conducted Oct. 31-Nov. 3, had Bush in the lead, 44
percent to 31 percent, and Gore had an edge over Bradley, 48 percent to 41
percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The margin of error for the sample of 518 likely voters in the Republican
primary was 4.5 percentage points, while it was plus or minus 5 percentage
points for the 418 likely voters in the Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
	   The other GOP candidates -- publisher Steve Forbes, former U.N. Ambassador
Alan Keyes, conservative activist Gary Bauer and Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah --
trail the front-runners. Only Forbes was in double digits, with 11 percent, the
same as in November.
</P>
<P>
	   Both the Republican and Democratic races are very close, with many New
Hampshire polls showing a tilt toward McCain and Bradley, and others showing the
races too close to call or with an edge for Bush and Gore.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dartmouth-AP poll disclosed some interesting dynamics in the races that
have developed into tight contests in both parties in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
	   The poll included 498 likely voters who were first contacted in early
November and were reinterviewed from Jan. 9-12.
</P>
<P>
	   Among that group, one out of three Republicans and one in five Democrats had
switched candidates. The differences were most pronounced among Republicans --
with 80 percent of the switchers from Bush going to McCain, a senator from
Arizona, and Bush getting 20 percent of former McCain supporters.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain pulled slightly ahead of Bush on the questions of who is perceived as
most trustworthy and as providing the strongest leadership, according to the
poll.
</P>
<P>
	   More than half of the Republican switchers were those who said they had been
paying very little attention to the campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think that basically McCain has been able to establish himself with
voters,'' said Linda Fowler, a professor of government and director of
Dartmouth's Rockefeller Center. ``There have been a lot of debates, a lot of
advertising, a lot of free media. People were responding to names, now they're
responding to a more substantial picture of the candidates.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Some candidates are converting people, and Bush isn't one of them.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain improved his appeal with women by 16 percentage points since
November, and is now supported equally by men and women -- 42 percent among each
group, the poll showed. He also improved his standing with independents by 16
points.
</P>
<P>
	   Marise LaPorte, 62, of Milford, N.H., attended a town hall meeting held by
McCain last week and liked his straightforward approach.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It seems that when something comes up, McCain addresses it. He doesn't
evade the issue. He meets things head-on,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
	   The changes in voters' perceptions of the candidate weren't as pronounced on
the Democratic side. Slightly more people viewed Bradley as more trustworthy
than Gore in both the November and January polls, with more than four in 10
saying that about Bradley and under one-third saying it about Gore.
</P>
<P>
	   Linda O'Mahoney, a Democratic-leaning independent from Pembroke, N.H., said
Bradley came across as wishy-washy when she first saw him in television ads and
news coverage.
</P>
<P>
	   ``But when I saw him in person, I was tremendously impressed and moved by
what he had to say,'' O'Mahoney said. ``He was just more dynamic in person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 0213 </TRAILER>
