<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Public Urination Plan Criticized  </HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT JABLON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A homeless advocate has criticized city officials for
trying to ban urinating in public rather than providing housing for the
homeless.
</P>
<P>
	   ``No one's the bad guy here. The bad guy is homelessness,'' Ted Hayes said
last week as he stood in front of a reeking Skid Row toilet to make his point.
</P>
<P>
	   The measure, which is under review by the city Police Commission, would make
it a misdemeanor to urinate or defecate in public or in a place open to public
view unless it was a restroom or similar dedicated facility.
</P>
<P>
	   The maximum punishment would be six months in jail and a $1,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
	   At least eight California cities, including Pasadena, Santa Ana and San
Diego, already have such ordinances, said Deputy City Attorney Hank Morris, who
added that complaints from local businesses usually prompt their passage.
</P>
<P>
	   At a Skid Row news conference Friday, Hayes argued that the city has ignored
the needs of homeless residents.
</P>
<P>
	   He donned plastic medical gloves to open the door of one of the portable
toilets that dot Fifth Street near downtown. There are about 30 of the white
plastic obelisks in the area, but they are poorly maintained and serve as ``sex
bins and drug bins'' that many homeless avoid, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is America's shame,'' he added, displaying the filthy, fly-dotted
interior.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's filthy in there. You might catch something,'' said a woman crouched
between shopping carts and blanket lean-tos on the street.
</P>
<P>
	   Nearby stores, restaurants and even shelters refuse to allow street people
to use their facilities, leaving them nowhere to go but outside, Hayes and
others said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Los Angeles proposal is the latest attempt by cities around the nation
to use nuisance ordinances in an effort to force the homeless off the streets,
Hayes said.
</P>
<P>
	   In New York, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has ordered police to arrest homeless
people who refuse orders to move from sidewalks. Judges last year temporarily
stopped a plan to evict from city shelters homeless adults who refuse to work.
</P>
<P>
	   Last month, the Clinton administration announced it was giving out $900
million to cities, states and nonprofit groups to help some 245,000 homeless
people find their way off the streets and into productive lives.
</P>
<P>
	   Hayes acknowledged that using the streets as a toilet is a problem, saying
it breeds disease and pollutes the ocean when raw sewage is washed down storm
drains.
</P>
<P>
	   But a law making public urination illegal would be a waste of time and
money, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The police would have to catch someone in the very act,'' Hayes said,
adding money for such an effort would be better used to build flush toilets and
hire the homeless to guard and clean them.
</P>
<P>
	   In the long term, he said, a national plan to eradicate homelessness should
be adopted.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We cannot consider ourselves a civilized, free, democratic republic if we
cannot get American people off of these streets,'' Hayes said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 0227 </TRAILER>
