<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Post 29-Month High  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices soared Monday to a 29-month high, supported
by Wall Street's overnight gains. The dollar fell against the yen.
</P>
<P>
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed up 480.68 points, or
2.54 percent, at 19,437.23 points. The average closed up 123.26 points, or 0.65
percent, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   It was the Nikkei's highest close since Aug. 8, 1997, when it ended the
trading day at 19,604.46 points.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar traded at 105.28 yen on the Tokyo foreign exchange market at 3
p.m. (1 a.m. EST) Monday, down 0.46 yen from late Friday, and also below its
late New York level of 105.70 yen overnight.
</P>
<P>
	   On the stock market, broad-based buying from foreign investors, domestic
brokerages and individual investors rallied Japan's key cash index.
</P>
<P>
	   "The Tokyo market was basically mirroring the movement in New York," said
Yuichi Kohashi, a strategist at Daiwa Securities.
</P>
<P>
	   Brokerage houses posted some of Monday's biggest gains, with foreign
investors eager to buy shares in Nomura, Daiwa, and Nikko Securities, traders
said.
</P>
<P>
	   The buying frenzy, however, extended across the board.
</P>
<P>
	   "The market is in a good cycle now," said Kunihiro Hatae, general manager at
Tokyo Securities Co., noting that investor interest spread from high-technology
stocks to biotechnology and domestic-demand issues on Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The advances came after the Dow Jones industrial average climbed 140.55
points to 11,722.98 on Friday. The technology-rich Nasdaq Composite index jumped
107.06 to 4,064.27.
</P>
<P>
	   Tokyo equity markets often move in tandem with Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section closed up 33.73 points, or 2.05 percent, to 1,681.97. The TOPIX closed
down 9.73 points, or 0.59 percent, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   In currency dealings, the greenback fell against the Japanese currency as
market expectation of the central bank easing monetary policy diminished. The
Bank of Japan's fortnightly policy meeting is still in session.
</P>
<P>
	   An increase in the amount of yen available in the market would decrease the
currency's strength against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
	   Japanese government officials have repeatedly said that too strong a yen
could hurt the fledgling economic recovery. A strong yen means that profits on
Japanese products sold overseas are worth less when they are changed into the
Japanese currency.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors are eying the Group of Seven finance ministers' meeting in Tokyo
on Jan. 22 for further clues to the dollar's future.
</P>
<P>
	   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 106.74 yen, down from 108.31 yen
late Friday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond remained
unchanged from Friday's finish of 1.7800 percent. Its price stayed flat at
101.01.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
