<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monday, Jan. 17, 2000 
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Drug Giants Agree on Merger
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- British pharmaceutical heavyweights Glaxo Wellcome PLC and
SmithKline Beecham PLC reached agreement to merge into the world's largest
drugmaker, the companies announced Monday. The merger creates a company valued
at $182.4 billion. The company said the merger would create $1.6 billion in
pretax cost savings after three years. Job cuts were expected, the group said,
but it released no other details. The planned merger still must be approved by
the Federal Trade Commission and the European Union.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mars Lander Search To End
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- After more than a month of searching for a signal
from NASA's Mars Polar Lander, mission controllers are losing any hope that the
$165 million mission to the Red Planet can be saved. The last effort to
communicate with the three-legged lander was scheduled today. After that, space
agency scientists and engineers will focus entirely on what could have gone
wrong and how to avoid the same mistakes in the next mission. Polar Lander was
to have touched down Dec. 3 for a 90-day mission near Mars' south pole to study
the atmosphere and dig for ice. It was last heard from minutes before beginning
its descent.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Paper: Whitney Houston Caught With Marijuana
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   KAILUA-KONA, Hawaii (AP) -- Whitney Houston was caught with 15.2 grams of
marijuana at an airport security checkpoint last week but boarded her departing
flight before police arrived, a newspaper reported Sunday. The Tribune-Herald of
Hilo, Hawaii said an airport security officer at Keahole-Kona International
Airport found the marijuana Tuesday after he asked the Grammy-winning singer to
open her bag for inspection. The bag was seized, but the singer walked away when
security officers tried to detain her, said Police Lt. Robert Hickcox.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cuba Orchestrating Anti-US Protests
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Cuba's government is orchestrating anti-American
demonstrations demanding the return of 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez largely to
protect U.S. property and diplomats in Havana, a top Cuban official says.
Ricardo Alarcon, president of the Cuban National Assembly, said Sunday that
anger over Elian's continued presence in the United States is so real and
widespread among Cubans as to pose a potential danger to American interests. The
Immigration and Naturalization Service has ruled the boy must be returned to his
father in communist Cuba.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
New Restrictions on Biotech Corn
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Environmentalists and farmers alike are praising the
planting restrictions that the government is placing on genetically altered corn
to prevent insects from become resistant to its toxin. About 30 percent of the
corn grown last year was Bt corn, named for the bacteria it contains to kill the
European corn borer. The new restrictions, which the Environmental Protection
Agency worked out with industry, will require farmers to plant at least 20
percent conventional corn in most regions, and 50 percent in areas where cotton
is grown.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
State Department Security Said Lax
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- An inspector general's audit found State Department
security officials failed to sweep scores of rooms for bugging devices and
repeatedly failed to account for highly classified documents, The Washington
Post reported. The IG report said lax security procedures plagued the
department's handling of the government's most sensitive intelligence reports
and that 140 offices handling those materials had never been swept for listening
devices, the paper said in Monday's editions.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Winds Cause Mass Outages in Northwest
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SEATTLE (AP) -- A fierce windstorm swept through the Pacific Northwest
Sunday, killing two people in Washington state and leaving hundreds of thousands
of customers without power. Hien Nguyen, 19, of Lacey, was killed around noon
when a 120-foot fir tree blew down on his pickup truck, crushing the cab, Lt.
Matt Koehler said. A 50-year-old Seattle architect died in an avalanche at the
Crystal Mountain ski resort, about 65 miles southeast of Seattle. Blown-down
trees and limbs caused most of the power outages, utility officials said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Post 29-Month High
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices soared Monday to a 29-month high, supported
by Wall Street's overnight gains. The Nikkei gained 480.68 points to close at
19,437.23.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rangers 6, Thrashers 3
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- John MacLean had two goals and an assist and Jan Hlavac
scored his third goal in two games as the New York Rangers defeated the Atlanta
Thrashers 6-3 Sunday. The Rangers, winning for the fourth time in five games,
scored three times in the first 6:41 and coasted the rest of the way. MacLean
scored his eighth and ninth goals for his second two-goal game of the season and
57th of his career.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS 
</SUBHEAD>
