<DOCNO> APW20000117.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 03:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mora Staying on an Even Keel  </HEADLINE>
    By JIM LITKE AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Win or lose, every morning in Jim Mora's house now
comes and goes much like every other one.
</P>
<P>
	   He isn't likely to get up on one side of the bed and suddenly mellowed,
chuck it all and go fishing. But he is no more likely to get up on the other
side, despondent, and go swimming with the fishes, either.
</P>
<P>
	   In the coaching business, this is called staying on an even keel. People who
remember the epic tirade Mora threw on his way out of New Orleans would call it
significant progress as well.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm not going to go out and commit suicide or get drunk, if that's what
you're asking," Mora said Sunday, just moments after his Colts were beaten 19-16
in Sunday's AFC divisional playoff by Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'll just get up in the morning," he reassured everyone, "and go back to
work."
</P>
<P>
	   Mora's colleague, Jimmy Johnson, will not be in the Dolphins' office when
Mora arrives, no matter the hour. And he won't be the only one. With each
passing day, fewer of the coaches the 64-year-old Mora once regarded as
contemporaries are around to take his calls.
</P>
<P>
	   Only Rams coach Dick Vermeil, 17 months younger than Mora and one of his
closest friends, still shows up at the office with anything like the same
enthusiasm. It may be because Vermeil still has a shot at the Super Bowl. Or it
may be because Vermeil already flamed out once -- he was out of football for 15
seasons before taking the St. Louis job three years ago.
</P>
<P>
	   Almost every other coach in the NFL seems to be in danger of burning out.
Two weeks ago, Bill Parcells, 58, walked away from the New York Jets and Mike
Ditka, 60, was the oldest of a handful of coaches shown the door soon after.
</P>
<P>
	   Having so many coaches out of work is nothing new in the fraternity, but to
have so many big names leave voluntarily is.
</P>
<P>
	   The salary cap and free agency have made it increasingly tough to acquire
new players and at the same time, hold onto the ones you already have. As the
talent margins between clubs gets slimmer, the coaches and general managers,
most already working 24/7, are being asked to work harder and harder. More are
just saying, "No."
</P>
<P>
	   Like Mora, Johnson lost a playoff game, only his came Saturday at
Jacksonville by an embarrassing 62-7 score. It was so embarrassing that Johnson
awoke Sunday, checked the tide tables in the newspaper and decided to chuck it
all. He collected his wife, his Yorkie, headed for his boat and on his way out
the door, Johnson told Miami owner Wayne Huizenga he might be available to
consult on personnel matters occasionally. But as far as working, that was it.
</P>
<P>
	   "He does not want to be under contract. He does not want a job. He does not
want any day-to-day position," Huizenga said. "He wants to fish."
</P>
<P>
	   Johnson is 56, but it seems like he'd been in the business forever. Maybe
that's because Johnson was so driven and so good -- he won a national
championship at the University of Miami and two Super Bowls in Dallas -- that it
was hard to imagine him doing anything less consuming.
</P>
<P>
	   But that was exactly the problem; he had nothing left.
</P>
<P>
	   "This time it's final and forever," Johnson said. "I've had my time in the
sun. I've had my time in the spotlight. And now it's time to spend time with my
family."
</P>
<P>
	   Mora felt the same way in October, 1996, in the middle of his 11th season in
New Orleans. The Saints were 2-6, going nowhere. He spent his days watching
films, running practices, drawing up game plans, sleeping a few hours and
starting all over again.
</P>
<P>
	   Frustrated, he staged a very public, very profane and ultimately
unforgettable meltdown. The next day he resigned.
</P>
<P>
	   "I was," Mora recalled, "a basket case."
</P>
<P>
	   The surprising thing is how a year-and-a-half away from the NFL rejuvenated
him -- that, and returning with a team like Indianapolis, loaded with young
talent and one of the best general managers in the game, Bill Polian.
</P>
<P>
	   A team he expected to finish 8-8 went 13-3 instead. It failed to give him
his first playoff win ever -- Mora is 0-5 -- but he is still cresting on a wave
of optimism. Winning might not really be everything, but it will keep a coach
off the ledge for a while.
</P>
<P>
	   "It isn't that Jim's changed that much," said Vic Fangio, now the Colts
defensive coordinator and a Mora assistant since New Orleans. "What's changed is
that the time away from the game let him see how easy it is to get too wrapped
up in things. He's making an effort to enjoy himself more now. So far it's
worked."
</P>
<P>
	   So far. 
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Jim Litke is the national sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write
to him at: jlitke@ap.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
