<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Renault To Inspect Samsung Motors  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- A four-member survey team from French carmaker
Renault SA arrived in Seoul on Monday to look over South Korea's troubled
Samsung Motors Inc.
</P>
<P>
	   The inspection is part of Renault's move to take over Samsung. They have
been in takeover talks since December.
</P>
<P>
	   The Renault team will survey and inspect Samsung's overall operations,
including its technology and financial condition, Samsung officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   Renault officials said that the takeover would give them privileged access
to the Korean market and a larger base in Asia.
</P>
<P>
	   Samsung Motors, a subsidiary of the giant Samsung Group, entered the
nation's already saturated auto market in early 1998 with an annual capacity of
240,000 cars.
</P>
<P>
	   It produced only 50,000 cars in 1998 and a mere 2,000 more in 1999 since
operations were halted during most of the year amid severe financial
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
	   With $4 billion in debt and $3 billion in assets, Samsung was put in
receivership in 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   The troubled carmaker has been cited as a typical case of over-investment by
South Korean conglomerates which relied heavily on bank loans.
</P>
<P>
	   Another South Korean carmaker, Daewoo Motors Co., is also on the market.
General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co. of the United States have expressed
interest in taking over the No. 2 South Korean car firm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
