<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 09:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Exchange Holdings Hit High  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- South Korea's foreign exchange holdings hit a new
record high of $75.6 billion as of Jan. 15 and will continue to rise to $100
billion by year's end, the government said Monday in a report.
</P>
<P>
	   The Jan. 15 figure was up from $74.5 billion at the end of last year and
compared with a mere $7.2 billion recorded when South Korea sought a bailout of
its economy from the International Monetary Fund in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   Government officials said foreign-currency reserves rose during the last two
weeks because local financial institutions paid off loans from the central bank.
</P>
<P>
	   South Korea's economy, which shrank 5.8 percent in 1998, dramatically turned
around last year, expanding more than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   In a report outlining its economic policy priorities for 2000, the
government reaffirmed its forecast that South Korea's economy will expand around
6 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
	   The country's customs-cleared exports are expected to rise 11 percent this
year to $160 billion, while imports are expected to grow 23.6 percent to $148
billion, the report said.
</P>
<P>
	   According to preliminary figures released earlier this month, South Korean
exports climbed 9 percent in 1999 to $144 billion, while imports surged 28.3
percent to $119 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   Considering the movement in short-term funds and the country's foreign
liabilities, the government will continue to increase its foreign reserves this
year, said officials at the Ministry of Finance and Economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 0910 </TRAILER>
