<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployment Falls in Hong Kong  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    HONG KONG (AP) -- Unemployment dropped slightly to 6.0 percent in the last
three months of 1999 as a result of increased demand for labor and steadily
improving business conditions, the Census and Statistics Department said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The unemployment rate for the three months ended Dec. 31 was down from 6.1
percent in the three months ending Nov. 30, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
	   The economy is coming out of a bruising 15-month recession, expanding 4.5
percent in the third quarter last year. The stock market is back at levels seen
before the financial downturn, and tourism has jumped nearly 10 percent in 1999
from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
	   The government will begin a series of public works and infrastructure
projects in the next six months to create more jobs, the statement said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 0930 </TRAILER>
