<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourist injured in Downing Street crash back in NJ, thankful to be  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A New Jersey woman who pushed her young son away
from an oncoming car at the British prime minister's London residence will
undergo surgery this afternoon to repair her shattered leg.
<P>
	   Ursula Webster, 39, was in London with her husband and three sons on a
sightseeing trip and was visiting 10 Downing Street because they live at the
same address in Livingston.
</P>
<P>
	   She was hailed by British newspapers as the "Heroine of Downing Street"
after she flung her 8-year-old son Andrew away from the car, which struck her
and tossed her 15 feet into the air.
</P>
<P>
	   "I pushed him as hard as I could, and I was hit by the car and thrown
through the air," she said today in a telephone interview from her hospital bed
at St. Barnabas Medical Center in Livingston. "As I was going up, I'm thinking,
'I'm dying, this is it, my life is ending,' and I could actually feel my bones
breaking.
</P>
<P>
	   "But when I hit the ground and was still conscious, I knew it wasn't nearly
that bad," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Andrew was grazed by the door of the red Vauxhall Astra and her 6
1/2-year-old son Alex was grazed by the car's wing mirror, but neither was
seriously hurt. Her 3 1/2-year-old son Peter and her husband David were not
struck.
</P>
<P>
	   The car then smashed into the gates that guard the entrance to Prime
Minister Tony Blair's residence.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Webster left a London hospital Sunday and flew home with her family,
accompanied by a nurse. She arrived late Sunday afternoon at Newark
International Airport, where her mother and other relatives were waiting.
</P>
<P>
	   She sustained a broken femur and tibia, and was to undergo surgery Monday
afternoon at St. Barnabas. She faces three to four months of rehabilitation
after the surgery, she said, and she predicted it would be difficult with three
active children.
</P>
<P>
	   "But I keep thinking this could have been so much worse," she said. "We
could have been killed."
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Webster said she and her family approached police officers at the gate
to the prime minister's residence, explained that they lived at the same address
in New Jersey and asked for and received permission to go inside the gates to
take photographs. It was as they were walking back out through the gates and
thanking the police officers that the accident happened, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   "The car skidded and went straight at the gates," said Sertac Bahri, 19, who
witnessed the accident. "As that was happening a woman tried to push her child
so he didn't get hurt. She saved the kid, but she didn't save herself."
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Webster was treated overnight at St. Thomas's Hospital in London. She
said the flight back to New Jersey was "excruciating."
</P>
<P>
	   London police filed charges Sunday against the driver of the car. Stephen
Bonnett, 26, an engineer from Chelmsford, east of London, was charged with
causing grievous bodily harm and dangerous driving, police said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bonnett was granted bail at a five-minute hearing Monday and ordered to
return to court Jan. 31 to face the charges.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Webster had high praise for British police.
</P>
<P>
	   "They were really great to us," she said. "I have to compliment the London
police."
</P>
<P>
	   Witnesses said tourists were clustered at the gates that lead to Downing
Street when Bonnett's car skidded and crashed. It was not immediately clear
whether he is suspected of deliberately crashing into the ornate black iron
gates or whether he simply lost control of the car.
</P>
<P>
	   Blair and his family were at the British prime minister's country residence,
Chequers, when the crash happened. Blair has asked to be kept informed of Mrs.
Webster's condition and would be writing to her, aides said.
</P>
<P>
	   The prime minister's official residence is visible through the gates that
seal the end of Downing Street - a short street leading on to Whitehall, the
seat of government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
