<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 11:10 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monday, Jan. 17, 2000
</P>
<P>
	   Secret Processor To Be Unveiled
</P>
<P>
	   SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) -- A top-secret computer chip designed
and funded by a powerful group of high-tech leaders is slated to
roll out this Wednesday amid a flurry of high expectations -- and
intrigue. For the past five years, Transmeta Corp. has secretly
toiled away on the project for the past five years. CEO David
Ditzel, a former chip designer for AT&AMP;T's Bell Labs and Sun
Microsystems Inc., is leading the operation. Transmeta all the more
interesting is the cast of characters attached to the Santa
Clara-based company. Employees include superstar designers like
Linux creator Linus Torvalds. Investors include industry barons
like Microsoft Corp. co-founder Paul Allen and billionaire
financier George Soros.
</P>
<P>
	   Glaxo Wellcome Buying SmithKline Beecham
</P>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- The world's largest drugmaker is in the works. The
British pharmaceutical company Glaxo Wellcome PLC plans to buy
rival SmithKline Beecham PLC for about $76 billion in stock. The
agreement announced today would create a company to be called Glaxo
SmithKline that would hold a 7.3 percent share of the global
pharmaceutical market and have a combined market value in excess of
$182 billion. The companies said the merger would create $1.6
billion in pretax cost savings after three years. They said job
cuts were expected, but released no other details.
</P>
<P>
	   Discrimination Suits Jumped in '90s
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Aided by new federal laws, private lawsuits
alleging discrimination in the workplace more than tripled during
in the 1990s, the Justice Department said Sunday. The department's
Bureau of Justice Statistics said job bias lawsuits filed in U.S.
District Courts soared from 6,936 in 1990 to 21,540 in 1998. ``The
growth in civil rights cases has been due largely to the increase
in employment cases between private parties,'' bureau statistician
Marika F.X. Litras wrote. Civil rights complaints of all varieties
more than doubled from 1990 to 1998, from 18,793 to 42,354. They
accounted for 8.6 percent of the 217,879 federal civil cases in
1990, compared with 16.5 percent of all 256,787 civil cases in
1998.
</P>
<P>
	   ENI Buys Stake in Portuguese Firm
</P>
<P>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) -- Italian energy giant ENI is paying $973
million for a 33.34 percent stake in Portuguese energy conglomerate
GALP SGPS, establishing a partnership to pursue joint investments
in Europe, Africa and Brazil. The Spanish utility Iberdrola is also
buying a 4 percent stake in GALP SPGS for $116.8 million, and the
Portuguese utility company Electricidade de Portugal bought another
11 percent of the company to lift its shareholding to 14.27
percent. The negotiated sale of stakes by the Portuguese state and
private investors disclosed today is part of a major restructuring
of GALP SPGS aimed at giving it the financial muscle and expertise
to expand in oil, gas and electricity sectors abroad.
</P>
<P>
	   Renault To Inspect Samsung Motors
</P>
<P>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- A four-member survey team from French
carmaker Renault SA arrived in Seoul on Monday to look over South
Korea's troubled Samsung Motors Inc. The inspection is part of
Renault's move to take over Samsung. They have been in takeover
talks since December. The Renault team will survey and inspect
Samsung's overall operations, including its technology and
financial condition, Samsung officials said. Renault officials said
that the takeover would give them privileged access to the Korean
market and a larger base in Asia.
</P>
<P>
	   Unemployment Falls in Hong Kong
</P>
<P>
	   HONG KONG (AP) -- Unemployment dropped slightly to 6.0 percent in
the last three months of 1999 as a result of increased demand for
labor and steadily improving business conditions, the Census and
Statistics Department said today. The unemployment rate for the
three months ended Dec. 31 was down from 6.1 percent in the three
months ending Nov. 30, the agency said. The economy is coming out
of a bruising 15-month recession, expanding 4.5 percent in the
third quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
	   Church Joins N. Korean Auto Venture
</P>
<P>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- The Unification Church of Rev. Sun
Myung Moon plans to invest $300 million in a joint venture to build
Fiat cars in North Korea, church officials said today. The church's
Pyonghwa Motors and North Korea's state-run Ryonbong Corp.
tentatively agreed last year to build car assembly lines in Nampo
on North Korea's southwestern coast. Under a contract with Italian
automaker Fiat SpA, 10,000 cars will be assembled each year, for
both domestic and overseas markets, church officials said.
Production is expected to start next year.
</P>
<P>
	   Most Asian Stock Markets Higher
</P>
<P>
	   HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed higher Monday,
with the key index in Tokyo rising to its highest level in 29
months on the back of last week's record gains on Wall Street. The
Japanese 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed up 480.68 points, or
2.54 percent, at 19,437.23. It was the Nikkei's highest close since
Aug. 8, 1997, when it ended the day at 19,604.46 points. South
Korean shares also sharply higher, with the main index rising 3.7
percent in reaction to Friday's gains on Wall Street. The Korea
Composite Stock Price Index rose 35.24 points to 983.27. Hong Kong
stocks closed slightly higher after three straight sessions of
declines. The Hang Seng Index gained 32.33 points, or 0.2 percent,
closing at 15,574.56.
</P>
