<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Upturn in Thai Banks Expected  </HEADLINE>
    By TOM WRIGHT
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Many of the larger Thai banks are set to become
profitable early this year, after a dismal 1999 that ended the worst downturn in
recent history, analysts said today.
</P>
<P>
	   Results due on Thursday and Friday will show all banks were deeply in the
red last year as the result of the huge cost of dealing with problem loans,
which totaled 36 percent of total lending at private banks at the end of
November.
</P>
<P>
	   But with loan-loss reserve building almost complete, and as debt
restructuring begins to reduce problem loans racked up since Asia's economic
crisis struck in 1997, large banks should post profits in 2000, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
	   Siam Commercial Bank already began to make net profits in the third quarter
of last year, after it completed provisioning with the help of a government
capital injection.
</P>
<P>
	   It should show a $35 million net profit in the fourth quarter, Kavee
Chukitkasem, an analyst at Capital Nomura Securities, told Dow Jones Newswires.
</P>
<P>
	   Other large banks, such as Bangkok Bank and Thai Farmers Bank, would remain
in the red during the fourth quarter as they continued to divert capital to
loan-loss reserves.
</P>
<P>
	   All banks made huge losses for the full year, including Siam Commercial with
a 1999 net loss estimated at $1.25 billion, said Kavee.
</P>
<P>
	   Thai Farmers, the country's third largest bank, will suffer a full-year net
loss of $864 million said Andrew Maule, bank analyst at ABN Amro Asia
Securities.
</P>
<P>
	   But Thai Farmers is expected return to net profit in the first quarter of
this year. Excluding the cost of provisioning, the bank has made operating
profits since the third quarter due to lower deposit rates.
</P>
<P>
	   The bank has restructured $400 million in problem loans during the fourth
quarter, which immediately began to earn interest. Maule said this should lead
to a "major improvement" in operating profits.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, the country's largest lender, Bangkok Bank, still needs to raise
more capital to complete provisioning in 2000, which should keep the bank's net
results in the red for at least the first quarter, most analysts said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bangkok Bank will have a 1999 net loss of $1.25 billion due to provisioning
costs, although the bank should make operating profits in the fourth quarter,
said ABN Amro's Maule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 1132 </TRAILER>
