<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 11:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Parker Hannifin-Gets Hydraulic Firm  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    CLEVELAND (AP) -- Parker Hannifin Corp., which makes industrial motion and
control devices, is buying Commercial Intertech Corp., a hydraulic systems
maker, for about $366 million in cash and stock.
</P>
<P>
	   In the deal announced today, Parker will also assume about $107 million of
Commercial Intertech's debt.
</P>
<P>
	   Parker's strategy is to serve customers in its industrial, mobile,
commercial and aerospace markets and this deal helps the company extend that,
said Duane Collins, chairman and chief executive officer of Parker Hannifin.
</P>
<P>
	   Collins noted that Parker has acquired 42 businesses in the last six years,
totaling $1.1 billion in first-year sales.
</P>
<P>
	   Parker Hannifan said it will cut some jobs but did not know how many or in
which facilities. "No decision has been made yet but there won't be a
significant employment reduction," said Jennifer Eaton, spokeswoman for Parker
Hannifan.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the terms of the agreement, Parker will pay $20 in cash or stock for
each Commercial Intertech share. The deal is expected to be completed by the end
of June.
</P>
<P>
	   That is a 20.3 percent premium over Commercial Intertech's stock price of
$16.62 in trading Friday when it rose 9 percent. Markets were closed Monday for
the Martin Luther King Jr. holiday.
</P>
<P>
	   The deal is still subject to approval from federal regulators and Commercial
Intertech shareholders.
</P>
<P>
	   Cleveland-based Parker Hannifin had almost $5 million in annual sales last
year and employs nearly 40,000 people in 39 countries.
</P>
<P>
	   Commercial Intertech, which posted sales of $535 million in 1999, has almost
4,000 employees at its 27 facilities worldwide. It is based in Youngstown. The
company makes hydraulic systems, including gear pumps and motors, control valves
and telescopic cylinders for use on equipment such as dump trucks, cranes,
refuse vehicles and backhoes. The company also produces metal stampings,
including tank ends and a variety of other stamped steel products.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
