<DOCNO> APW20000117.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 11:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Glaxo Buying SmithKline Beecham  </HEADLINE>
    By BRUCE STANLEY AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- The British pharmaceutical company Glaxo Wellcome PLC plans
to buy rival SmithKline Beecham PLC for about $76 billion in stock in a
long-anticipated deal that would create the world's largest drugmaker.
</P>
<P>
	   The combination announced today would form a company to be called Glaxo
SmithKline that would hold a 7.3 percent share of the global pharmaceutical
market and have a combined market value of about $182.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   The companies said the union would create $1.6 billion in pretax cost
savings after three years. They said job cuts were expected but that they were
still deciding where to make them.
</P>
<P>
	   The announcement came after previous merger discussions between the two
firms collapsed two years ago.
</P>
<P>
	   "It has not been easy ..., that is true. On the other hand, today we can
honestly say we have a real powerhouse of a new company," SmithKline Beecham
chief executive Jan Leschly told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
	   The Federal Trade Commission and the European Union still must approve the
combination.
</P>
<P>
	   Although executives from both companies stressed that this was "a merger of
equals," their respective shares of ownership of the new group suggest that
Glaxo Wellcome has the upper hand.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the deal, Glaxo shareholders would hold a 58.75 percent stake in the
new entity, with SmithKline shareholders holding a 41.25 stake.
</P>
<P>
	   Each Glaxo share would be exchanged for one share in the new company, while
each SmithKline share would be worth 0.4552 shares in the combined group.
</P>
<P>
	   The new company would have its corporate headquarters in London, and its new
operational base in the United States, probably in or near New York City.
</P>
<P>
	   The deal demonstrates the pressure facing even the biggest names in the
pharmaceutical industry to consolidate with rivals as a way to afford the rising
costs of developing and selling new medicines. It is also likely to trigger a
new round of takeovers and mergers throughout the industry.
</P>
<P>
	   "To succeed in this industry, you must be top-tier, and preferably, you must
have market leadership," Glaxo Wellcome chairman Sir Richard Sykes said.
</P>
<P>
	   Only last week, Pfizer Inc. emerged as the likely winner in the battle for
U.S. drugmaker Warner-Lambert Co. Bowing to pressure from its investors,
Warner-Lambert management said it would negotiate a buyout by Pfizer, backing
away from a previously announced merger deal with American Home Products Corp.
</P>
<P>
	   If the deal with Pfizer goes forward, the combined U.S. group would have an
estimated 6.7 percent of the global pharmaceutical market.
</P>
<P>
	   Glaxo Wellcome and SmithKline Beecham have long pondered a merger, but the
apparent success of Pfizer's hostile bid for Warner-Lambert gave new impetus to
the merger, said Kevin Wilson, an industry analyst at Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
	   But he said creating operational synergies and a bigger sales force are the
main reasons that the two sides decided to strike a deal now.
</P>
<P>
	   "It will clearly be a challenge to achieve the integration, but the
potential of the organization three to five years out is intriguing."
</P>
<P>
	   Talks between Glaxo and SmithKline were only announced on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   Some analysts have said the British firms were able to start a new round of
merger talks following the announcement in December that Leschly planned to
resign by April. Leschly's reported inability to agree with Sykes was seen as
one of the reasons earlier negotiations were suspended.
</P>
<P>
	   "It had nothing to do with my retirement," Leschly insisted.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the merger, to become effective this summer, Sykes would serve the new
company as non-executive chairman, and Leschly's deputy at Glaxo, Jean-Pierre
Garnier, would become its chief executive.
</P>
<P>
	   The board of Glaxo SmithKline would consist of 14 directors drawn equally
from the boards of Glaxo and SmithKline.
</P>
<P>
	   Glaxo's strength lies in its top anti-migraine drug, Imitrex, and in
treatments for asthma and viral infections, including HIV.
</P>
<P>
	   SmithKline's top products include the antibiotic Augmentin, the
anti-depressant Paxil and a new diabetes drug, Avandia. It also has a strong
vaccines business.
</P>
<P>
	   Shares in both companies were trading lower in afternoon trading. Glaxo
Wellcome shares were down 4 percent from Friday's close. SmithKline Beecham
shares were 8 percent lower.
</P>
<P>
	   Worldwide pharmaceutical sales of the combined company would total an
estimated $15 billion, based on 1998 annual figures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 1144 </TRAILER>
