<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 12:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Petrochemical Restructuring  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Thailand's largest corporate debtor, Thai
Petrochemical Industries PCL, agreed with creditors Monday to enter bankruptcy
court proceedings, a deal that could help break the logjam of problem bank loans
hobbling Thailand's economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
	   Thai Petrochemical had waged a two-year battle with creditors over
restructuring its $3.5 billion debt, representing close to 5 percent of the dud
loans held by Thai banks in the wake of the Asian economic crisis that struck in
mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
	   The company's decision to give up its fight signals a victory for Thailand's
new bankruptcy laws, which give creditors increased clout and are seen as vital
toward whittling down a mountain of dud loans amounting to nearly half of all
lending.
</P>
<P>
	   TPI had become notorious in Thai corporate circles for resisting debt
restructuring, seeking a better deal by trying to divide and delay action by its
148 creditors, mostly domestic banks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
