<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 12:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Winners Picked in Kid Book Awards  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- A story about a boy who runs away from a foster home to
search for his father took top honors in children's literature Monday from the
American Library Association.
</P>
<P>
	   "Bud, Not Buddy" by Christopher Paul Curtis won the association's 2000 John
Newbery Medal.
</P>
<P>
	   Simms Taback, illustrator of "Joseph Had a Little Overcoat," won the
Randolph Caldecott Medal for most distinguished picture book, the association's
other top honor.
</P>
<P>
	   Illustrated in watercolor, gouache, pencil, ink and collage, "Joseph Had a
Little Overcoat" is based on a Yiddish folktale of a resourceful tailor who
transforms his old overcoat into smaller garments.
</P>
<P>
	   "Bud, Not Buddy" tells the story of a 10-year-old boy who searches for his
father using clues left by his dead mother that point to a legendary jazz
bandleader. The novel explores questions about racism, belonging, love and hope,
said Carolyn S. Brodie, chair of the Newbery Award Selection Committee.
</P>
<P>
	   Curtis also is the recipient of the Coretta Scott King Author Award
recognizing excellence by black authors. Brian Pinkney, illustrator for "In the
Time of the Drums," received the King Illustrator Award.
</P>
<P>
	   In other honors announced at the ALA's midwinter meeting:
</P>
<P>
	   --Chris Crutcher was named the 2000 recipient of the Margaret A. Edwards
Award honoring lifetime contribution in writing for teens. Crutcher writes
novels revolving around school, sports, friends and family.
</P>
<P>
	   --Walter Dean Myers, author of "Monster," was named the first winner of the
Michael L. Printz Award for excellence in literature for young adults. Prinz was
a Topeka, Kan., school librarian known for promoting quality books for young
adults.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
