<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rowland campaign benefited from treasurer contacts  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Gov. John G. Rowland's 1998 re-election campaign
received $145,000 from some of the key figures in fee scandal involving the
state treasurer's office, the Journal Inquirer reported Monday.
<P>
	   The campaign collected the money in contributions from people who did
official business with former state Treasurer Paul J. Silvester, according to
government records obtained by the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
	   The records also show more than half of the Silvester-related donations came
from key figures in the scandal over so-called finder's fees. Those were fees
that investment firms paid to Silvester's associates for helping to arrange
state pension-fund deals.
</P>
<P>
	   Silvester, who was defeated in his own election bid in 1998, is awaiting
sentencing after pleading guilty last fall to federal racketeering and
money-laundering charges. He admitted that some of those fees were kicked back
to him, or his campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   The governor's spokesman, Dean Pagani, acknowledged that there were
considerably more contributions from Silvester's associates and business
partners than previously reported.
</P>
<P>
	   But Pagani denied there was anything untoward about the governor having
accepted the contributions.
</P>
<P>
	   "You have to keep in mind that we're looking at this in hindsight, and that
at the time there was absolutely no evidence that Paul Silvester was doing
anything wrong or illegal," Pagani said.
</P>
<P>
	   "There is no indication that the governor, his campaign staff, or anyone
from the administration had done anything that breaks either the letter or the
spirit of the election laws," Pagani added.
</P>
<P>
	   Among those making contributions were Washington lobbyist Wayne L. Berman,
whose consulting firm hired the former treasurer and his campaign manager after
Berman got $1.5 million in finder's fees. Also, Darien lawyer Christopher A.
Stack, who has admitted kicking back to Silvester proceeds from finder's fees he
received.
</P>
<P>
	   Besides Berman and Stack, the governor's contributors include seven other
recipients of sizable finder's fees, more than 30 people connected to about ten
companies in which the treasurer invested hundreds of millions of dollars, and
dozens of people employed by the select banks in which Silvester deposited $100
million in state cash.
</P>
<P>
	   Rowland also accepted an additional $117,000 in campaign contributions from
more than 100 individuals whom his reports variously identify as private
investors, money managers, brokers, and other investment professionals.
</P>
<P>
	   However, the records don't provide enough information to determine whether
any of those contributors also had business relationships with the state
treasury under Silvester.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-17-00 1257 </TRAILER>
