<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 13:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ainsley Harriott Dishes Up New Show  </HEADLINE>
    By FRAZIER MOORE AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Ainsley Harriott's new cooking show may be the tastiest
item on the daytime TV menu.
</P>
<P>
	   Celebrity talk, musical guests, audience participation -- even a house band
-- are among the ingredients. Plus, the expected recipes and kitchen tips.
</P>
<P>
	   "But it's how you jazz it up, isn't it?" Harriott says. "You take a little
bit of this, a little bit of that and stir it up, and it's fantastic!
</P>
<P>
	   "That's what it's all about."
</P>
<P>
	   He happens to be talking about food, not TV. But on the syndicated "Ainsley
Harriott Show," which airs live every weekday at 9 a.m. EST (check local
listings), its expansive host is jazzing up the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
	   A strapping, rubber-faced bloke you could eat with a spoon, Harriott has
long been a familiar TV presence in his native England. But as of last week, he
is out to conquer the New World.
</P>
<P>
	   He has brought with him to his Chelsea Piers studio a broad grin, a hearty
laugh and a bald pate as smooth as his Corian countertops. ("No hair is gonna
fall in the food," he vows with a chuckle.)
</P>
<P>
	   His focus on the show is "simple, nice, easy food -- food that's attractive
and quick to prepare."
</P>
<P>
	   Preparing it, Harriott is effusive. Passionate. Charming. Clownish. (Why NOT
a little ham on the bill of fare?)
</P>
<P>
	   "I need someone to cook with me!" he trumpeted on Wednesday's show. "I need
someone from the audience!"
</P>
<P>
	   A woman named Richarda joined him on the set in his gourmet kitchen. Before
the hour was done, she had helped him whip up a Tropical Fruit Brulee.
</P>
<P>
	   In the meantime, he had brought on his celebrity guest, "Inside Edition"
anchor Deborah Norville, and, after tea and a chat, they set about preparing a
nutritious dish her kids would like: Turkey Tacos.
</P>
<P>
	   Singer Kevon Edmonds did a number.
</P>
<P>
	   And "Produce Pete" Napolitano disclosed a use for the papaya seeds you'd
otherwise discard: After oven-drying them, pour them in a pepper mill for duty
as a meat tenderizer.
</P>
<P>
	   On Thursday's show, Harriott welcomed an ice sculptor and the former Sarah
Ferguson, Duchess of York, who confessed, "I can't cook."
</P>
<P>
	   "Ohhhh, you can," insisted Harriott. "Everybody's got the ability to cook.
They just have to be shown."
</P>
<P>
	   Then, as if to prove it, a pre-taped remote showed him raiding the cupboard
and fridge of an "Ainsley Ambush" volunteer named Don, who played sous-chef as
Harriott improvised Tortilla Tuna Triangles. Don was last seen sitting down to
this impromptu, candlelit dinner with wife Dolores, as Harriott slipped away.
</P>
<P>
	   It was as bright as a David Letterman bit -- and oddly inspiring.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm not saying to people, 'You've got to cook this,"' Harriott explains. "I
just want to give them ideas. Then, when they try something and it works, they
go on to the next thing.
</P>
<P>
	   "Besides, there's going to be a very high percentage of viewers who don't
cook. But they might be inspired to order something new at a restaurant: 'I saw
Ainsley Harriott cook that the other day. I want to have a try!"'
</P>
<P>
	   As further incentive, Harriott has established a Web site as a useful
supplement to his show. Not only are all TV-demonstrated recipes available, but
an "Ask Ainsley" feature invites "questions, suggestions, tips, cooking traumas,
whatever." (On one show, Harriott tackled this problem from a viewer: How do you
keep your gravy free of lumps?)
</P>
<P>
	   The 42-year-old Harriott, a best-selling author of cookbooks and a former
chef at several top London restaurants, began cooking as a child under the
tutelage of his mother.
</P>
<P>
	   "I grew up not being intimidated by the kitchen," he says, "because she gave
me the skill to express myself. And I just went on from there.
</P>
<P>
	   "I was quite shy," he recalls, for the first time straining credibility. "I
found my way, I suppose, with food. It's a confidence builder. How else in life
do you get that opportunity for someone to say to you, 'Wow, that's really
great'? You put food in front of someone and, 'Ahhh, I really enjoyed that!'
It's a lift."
</P>
<P>
	   Similarly, the show Harriott puts in front of viewers is a lift -- fun and
informative.
</P>
<P>
	   Moreover, he demonstrates refreshingly that food unites us all. Whether it's
a star or a civilian in the kitchen with Harriott, food becomes the great
equalizer. Everyone has something to offer when cooking. And something to learn.
</P>
<P>
	   "The kitchen is the place you feel relaxed," says Harriott.
</P>
<P>
	   Even watching it on TV.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Elsewhere in television ...
</P>
<P>
	   'FORGIVE OR FORGET': Who knows if Mother Love can forgive or forget getting
dumped from this show? No matter. Actress Robin Givens ("Head of the Class," the
feature "A Rage in Harlem") premieres today as the new host of this syndicated
talk-relationship series. In its second season, "Forgive or Forget" invites
guests to appeal for forgiveness from someone whom they have wronged. That
person listens backstage, and if willing to forgive, he or she will be found
standing on the other side of an onstage door. Otherwise ... forget it!
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Frazier Moore can be reached at fmoore "at" ap.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 1300 </TRAILER>
