<DOCNO> APW20000117.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mannesmann Shuffles Management  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    DUESSELDORF, Germany (AP) -- The embattled telecommunications company
Mannesmann AG shuffled its top management today, an expected change made in
preparation of the spinoff of its engineering and automotive unit.
</P>
<P>
	   Albert Weismuller will become chief financial officer, taking over from
Joachim Rauhut, who will head Mannesmann Engineering and Automotive, a division
that is to be split off from the company's telecom operations.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was no surprise that Weismuller will become CFO because he was the right
hand of chief executive Klaus Esser," said Hermann Reith, an analyst with BHF
Bank in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
	   Reith said the personnel changes are unrelated to the hostile, $137 billion
takeover bid by British rival Vodafone AirTouch PLC.
</P>
<P>
	   Weismuller and Kurt Kinzius will become members of the Mannesmann executive
board on Feb. 15 with Kinzius heading mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition, the company set up a new group management board in charge of
overseeing Mannesmann's recent acquisitions, such as the British
telecommunications company Orange PLC.
</P>
<P>
	   By midday Monday, Mannesmann shares were up 6.4 percent in Frankfurt trading
at $278 a share. Vodafone has offered stock worth about $265 a share for each
Mannesman share.
</P>
<P>
	   Some traders felt the Vodafone bid might be successful, after a weekend of
analyzing Mannesmann's defense documents, which were released Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   Critics of the papers said Mannesmann offered no new arguments for going
alone.
</P>
<P>
	   Mannesmann released its official defense documents Friday in an attempt to
persuade shareholders to reject the bid from Vodafone, the world's No. 1 mobile
phone company. Mannesmann shareholders have until Feb. 7 to reply to the offer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
