<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki has huge lead over possible rival in 2002  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Gov. George Pataki has a huge lead over a possible
Democratic challenger in the 2002 governor's race when it comes to raising money
for the campaign, reports showed Monday.
<P>
	   The reports, prepared for filing with the state Board of Elections, showed
the Republican governor had raised more than $824,000 over the past six months
and had $2.32 million on hand as of Jan. 11.
</P>
<P>
	   "Clearly, this is an indication that the governor is seriously considering a
run for a third term," Zenia Mucha, a spokeswoman for Pataki and his 1998
campaign manager, said.
</P>
<P>
	   In fact, at this point four years ago, Pataki's state campaign committee
reported $1.35 million in the bank. Even so, the governor's committee back then
had raised about $760,000 over the previous six months - almost the same
fund-raising pace as over the last six months of 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, a report prepared by state Comptroller H. Carl McCall, a
Democrat, showed he had just $72,711.83 in his state campaign account as of the
middle of this month, having raised $22,250 over the past six months.
</P>
<P>
	   "We took '99 off (from fund raising) and now we're gearing up and planning
to go full-steam ahead," Shawn Thompson, executive director of the Friends of
McCall campaign committee, said.
</P>
<P>
	   Thompson, a fund-raising specialist, was recently hired by McCall to help
raise the money needed if the comptroller decides to go ahead with a run for
governor in two years.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to McCall, the Democratic nomination for governor has drawn the
interest of federal Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo, the eldest son of former New
York Gov. Mario Cuomo who was driven out of office by Pataki. The younger Cuomo
has yet to form a state campaign committee and has not begun raising money for a
possible gubernatorial campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   Neither McCall nor Cuomo has yet announced plans to run for governor. Mucha
said any announcement from Pataki is a long way off.
</P>
<P>
	   Nonetheless, Mucha said the Pataki camp was "very pleased with the results
and we intend to continue to raise the funds that are necessary in order to
launch a third campaign should the governor make that decision."
</P>
<P>
	   In 1998, Pataki spent more than $20 million in easily defeating Democrat
Peter Vallone and Independence Party candidate B. Thomas Golisano to win a
second term.
</P>
<P>
	   While Pataki said during his 1994 campaign against Mario Cuomo that he would
serve only two four-year terms if elected, the New York Republican has since
said he is considering a run for a third term in 2002. At the time of their
race, Cuomo was seeking a fourth term and polling indicated many New Yorkers
felt the Democratic incumbent had simply stayed around too long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-17-00 1405 </TRAILER>
