<HEADLINE> Hyundai Founder To Visit N. Korea  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Chung Ju-yung, South Korea's richest man and head
of the Hyundai group, plans to visit North Korea in February to promote business
with the communist country, group officials said today.Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Chung hopes to meet leader Kim Jong Il and discuss several investment
projects, including a major industrial complex on North Korea's west coast, said
Kim Yun-kyu, a senior Hyundai official.
</P>
<P>
	   Hyundai plans to relocate hundreds of footwear and other small-scale,
labor-intensive South Korean plants to the industrial complex.
</P>
<P>
	   Hyundai also is pushing to invest in about a dozen handicraft and other
small businesses in Chung's hometown of Tongchun on North Korea's east coast.
</P>
<P>
	   It will be Chung's fourth visit to North Korea since the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
	   Chung and his family settled in South Korea before the Korean Peninsula was
divided into the communist North and the capitalist South in 1945. He founded
Hyundai in the early 1950s and has developed it into South Korea's largest
conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
	   In an unprecedented joint venture with North Korea, Hyundai launched a
cruise tour to a scenic North Korean mountain in late 1998. More than 160,000
South Koreans have visited the mountain on the tour.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
