<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jailed Market Guru Mighr Appeal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- An attorney for Martin A. Armstrong said today he is
considering filing an appeal to get the renowned market forecaster out of jail.
</P>
<P>
	   Armstrong was handcuffed and led out of court Friday for failing to comply
with an order to turn over gold bars, antiques and company records.
</P>
<P>
	   Judge Richard Owen told Armstrong he had the keys to his own cell, and would
be released as soon as he agreed to provide the missing items, which include
about $14 million in valuables and at least one computer.
</P>
<P>
	   Armstrong, founder of Princeton Economics International Ltd., has been
charged with defrauding Japanese investors out of almost $1 billion. He has
pleaded not guilty.
</P>
<P>
	   Armstrong, 50, did produce a half-dozen ancient marble busts, hundreds of
gold coins and four computers last week for a court-appointed receiver.
</P>
<P>
	   "His position is he produced a significant amount of material over the
course of the week, and he needed a bit more time," said Martin Unger, an
attorney with the law firm Tenzer Greenblatt, which is representing Armstrong.
He said he had not yet decided whether to appeal the judge's order to the 2nd
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to the missing items, however, Judge Owen was concerned that the
computers Armstrong handed over were damaged -- one was missing a hard drive --
and almost 600 files had been deleted just hours before the computers were
turned over to the receiver.
</P>
<P>
	   Unger said, "All the information that was on the computer was on another
computer, so it wasn't so much as tampering as he made a mistake."
</P>
<P>
	   Armstrong testified that he no longer has the other valuables the receiver
claims Armstrong purchased with company funds. Armstrong said several of the
missing items, including a $750,000 black basalt bust of Julius Caesar and a
collection of coins, were given to Australian businessman Nigel Kirwan in
exchange for a 50 percent interest in the Princeton Precious Metals &AMP; Capital
Fund.
</P>
<P>
	   Armstrong also testified that he gave $1 million in gold bars to Akira
Setogawa, chairman of Cresvale in Tokyo, a subsidiary of Princeton Economics.
Armstrong said the gold was payment for Setogawa's interest in Cresvale.
</P>
<P>
	   Setogawa was indicted last month in Japan for tax evasion and paying illegal
rebates to investors.
</P>
<P>
	   Armstrong, who is in the Metropolitan Correctional Center in Manhattan, can
be held in jail for up to 18 months for contempt of court in this case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
