<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Religious Violence Grows  </HEADLINE>
   By GEOFF SPENCER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Religious strife spread in eastern Indonesia on
Monday, where angry Muslims burned as many as a dozen churches.
</P>
<P>
	   In Jakarta, meanwhile, reformist Indonesian President Abdurrahman Wahid
downplayed rumors of an impending coup.
</P>
<P>
	   The churches were burned in the towns of Mataram and Ampenan on Lombok
island, 1,600 miles east of Jakarta, the national capital. Troops fired warning
shots at rock-throwing mobs on the island while Islamic protesters attacked the
Christian places of worship.
</P>
<P>
	   Eight people were hospitalized with gunshot wounds, officials said. Police
said eight churches were burned, while church officials set the number at 12.
</P>
<P>
	   Lombok lies just east of Bali, Indonesia's main tourist destination. Police
said Monday's violence flared well away from popular beach resorts.
</P>
<P>
	   The trouble erupted after thousands of protesters accused Wahid's
three-month-old government of doing little to quell more than a year of civil
war between Muslims and Christians in troubled Maluku province in Indonesia's
remote east.
</P>
<P>
	   The bloodshed, which has claimed more than 1,000 lives, has triggered an
outcry among Muslims, who make up more than 90 percent of Indonesia's 210
million people. Big protests in several cities recently have called for a
``jihad,'' or holy war, against the Christian minority.
</P>
<P>
	   The fighting in Maluku plus bloody rebel violence in Aceh in Indonesia's far
west also have generated discontent within the ranks of the military -- and
fueled coup rumors.
</P>
<P>
	   Wahid, a moderate Muslim leader, has infuriated some generals by refusing to
impose martial law in Maluku and Aceh. The military, used to using its might to
crush troublemakers during three decades of authoritarian rule under
ex-President Suharto, is also angry at attempts to prosecute some top commanders
for human rights abuses in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
	   Many say Wahid, who has promised democratic reforms, is slowly whittling
away at the military's once unchecked power. Last week, he fired the military's
top spokesman after he publicly criticized Wahid.
</P>
<P>
	   On Friday, U.S. Ambassador to the United Nations Richard Holbrooke added
credence to coup fears by warning the military not to try to move against
Wahid's democratically elected government. Wahid made light of the rumors
Monday, but vowed to quash any plot against him.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't think there will be a coup, that is one thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Military chief Adm. Widodo Adisutjipto also denied the speculation.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Who's going to launch a coup? You must have to learn from history that
Indonesia's military has never launch a coup,'' the official Antara news agency
quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
	   In an apparent attempt to placate the generals, Foreign Minister Alwi Shihab
left Monday for the United Nations, where he will try to block efforts to
establish an international East Timor war crimes tribunal.
</P>
<P>
	   Investigators accuse the military of permitting the frenzy of violence that
swept East Timor in September after the territory voted to secede from
Indonesia. Wahid says Indonesia's legal system must handle the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 1503 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
