<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 3:10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monday, Jan. 17, 2000
</P>
<P>
	   Mannesmann Shuffles Management
</P>
<P>
	   DUESSELDORF, Germany (AP) -- The embattled telecommunications
company Mannesmann AG shuffled its top management today, an
expected change in preparation of the spinoff of its engineering
and automotive unit. Albert Weismuller will become chief financial
officer, taking over from Joachim Rauhut, who will head Mannesmann
Engineering and Automotive, a division that is to be split off from
the company's telecom operations. Hermann Reith, an analyst with
BHF Bank in Frankfurt, said the personnel changes are unrelated to
the hostile, $137 billion takeover bid by British rival Vodafone
AirTouch PLC. Mannesmann has also set up a new group management
board in charge of overseeing Mannesmann's recent acquisitions,
such as the British telecommunications company Orange PLC.
Mannesmann shares were up 6.4 percent in Frankfurt trading at $278
a share today.
</P>
<P>
	   Glaxo Wellcome Buying SmithKline Beecham
</P>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- British pharmaceutical company Glaxo Wellcome PLC
plans to buy rival SmithKline Beecham PLC for about $76 billion in
stock, creating the world's largest drugmaker. The combination
announced today would form a company to be called Glaxo SmithKline
that would hold a 7.3 percent share of the global pharmaceutical
market. The deal demonstrates the pressure facing even the biggest
names in the pharmaceutical industry to consolidate with rivals as
a way to afford the rising costs of developing and selling new
medicines. It is also likely to trigger a new round of takeovers
and mergers throughout the industry. Under the deal, Glaxo
shareholders would hold a 58.75 percent stake in the new entity,
with SmithKline shareholders holding a 41.25 stake.
</P>
<P>
	   German Software Firm Woos Top Staff
</P>
<P>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Europe's largest software company,
Germany's SAP AG, is asking shareholders to vote at a special
meeting tomorrow on a stock plan that gives management the option
to buy company shares at a set price in the future, a rare move for
a German company its size. The proposal, disparaged by critics as
``plain vanilla'' for its relative simplicity, is aimed at stemming
a flow of nearly 50 top level employees who have left its
U.S.-based unit over the last year for competitors with more
generous stock offerings. But it also bucks a growing trend in
Germany that ties employee incentives and bonuses more closely to
actual stock performance and stays away from stock options.
</P>
<P>
	   Secret Processor To Be Unveiled
</P>
<P>
	   SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) -- A top-secret computer chip designed
and funded by a powerful group of high-tech leaders is slated to
roll out this Wednesday amid a flurry of high expectations -- and
intrigue. For the past five years, Transmeta Corp. has secretly
toiled away on the project for the past five years. CEO David
Ditzel, a former chip designer for AT&AMP;T's Bell Labs and Sun
Microsystems Inc. Employees of Transmeta include superstar
designers like Linux creator Linus Torvalds. Investors include
industry barons like Microsoft Corp. co-founder Paul Allen and
billionaire financier George Soros.
</P>
<P>
	   'Fair Trade' Bananas Reach Britain
</P>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- Bananas stamped ``people-friendly'' hit British
supermarket shelves today as part of an initiative to support
independent producers and their workers, instead of multinational
corporations. The Fairtrade Foundation stamp on the fruit, imported
from independent Costa Rican farmers, is designed to tell shoppers
that the workers who produced the bananas receive a fair wage and
work in satisfactory conditions.
</P>
<P>
	   ENI Buys Stake in Portuguese Firm
</P>
<P>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) -- Italian energy giant ENI is paying $973
million for a 33.34 percent stake in Portuguese energy conglomerate
GALP SGPS, establishing a partnership to pursue joint investments
in Europe, Africa and Brazil. The Spanish utility Iberdrola is also
buying a 4 percent stake in GALP SPGS for $116.8 million, and the
Portuguese utility company Electricidade de Portugal bought another
11 percent of the company to lift its shareholding to 14.27
percent. The negotiated sale of stakes by the Portuguese state and
private investors disclosed today is part of a major restructuring
of GALP SPGS aimed at giving it the financial muscle and expertise
to expand in oil, gas and electricity sectors abroad.
</P>
<P>
	   Renault To Inspect Samsung Motors
</P>
<P>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- A four-member survey team from French
carmaker Renault SA arrived in Seoul today to look over South
Korea's troubled Samsung Motors Inc. The inspection is part of
Renault's move to take over Samsung. They have been in takeover
talks since December. The Renault team will survey and inspect
Samsung's overall operations, including its technology and
financial condition, Samsung officials said. Renault officials said
that the takeover would give them privileged access to the Korean
market and a larger base in Asia.
</P>
<P>
	   Thai Petrochemical To Restructure
</P>
<P>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Thailand's largest corporate debtor,
Thai Petrochemical Industries PCL, agreed with creditors today to
enter bankruptcy court proceedings, a deal that could help break
the logjam of problem bank loans hobbling Thailand's economic
recovery. Thai Petrochemical had waged a two-year battle with
creditors over restructuring its $3.5 billion debt. The debt
represents almost 5 percent of the dud loans held by Thai banks in
the wake of the Asian economic crisis that struck in mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
	   Unemployment Falls in Hong Kong
</P>
<P>
	   HONG KONG (AP) -- Unemployment dropped slightly to 6.0 percent in
the last three months of 1999 as a result of increased demand for
labor and steadily improving business conditions, the Census and
Statistics Department said today. The unemployment rate for the
three months ended Dec. 31 was down from 6.1 percent in the three
months ending Nov. 30, the agency said. The economy is coming out
of a bruising 15-month recession, expanding 4.5 percent in the
third quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
