<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Volunteers on King Holiday  </HEADLINE>
   By REBECCA SINDERBRAND Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton spent a few hours of his Martin Luther
King Jr. holiday volunteering at a Southeast Washington Boys and Girls Club and
said he hoped people would begin to view the day as ``a day on, not a day off.''
</P>
<P>
	   The president put a dark stain on wooden shelves in a third-floor computer
lab with a group of young volunteers. He later thanked them for keeping him from
``messing up too bad.''
</P>
<P>
	   The president may have revealed one reason he used Monday's event to brush
up on home-improvement skills with his comment that he has a ``lot of work to
do'' on his new Chappaqua, N.Y., house. He said he managed already to get a lot
of work done in the few days he spent there.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's a great house, and we're making progress,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The president traveled a couple of miles from the White House to the club,
which serves low-income children, to mark the holiday named for the slain civil
rights leader.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's a source of immense pride and joy to me every time I see people
reaching across the lines that divide them to do things that lift us all up,''
Clinton said. ``This holiday embodies that. All these children embody that.''
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton also praised ``hundreds of thousands'' of AmeriCorps volunteers, who
he said were spending the King holiday on the job in a variety of volunteer
projects. The Clinton administration founded the national service program five
years ago and points to it as an example of volunteer initiative.
</P>
<P>
	   ``My son Simon is very excited the president's here,'' said volunteer
Cynthia Jones. ``Heck, I'm excited.'' She said she hoped the president's
presence brought more attention to the holiday as a day to volunteer, rather
than just another day off from work.
</P>
<P>
	   Asked by reporters about his long-delayed book on race relations, Clinton
said the project is running a little behind because of time spent working on the
Middle East peace talks.
</P>
<P>
	   ``You know, I'm not going to put it out until I have lots of time to spend
personally on it,'' Clinton said. ``I don't want it to be something somebody
else did that my name is on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
