<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl's Party Sets Emergency Session  </HEADLINE>
   By TONY CZUCZKA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BERLIN (AP) -- Germany's Christian Democrats scheduled an emergency
leadership meeting Monday as calls grew louder for party leaders to resign over
a spreading campaign finance scandal.
</P>
<P>
	   Party leader Wolfgang Schaeuble, himself facing suspicions for accepting the
equivalent of $52,000 from a businessman, set the national party executive
meeting for Tuesday, six days ahead of its next regular session.
</P>
<P>
	   The leaders will be trying to deal with a scandal that was touched off last
month by revelations that former chancellor Helmut Kohl accepted up to $1
million in unreported campaign funds in the 1990s, when the conservative
Christian Democrats led Germany's government.
</P>
<P>
	   The scandal grew last week in Hesse state, where former party officials
admitted funneling millions to party coffers from a Swiss account and falsely
reporting the money as bequests. Those irregularities implicated yet another
senior party figure -- former Hesse party chairman Manfred Kanther, once a tough
law-and-order advocate as Kohl's interior minister.
</P>
<P>
	   Over the weekend, Germany's justice minister urged the entire conservative
leadership to step down. Leaders of the Christian Democrats' post-Kohl
generation pressed for resignations themselves on Monday, and Hesse state Gov.
Roland Koch suggested that Kanther give up his seat in the federal parliament.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We will have to part ways with all those entangled in this affair,''
Christian Wulff, a deputy national party chairman, told North German Radio. ``I
certainly don't exclude expulsions of party members.''
</P>
<P>
	   Schaeuble, Kohl's hand-picked successor in 1998, has been undermined by the
ever-growing revelations of apparent breaches of Germany's party financing law.
Hecklers at a weekend party rally urged Schaeuble to resign and scorned his
efforts to clear up the scandal, which is overshadowing the Christian Democrats'
campaign for Feb. 27 elections in the northern state of Schleswig-Holstein.
</P>
<P>
	   Hesse prosecutors opened a fraud probe Monday against a former party
treasurer and a party tax adviser, widening the range of formal suspects in the
scandal beyond Kohl.
</P>
<P>
	   The probe will seek to determine whether fraud or breach of trust charges
are warranted against tax adviser Horst Weyrauch and the former Hesse party
treasurer, Prince Casimir Sayn-Wittgenstein, prosecutors said. They said they
acted on Kanther's disclosure that $6.8 million flowed to the state's Christian
Democrats from abroad between 1989 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors in Bonn opened a similar probe against Kohl last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 1522 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000117.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CIA Helps State Dept. on Security  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Central Intelligence Agency is helping the State
Department safeguard its secrets and to improve security in general, a CIA
spokesman said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Congress has set a Jan. 31 deadline for the State Department to come up with
a plan to improve security. It threatened to stop financing the department's
Bureau of Intelligence and Research if a plan is not produced.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We are working with State to help assure that classified information is
protected,'' said CIA spokesman Bill Harlow. He said the agency is working to
help State meet the deadline.
</P>
<P>
	   An internal audit by the State Department's inspector general cited lax
procedures in handling classified materials and said the agency was not in
compliance with CIA directives that govern the handling of sensitive material,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   The audit was conducted last September, well before the FBI accused a
Russian diplomat in December of spying. The Russian, told to leave the country,
was listening in his car to transmissions from a bug planted in a State
Department conference room on the same floor as Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright's office.
</P>
<P>
	   Although the audit has not been released publicly, parts of it have been
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
	   Previously, officials familiar with the audit said it criticized the State
Department for letting visitors, contractors and maintenance workers roam its
building unescorted. While visitors were screened on entry, they were not
routinely escorted to the offices in which they claimed to have appointments,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
	   Another portion of the internal audit, reported Monday by The Washington
Post, found that 140 offices where highly classified documents were handled had
never been swept for listening devices.
</P>
<P>
	   Furthermore, the newspaper reported, 239 of 1,890 highly classified reports
from the Cryptological Support Group of the National Security Agency had not
been returned to the group's secure facility inside the State Department between
August and October 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   In one case, a pouch was returned empty. Another was returned open with a
key in it, the report said.
</P>
<P>
	   Congress demanded the security improvements after a man strolled into a room
six doors down from Albright's office in 1998, helped himself to classified
briefing materials and walked out. He was never identified, and the documents
were never recovered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 1523 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000117.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Glaxo Wellcome buyout of SmithKline Beecham speeds drug industry's  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   LONDON (AP) - Glaxo Wellcome's planned acquisition of rival drugmaker
SmithKline Beecham would do more than create the world's largest pharmaceutical
company.
<P>
	   The deal, announced Monday and worth about $76 billion in stock, is a clear
sign that the merger trend now reshaping other industries is accelerating in the
still-fragmented drug business.
</P>
<P>
	   Just last week, Pfizer emerged as the likely winner in a battle with
American Home Products for drugmaker Warner-Lambert, while Monsanto is in the
process of merging with Pharmacia and Upjohn. Industry analysts predict other
blue-chip names, including Eli Lilly, Schering Plough, Novartis, Bristol-Myers
Squibb and even merger-averse Merck, won't be far behind.
</P>
<P>
	   It's a trend that could have a significant impact on New Jersey's economy.
American Home Products, Warner-Lambert, Pharmacia and Upjohn, Merck and Schering
Plough all are headquartered here. Bristol-Myers Squibb has its research
headquarters in Princeton, and Novartis, a Swiss company, has its U.S.
headquarters in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think that eventually about six to 10 companies will own the
pharmaceutical market," said Hemant Shah, an independent industry analyst based
in Warren, N.J.
</P>
<P>
	   That's a far cry from the mosaic of firms currently vying for a few cents of
each dollar consumers spend on medicines.
</P>
<P>
	   Compared to other industries, the pharmaceutical business still has many
competitors. Indeed, the combined Glaxo and SmithKline would control just 7.3
percent of global sales, although individual companies dominate treatments for
several specific conditions such as allergies and high cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts say that consolidations are gathering momentum because drugmakers
are pinched between the ballooning costs of developing new drugs and the demands
of investors and shareholders that they deliver double-digit growth in profits.
</P>
<P>
	   Only by bulking up to pool research and development funds and by slashing
costs can pharmaceutical firms avoid financial peril in an ever more Darwinian
market.
</P>
<P>
	   "To succeed in this industry, you must be top-tier, and preferably, you must
have market leadership," Glaxo Wellcome chairman Sir Richard Sykes told a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
	   Glaxo Wellcome and SmithKline Beecham said their union would yield $1.6
billion in annual savings after three years. They said job cuts were expected,
but that they were still deciding where to make them.
</P>
<P>
	   The two British-based companies plan to keep their corporate headquarters in
London, but open a new operational headquarters in or near New York.
</P>
<P>
	   They would keep their U.S. businesses separate. SmithKline has a research
and development unit based in Philadelphia and a non-prescription drug business
in Pittsburgh. Glaxo's American operations are headquartered in Research
Triangle Park, N.C.
</P>
<P>
	   Their union comes two years after previous merger talks collapsed in a fight
over which executives would run the company
</P>
<P>
	   The apparent success of Pfizer's hostile bid for Morris Plains-based
Warner-Lambert gave new impetus to the idea, said Kevin Wilson, an industry
analyst at Salomon Smith Barney in London.
</P>
<P>
	   "Pfizer-Warner-Lambert has acted as a catalyst," he said. "I could easily
imagine them saying, 'Look, this is a good idea. We might as well get on with it
now.' "
</P>
<P>
	   Glaxo SmithKline would have worldwide pharmaceutical sales of an estimated
$15 billion, based on 1998 annual figures. But a combined Pfizer-Warner-Lambert
would be close behind with a 6.7 percent market share, and it would be gaining
fast, Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
	   Madison-based American Home Products - the apparent loser in the fight for
Warner-Lambert - has failed three times to combine with other drug companies and
looks like an increasingly attractive takeover target for a European company
such as Bayer that might be aiming to expand its U.S. pharmaceuticals business,
said Andy Penman, an analyst at London brokerage Greig Middleton.
</P>
<P>
	   Even Merck, which has publicly sworn off mergers in the past, might have its
hand forced if it wants to keep up with more financially powerful rivals. Merck
is headquartered in Whitehouse Station.
</P>
<P>
	   "There's no question that Merck is the best in the business in terms of
developing new drugs, but it's going to be very difficult to compete when there
are companies with R and D budgets that are twice that of Merck," said Shah, the
New Jersey-based analyst.
</P>
<P>
	   Glaxo's strength lies in its top anti-migraine drug, Imitrex, and in
treatments for asthma and viral infections, including HIV.
</P>
<P>
	   SmithKline's top products include the antibiotic Augmentin, the
antidepressant Paxil and a new diabetes drug, Avandia. It also has a strong
vaccines business.
</P>
<P>
	   But both firms are feeling pressure because their top drugs are facing
expiration of their patents, allowing cheaper generics into the market.
</P>
<P>
	   Glaxo's leading ulcer drug Zantac lost its patent protection in 1997, and
SmithKline's lucrative Augmentin will lose its patent in 2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-17-00 1523 </TRAILER>
