<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Marches, church services mark observances of slain civil rights  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) - About 250 people braved bitter cold Monday
for an abbreviated parade and a church service honoring the Rev. Dr. Martin
Luther King Jr. - one of many observances across New Jersey marking the birthday
of the slain civil rights leader.
<P>
	   The route for the annual parade was shortened in deference to the cold - a
temperature of 16 degrees and a wind chill factor of 17 below zero, according to
the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
	   The march attracted fewer people than usual, as did a service afterward at
St. James AME Church.
</P>
<P>
	   "It cut back on the numbers, but the spirit was just as high," said William
Marsh, president of the Atlantic City chapter of the NAACP, which sponsored the
event. "We marched like it was 90 degrees."
</P>
<P>
	   King, 39, was shot to death April 4, 1968, in Memphis, Tenn. His birthday -
Jan. 15 - became a national holiday in 1986.
</P>
<P>
	   The Atlantic City parade began, fittingly, at the Rev. Martin Luther King
Jr. School. Marching from the school down a street also named for King,
bundled-up participants from the NAACP, the Atlantic City High School marching
band and the Stanley Holmes Village housing project put on brave faces for the
15-minute walk.
</P>
<P>
	   Organizers said the nasty weather was not unusual.
</P>
<P>
	   "We've been doing this for 26 years now, and in all that time we've had only
four nice days," said Pierre Hollingsworth, a former NAACP chapter president who
marched Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The biting cold prompted organizers to cut corners: Instead of marching to
Arctic Avenue and turning left to go to the church, the procession peeled off at
Bacharach Boulevard and made a bee-line to the church, where hot dogs and hot
chocolate awaited.
</P>
<P>
	   In previous years, the march included 400 people or more.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was good that we had the numbers we did, since it was so cold," said
Stephenie Dixon, chairwoman of the event.
</P>
<P>
	   During the church service, a half-dozen clergymen and NAACP officials lauded
King's work but said much more still needs to be done.
</P>
<P>
	   "The dream has not been fulfilled," said the Rev. Milton Hendricks, pastor
of Faith Baptist Church in nearby Pleasantville. "We are still the last hired
and the first fired. Our cities and schools are in a deplorable condition.
Racism still rears its ugly head and brotherhood is still a dream deferred."
</P>
<P>
	   Elsewhere, the Concerned Citizens of Camden Association held a march and
rally in the morning, followed by a neighborhood cleanup in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
	   Community service was also the theme in Livingston, where the high school
was the focal point for a blood drive and collections of eyeglasses, household
items and clothing for needy families.
</P>
<P>
	   In Lawnside, school children competed in the fifth annual Rosie Lee Oates
Teen Speech Contest at Grace Temple Baptist Church. Teen-agers had to pick a
current event and deliver a three- to five-minute speech about it.
</P>
<P>
	   Col. Carson Dunbar, superintendent of the New Jersey State Police, was
scheduled as the keynote speaker at an evening service at St. Andrew's United
Methodist Church in Cherry Hill.
</P>
<P>
	   Dunbar was appointed in November to rebuild a department plagued by
race-related troubles.
</P>
<P>
	   "He's doing some things that Dr. King wanted to do for this country," said
Rabbi Lewis Eron, coordinator of the religious Leaders Coalition, one of the
sponsors of the event.
</P>
<P>
	   "It shows the struggle still continues," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-17-00 1552 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000117.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cold keeps MLK celebration inside but doesn't stop it  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The bitter -4 degree weather on Monday kept most of
New York's Martin Luther King Jr. celebrations inside, but hearts were still
warmed from the compelling speeches, inspirational choirs and motivational
orchestra music.
<P>
	   "Forget about the weather outside," Albany Mayor Jerry Jennings said during
the program in the Empire State Plaza Convention Center. "It's warm in here."
</P>
<P>
	   The frigidly-cold weather in Albany - the wind chill factor at noon was -45
degrees - forced planners to cancel a march to the Martin Luther King Monument
at Albany's Lincoln Park.
</P>
<P>
	   But no one seemed to mind after inspirational songs by the Empire State King
Interdenominational Mass Choir and the Empire State Youth Orchestra, as well as
an impassioned lecture from the Rev. Calvin Butts III, pastor of the Abyssinian
Baptist Church in New York City.
</P>
<P>
	   Butts, who also is the president of the State University of New York at Old
Westbury, praised King, saying "the marching feet of his nonviolent army shook
the foundations of America."
</P>
<P>
	   "He was a prophet to the nation, saying that we will live together as
brothers and sisters or we will perish apart as fools," Butts said.
</P>
<P>
	   Lt. Gov. Mary Donohue, the highest-ranking state official at the program,
urged people to make every day a celebration of Martin Luther King's dream of
equality and civil rights. "The key is action now, today and every day," she
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Donohue also accepted on behalf of the state a small crystal Marin Luther
King Jr. monument donated by Steuben Glass and the New York Power Authority. The
monument will "remind us of the past and guide us to the future," Donohue said.
</P>
<P>
	   The monument will be placed in the Empire State Plaza later this year, she
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Not everyone was celebrating this day, however. Members of the Center For
Law &AMP; Justice protested outside the Empire State Convention Center during the
program, trying to call attention to the growing number of prisoners being
denied parole in the state.
</P>
<P>
	   Alice Green, the center's executive director, wants legislative hearings on
the state's prison systems. She says the prisons are steadily getting worse for
inmates and officials are denying inmates a chance at parole to keep a steady
low-paid work force for the state.
</P>
<P>
	   Protesters carried signs saying "Dr. King was a prisoner too," "Parole
justice" and "Prisoners have families too." and chanted "We are Family."
</P>
<P>
	   "If George Pataki is serious about Martin Luther King Day, then he would
listen to what these people have to say," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Green saw no conflict in holding protests on Martin Luther King Jr. Day,
saying peaceful protests - not acceptance of the status quo - are what Dr. King
espoused.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're not here to sing and dance for the white people," Green said. "That's
what they want us to do."
</P>
<P>
	   In Utica, a luncheon and awards ceremony were held along with an evening
march and memorial service at Hope Chapel African Methodist Episcopal Church.
</P>
<P>
	   Carolyn Bradley was on pins and needles in anticipation. "We were raised to
look for the good in people, not the bad," said Bradley, who met King after he
gave a speech in Kingstree, S.C., in the early 1960s. "We had a lot of love
instilled in us."
</P>
<P>
	   Growing up in the South, the 47-year-old Bradley can remember a time when
she wasn't able to play at white children's homes. But in her house, it was
different.
</P>
<P>
	   "We didn't have white friends, black friends," she said. "We had friends. I
tried to instill in my kids the same things."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
