<HEADLINE> EU Lifts Arms Embargo on Indonesia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Despite opposition from human rights campaigners,
the European Union on Monday lifted a 4-month-old arms embargo imposed on
Indonesia during the violence that followed East Timor's vote for independence.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The restrictive measures taken against the previous Indonesian government
... need not be renewed,'' the EU said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
	   The 15-nation bloc said it would continue to closely monitor weapons sales.
</P>
<P>
	   The ban was lifted despite objections from the human rights group Amnesty
International.
</P>
<P>
	   ``While East Timor is now secure, similar patterns of intimidation and
killing which shocked the world ... are being repeated in parts of Indonesia,''
the group said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
	   The arms embargo was introduced to pressure Jakarta into accepting
international peacekeepers in East Timor, where pro-Indonesia militias rampaged
after the province voted overwhelming for independence in an Aug. 30 referendum.
</P>
<P>
	   The EU banned all sales of arms, munitions, military equipment and other
goods ``which may be used for internal repression.'' It also suspended military
cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
