<HEADLINE> Cayugas turn to court for compensation in land claim  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -The negotiating is over. Now it is up to a federal
court jury to listen, and decide how much the Cayuga Indian Nation should be
awarded for its lost ancestral lands.
<P>
	   "There's always a chance of settling in any case. But I can't give you any
reason for great optimism," said Martin Gold, the Cayugas' attorney, as he
prepared for jury selection Tuesday and the start of the damages phase of the
tribe's 19-year-old land claim.
</P>
<P>
	   "The state is defending this case with an absolute scorched earth policy, as
if they have just been wonderful to the Cayugas and the other Indian nations
since the beginning of history," said Gold.
</P>
<P>
	   Nearly a year's worth of negotiations directed by a court-appointed mediator
have failed to resolve how much the state of New York owes for illegally taking
64,027 acres of Cayuga land two centuries ago. A 12-member jury will be seated
to complete that task. Lawyers have said testimony could take two to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   The Cayugas claimed in a 1980 lawsuit that the land was wrongfully acquired
by the state, which failed to obey a 1790 federal law requiring the federal
government to approve all land treaties. Based on a 1985 U.S. Supreme Court
ruling, U.S. District Judge Neal McCurn upheld the Cayugas' claim in 1994.
</P>
<P>
	   The Cayugas original claim sought the return of all their lost lands in
Cayuga and Seneca counties and $350 million. In June, the state reportedly
offered a settlement that included $110 million and 4,500 acres of private and
state land. McCurn has said no landowners will be unwillingly evicted from their
property.
</P>
<P>
	   Last week, the mediator floated a settlement proposal of $120 million but no
land. It was a move sharply criticized by the state and counties, who said they
did not authorize it. On Monday, state Sen. Michael F. Nozzolio wrote to McCurn
calling for the mediator's dismissal for making such an "irresponsible" offer.
</P>
<P>
	   During an eight-day pretrial hearing, the state's expert appraiser placed
the value of the Cayuga claim at $25 million to $40 million and the land's
rental value no more than $6 million. The highest land value was offered by the
federal government's appraiser, who said the land's current market value was
$264.7 million and its rental value $70.4 million.
</P>
<P>
	   The jury will not have to stay within the experts' monetary limits. And,
whatever amount it decides, is unlikely to end the land claim because one side
will almost surely appeal the ruling to the U.S. Second Circuit, and eventually
the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
	   The Mohawks, Oneidas and Senecas also have land claims pending and the
Onondaga Nation has said it would file its lawsuit after seeing how the Cayuga's
trial ends. All of the tribes are watching the Cayugas trial with interest
because it is the first to reach the damages stage and will have an impact on
their unsettled claims.
</P>
<P>
	   The Cayugas, who once spread out over 3 million acres of upstate New York,
are the only landless tribe among the five aboriginal tribes of the Iroquois
Confederacy. Currently, about 500 Cayugas live in western New York on and around
the Seneca's Cattaraugus reservation. Two other groups of Cayugas live in Canada
and Oklahoma.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-17-00 1602 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
