<HEADLINE> Japan Stocks Soar; Europe Shares Up  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose to a 29-month high in Tokyo today as Japan's
central bank left its monetary policy unchanged, a move that also boosted the
yen against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
	   European markets were modestly higher, with a new high reached by Germany's
main index, as investors debated the merits of a $76 billion merger in the
pharmaceutical industry.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. financial markets were closed today in observance of Martin Luther King
Jr. Day.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, a solid rally Friday on Wall Street that left the Dow Jones
industrial average at a record high helped lift stocks in overseas markets
today.
</P>
<P>
	   In Japan, the benchmark Nikkei Stock Average rose 480.68 points, or 2.54
percent, to close at 19,437.23 points. It was the Nikkei's highest close since
Aug. 8, 1997, when it ended the day at 19,604.46 points.
</P>
<P>
	   Traders said technology and brokerage stocks boosted the index. The Nikkei
also benefited from strength last week in the U.S. stock market.
</P>
<P>
	   "The Tokyo market was basically mirroring the movement in New York," said
Yuichi Kohashi, a strategist at Daiwa Securities.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar tumbled against the yen as Bank of Japan opted to leave interest
rates and monetary policy unchanged.
</P>
<P>
	   In recent weeks, the Bank of Japan has repeatedly intervened in the currency
market to buy dollars in order to stem the yen's rise. A strong yen means that
profits on Japanese products sold overseas are worth less when they are changed
into the Japanese currency.
</P>
<P>
	   In London trading, the dollar fell to 104.78 yen from 107.40 Friday. Most
European currencies slipped against the dollar, however. The euro fell to
$1.0090 from $1.0142 Friday and the British pound fell to $1.6308 from $1.6377.
</P>
<P>
	   In Europe, stocks closed higher despite some mixed reactions to the latest
round of corporate mergers. Shares of drug companies were mostly lower following
the announcement of the merger agreement between British drug companies Glaxo
Wellcome PLC and SmithKline Beecham PLC.
</P>
<P>
	   Glaxo's acquisition of SmithKline, which would create the world's largest
drugmaker, unites two companies that conducted unsuccessful merger talks two
years ago. Traders suggested that investors were disappointed because they had
hoped the deal would create greater cost savings than the $1.6 billion projected
by Glaxo and SmithKline.
</P>
<P>
	   Technology shares rose on growing confidence that Vodafone AirTouch PLC will
be successful in its $137.6 billion bid for German telecommunications company
Mannesmann AG. Mannesmann is fighting the bid. Shareholders have until Feb. 7 to
reply to the offer.
</P>
<P>
	   London's FTSE-100 Share Index closed up 11.3 points, or 0.2 percent, and the
Paris CAC-40 Index closed 55.34 points or 1.0 percent higher. Frankfurt's Xetra
DAX Index surged to its second record close in a row, ending 85.68 points or 1.2
percent higher.
</P>
<P>
	   Latin American indexes were also mostly higher Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
