<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Adjourns Ex-Premier's Hearing  </HEADLINE>
   By ZAHID HUSSAIN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) -- The hearing into allegations of treason and
hijacking against deposed Premier Nawaz Sharif was adjourned Monday, giving
defense attorneys an extra day to prepare their case.
</P>
<P>
	   The judge ordered Sharif to return to court on Tuesday, along with his six
codefendants.
</P>
<P>
	   Judge Rehmet Hussein Jaffri adjourned the hearing after Sharif's lawyers
said they were still waiting for a recording of conversations that occurred Oct.
12 in the control tower of the Karachi International Airport.
</P>
<P>
	   Oct. 12 was the day of the military coup that overthrew Sharif. That day,
the army alleges, Sharif refused to let an aircraft carrying army chief Gen.
Pervez Musharraf land in Karachi.
</P>
<P>
	   Barely seven minutes of fuel remained when the aircraft finally landed.
After seizing power, the army placed Sharif in protective custody and later
accused him of trying to kill Musharraf.
</P>
<P>
	   Sharif has denied the allegation, and so far no formal charges have been
filed. It was not clear whether charges would be filed Tuesday, but once they
are filed and a trial begins, it must be completed within seven days.
</P>
<P>
	   Musharraf, who is leading the country's military regime, has said he will
restore civilian rule only after he revives the battered economy and introduces
political reforms.
</P>
<P>
	   Also Monday, China pledged unwavering support for Pakistan, giving a boost
to Musharraf on his first visit to a non-Islamic state since taking charge.
Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji promised his government will nurture the nations'
``comprehensive partnership,'' China's Xinhua News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
	   China has been a loyal ally of Pakistan for decades, seeing it as a useful
counterbalance to India's regional dominance. China has refrained from publicly
criticizing the coup and has said Sharif's trial was Pakistan's internal affair.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, tensions continued between India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
	   The Pakistan Foreign Ministry said Monday that Sunday's arrest of a junior
employee at the Indian Embassy is proof that India is sponsoring terrorism in
Pakistan. The employee, identified as P. Moses, allegedly had an explosive
device. The Foreign Ministry said Moses admitted the bomb was to be detonated in
a congested bazaar.
</P>
<P>
	   India denied the allegation and demanded Moses be released.
</P>
<P>
	   Since last month's hijacking of an Indian Airlines plane, the troubled
relations between India and Pakistan have plummeted. India has accused Pakistan
of orchestrating the hijacking. Pakistan denies the charge.
</P>
<P>
	   Musharraf was quoted by one of India's principal newspapers, The Hindu, as
saying that no progress will be made if India repeats assertions that Pakistan
harbors terrorist groups.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I may add,'' Musharraf said, ``that I am not one of those that when you
keep receiving all this kind of flak from across the border, I keep sitting and
I turn my other cheek.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
