<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weyerhaeuser;s 100th Birthday Tues.  </HEADLINE>
    By MICHAEL J. MARTINEZ AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FEDERAL WAY, Wash. (AP) -- In 1900, German immigrant and businessman
Frederick Weyerhaeuser bought 900,000 acres of prime timberland in the rugged
mountains of Washington state, leftovers from the Great Western Railroad.
</P>
<P>
	   A century later, the company that bears his name is one of the largest
lumber and forest products companies in the world, expanding heavily into the
Pacific Rim and boasting the latest technology.
</P>
<P>
	   Yet, as the company prepares to celebrate its first 100 years in business on
Tuesday, this could be the most competitive time in Weyerhaeuser Co.'s history.
</P>
<P>
	   "There are so many innovations that affect what we do," said George
Weyerhaeuser Jr, Frederick's great-great-grandson and the company's senior vice
president of technology. "Will online news threaten our newsprint business? Will
more houses be built with concrete instead of lumber?"
</P>
<P>
	   The challenges of the 21st century are not lost on George Weyerhaeuser Jr.,
who declined the traditional family leadership roles in the company to focus on
technologies that will help the company compete.
</P>
<P>
	   "I have been fascinated with the technology side of the business," he said.
"How our society gets its materials is going to change, and we want to be part
of it."
</P>
<P>
	   Frederick Weyerhaeuser started the company in Tacoma with a team of 11
investors, three employees and a $6 million investment in timberland. Today, now
based in Federal Way, Weyerhaeuser Co. has 45,000 employees in 13 countries.
Revenues last year totaled nearly $11 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   The family business was listed on the New York Stock Exchange in 1963 -- the
same year it opened its first office in Japan. In 1964, it began operating in
Europe. In 1984, it opened an office in China, where a box plant in Shanghai now
makes containers for Coca-Cola and Budweiser.
</P>
<P>
	   "We've positioned ourselves to be the forest products purveyor to the
Pacific Rim," said George Weyerhaeuser.
</P>
<P>
	   That position is key, because other companies around the globe have stepped
up their acquisitions and competition. Foreign companies -- once thought to be
second-tier competitors best left to their own markets -- have grown
considerably, even as Weyerhaeuser Co. has itself expanded overseas.
</P>
<P>
	   "We now have very large, very effective international competitors," George
Weyerhaeuser said. "If we take our customers for granted, they can muscle right
in."
</P>
<P>
	   The nature of the business has changed as well. While Weyerhaeuser has
continued to grow its core business -- forestry, lumber and basic wood products
-- it has also made key acquisitions and spent $80 million on research last year
alone to develop the next generation of engineered products.
</P>
<P>
	   "There's a lot of potential in carbon-based products," George Weyerhaeuser
said, noting the recent development of plastics based on organic materials like
corn. "They are renewable, they're powered by the sun, and they're benign
environmentally. That's a very intriguing combination for us."
</P>
<P>
	   The recent acquisition of Trus Joist Co. gives Weyerhaeuser strong inroads
into the engineered wood products market. By combining traditional lumber with
chemical and physical processes, the company can make stronger building
materials using less actual lumber.
</P>
<P>
	   George Weyerhaeuser said that kind of innovation will help the company in
the near future, but added that his great-great-grandfather would be more amazed
by the level of communication and cooperation that helps run the company today.
</P>
<P>
	   "Back when Frederick started the company, you basically sent your best, most
trustworthy person out to essentially run things for you," he said. "You trusted
them to pretty much run everything. I think the biggest surprise to him would be
in how we coordinate and communicate and use computers to tie everything
together."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 1657 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000117.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court To Weigh 'Bubble' Law  </HEADLINE>
   By AARON J. LOPEZ Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DENVER (AP) -- The morning calm on a tree-lined residential street is
pierced as sign-carrying protesters shout at women entering an abortion clinic.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's an office of death! Don't kill your baby! Do you know what you're
doing?'' they yell from eight feet away at women partially shielded by a 4-foot
brick wall outside the Planned Parenthood clinic.
</P>
<P>
	   It is a scene dictated by Colorado's 1993 ``bubble'' law, which requires
protesters to keep their distance from patients entering health-care facilities.
</P>
<P>
	   On Wednesday, the U.S. Supreme Court will hear arguments on whether the law
legally protects patients from harassment and intimidation or violates the
protesters' right to free speech.
</P>
<P>
	   The decision could establish guidelines for other states and cities that
have grappled with ways to maintain peace between protesters and women seeking
abortions.
</P>
<P>
	   The state of Colorado argues that the law balances free-speech rights with
the right to access to health care. The Legislature passed the law after hearing
patients complain of being spat on, kicked and harassed.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's all right to protest. That's fine, but when it gets down to
intervening with another person's recognized right, the Legislature felt obliged
to step in,'' said Deputy Attorney General Ken Lane.
</P>
<P>
	   James Henderson of the Virginia-based American Center for Law and Justice,
which represents the protesters, counters that the law tramples on free-speech
rights.
</P>
<P>
	   ``My way of sidewalk counseling is to be gentle and to be compassionate.
Colorado's way is to put me so far away I have to scream and yell,'' Jeanne
Hill, one of three protesters challenging the law.
</P>
<P>
	   Around the country, some cities have tried creating buffer zones between
protesters and clinic patients, and between protesters and churches. Others have
required protesters to obtain permits for demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
	   Fourteen states and the District of Columbia have laws that prohibit
protesters from blocking clinic entrances, said Elizabeth Arndorfer, an attorney
with the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League.
</P>
<P>
	   The Colorado law bars people from counseling, distributing leaflets or
displaying signs within eight feet of others without their consent. The
protective bubble is maintained within 100 feet of an entrance to a health-care
facility. Violators can get up to six months in jail and a $750 fine.
</P>
<P>
	   None of the three protesters at the center of the case was arrested under
the law. Colorado Senate Minority Leader Mike Feeley, a Democrat who sponsored
the legislation, said no one at all has been arrested since it was enacted.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S. Supreme Court returned the case to Colorado's state courts in 1997
to reconsider it in wake of the high court's decision in a New York case. In
that case, the high court allowed abortion protesters to confront patients on
public sidewalks as long as they stayed at least 15 feet from the clinic's
entrance.
</P>
<P>
	   A Colorado appeals court again upheld the law, noting it was enacted by
lawmakers, while the New York case involved a judge's injunction.
</P>
<P>
	   The Colorado Supreme Court also voted last year to uphold the state law,
citing ``greater deference for legislative enactments regulating speech.'' It
also drew a distinction between buffer zones of 15 feet and eight feet, ruling
that the smaller buffer zone allows for ``normal conversational tones.''
</P>
<P>
	   Ellen Brilliant of Planned Parenthood of the Rockies said the mere threat of
prosecution has made a noticeable improvement.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I have seen clients shoved. I've seen staff pushed,'' Ms. Brilliant said.
``With the bubble law, protesters still can say what they want to say and
clients are able to access health care free from harassment and intimidation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 1700 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000117.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weyerhaeuser Reacheing 100 Years  </HEADLINE>
    By MICHAEL J. MARTINEZ AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FEDERAL WAY, Wash. (AP) -- In 1900, German immigrant and businessman
Frederick Weyerhaeuser bought 900,000 acres of prime timberland in the rugged
mountains of Washington state, leftovers from the Great Western Railroad.
</P>
<P>
	   A century later, the company that bears his name is one of the largest
lumber and forest products companies in the world, expanding heavily into the
Pacific Rim and boasting the latest technology.
</P>
<P>
	   Yet, as the company prepares to celebrate its first 100 years in business on
Tuesday, this could be the most competitive time in Weyerhaeuser Co.'s history.
</P>
<P>
	   "There are so many innovations that affect what we do," said George
Weyerhaeuser Jr, Frederick's great-great-grandson and the company's senior vice
president of technology. "Will online news threaten our newsprint business? Will
more houses be built with concrete instead of lumber?"
</P>
<P>
	   The challenges of the 21st century are not lost on George Weyerhaeuser Jr.,
who declined the traditional family leadership roles in the company to focus on
technologies that will help the company compete.
</P>
<P>
	   "I have been fascinated with the technology side of the business," he said.
"How our society gets its materials is going to change, and we want to be part
of it."
</P>
<P>
	   Frederick Weyerhaeuser started the company in Tacoma with a team of 11
investors, three employees and a $6 million investment in timberland. Today, now
based in Federal Way, Weyerhaeuser Co. has 45,000 employees in 13 countries.
Revenues last year totaled nearly $11 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   The family business was listed on the New York Stock Exchange in 1963 -- the
same year it opened its first office in Japan. In 1964, it began operating in
Europe. In 1984, it opened an office in China, where a box plant in Shanghai now
makes containers for Coca-Cola and Budweiser.
</P>
<P>
	   "We've positioned ourselves to be the forest products purveyor to the
Pacific Rim," said George Weyerhaeuser.
</P>
<P>
	   That position is key, because other companies around the globe have stepped
up their acquisitions and competition. Foreign companies -- once thought to be
second-tier competitors best left to their own markets -- have grown
considerably, even as Weyerhaeuser Co. has itself expanded overseas.
</P>
<P>
	   "We now have very large, very effective international competitors," George
Weyerhaeuser said. "If we take our customers for granted, they can muscle right
in."
</P>
<P>
	   The nature of the business has changed as well. While Weyerhaeuser has
continued to grow its core business -- forestry, lumber and basic wood products
-- it has also made key acquisitions and spent $80 million on research last year
alone to develop the next generation of engineered products.
</P>
<P>
	   "There's a lot of potential in carbon-based products," George Weyerhaeuser
said, noting the recent development of plastics based on organic materials like
corn. "They are renewable, they're powered by the sun, and they're benign
environmentally. That's a very intriguing combination for us."
</P>
<P>
	   The recent acquisition of Trus Joist Co. gives Weyerhaeuser strong inroads
into the engineered wood products market. By combining traditional lumber with
chemical and physical processes, the company can make stronger building
materials using less actual lumber.
</P>
<P>
	   George Weyerhaeuser said that kind of innovation will help the company in
the near future, but added that his great-great-grandfather would be more amazed
by the level of communication and cooperation that helps run the company today.
</P>
<P>
	   "Back when Frederick started the company, you basically sent your best, most
trustworthy person out to essentially run things for you," he said. "You trusted
them to pretty much run everything. I think the biggest surprise to him would be
in how we coordinate and communicate and use computers to tie everything
together."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 1701 </TRAILER>
