<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weyerhaeuser Reaching 100 Years  </HEADLINE>
    By MICHAEL J. MARTINEZ AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FEDERAL WAY, Wash. (AP) -- In 1900, German immigrant and businessman
Frederick Weyerhaeuser bought 900,000 acres of prime timberland in the rugged
mountains of Washington state, leftovers from the Great Western Railroad.
</P>
<P>
	   A century later, the company that bears his name is one of the largest
lumber and forest products companies in the world, expanding heavily into the
Pacific Rim and boasting the latest technology.
</P>
<P>
	   Yet, as the company prepares to celebrate its first 100 years in business on
Tuesday, this could be the most competitive time in Weyerhaeuser Co.'s history.
</P>
<P>
	   "There are so many innovations that affect what we do," said George
Weyerhaeuser Jr, Frederick's great-great-grandson and the company's senior vice
president of technology. "Will online news threaten our newsprint business? Will
more houses be built with concrete instead of lumber?"
</P>
<P>
	   The challenges of the 21st century are not lost on George Weyerhaeuser Jr.,
who declined the traditional family leadership roles in the company to focus on
technologies that will help the company compete.
</P>
<P>
	   "I have been fascinated with the technology side of the business," he said.
"How our society gets its materials is going to change, and we want to be part
of it."
</P>
<P>
	   Frederick Weyerhaeuser started the company in Tacoma with a team of 11
investors, three employees and a $6 million investment in timberland. Today, now
based in Federal Way, Weyerhaeuser Co. has 45,000 employees in 13 countries.
Revenues last year totaled nearly $11 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   The family business was listed on the New York Stock Exchange in 1963 -- the
same year it opened its first office in Japan. In 1964, it began operating in
Europe. In 1984, it opened an office in China, where a box plant in Shanghai now
makes containers for Coca-Cola and Budweiser.
</P>
<P>
	   "We've positioned ourselves to be the forest products purveyor to the
Pacific Rim," said George Weyerhaeuser.
</P>
<P>
	   That position is key, because other companies around the globe have stepped
up their acquisitions and competition. Foreign companies -- once thought to be
second-tier competitors best left to their own markets -- have grown
considerably, even as Weyerhaeuser Co. has itself expanded overseas.
</P>
<P>
	   "We now have very large, very effective international competitors," George
Weyerhaeuser said. "If we take our customers for granted, they can muscle right
in."
</P>
<P>
	   The nature of the business has changed as well. While Weyerhaeuser has
continued to grow its core business -- forestry, lumber and basic wood products
-- it has also made key acquisitions and spent $80 million on research last year
alone to develop the next generation of engineered products.
</P>
<P>
	   "There's a lot of potential in carbon-based products," George Weyerhaeuser
said, noting the recent development of plastics based on organic materials like
corn. "They are renewable, they're powered by the sun, and they're benign
environmentally. That's a very intriguing combination for us."
</P>
<P>
	   The recent acquisition of Trus Joist Co. gives Weyerhaeuser strong inroads
into the engineered wood products market. By combining traditional lumber with
chemical and physical processes, the company can make stronger building
materials using less actual lumber.
</P>
<P>
	   George Weyerhaeuser said that kind of innovation will help the company in
the near future, but added that his great-great-grandfather would be more amazed
by the level of communication and cooperation that helps run the company today.
</P>
<P>
	   "Back when Frederick started the company, you basically sent your best, most
trustworthy person out to essentially run things for you," he said. "You trusted
them to pretty much run everything. I think the biggest surprise to him would be
in how we coordinate and communicate and use computers to tie everything
together."
</P>
</TEXT>
