<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monday, Jan. 17, 2000
</P>
<P>
	   Ben &AMP; Jerry Sale Opposed
</P>
<P>
	   MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) -- In a bid to keep Ben &AMP; Jerry's
independent and socially active, some franchisees of the gourmet
ice cream company are pressuring its board to abandon plans to sell
the company. But they also want to send a message to any suitor:
``If by some miracle you are able to take us over, we're not
changing. You have to change,'' said Michael Garrett, who owns four
Ben &AMP; Jerry's stores in Connecticut and New York. Ben &AMP; Jerry's
Homemade Inc., known for serving flavors like Rainforest Crunch and
embracing the liberal causes of the former hippies who founded the
business, revealed last month that it was being courted.
</P>
<P>
	   Mannesmann Shuffles Management
</P>
<P>
	   DUESSELDORF, Germany (AP) -- The embattled telecommunications
company Mannesmann AG shuffled its top management today, an
expected change in preparation of the spinoff of its engineering
and automotive unit. Albert Weismuller will become chief financial
officer, taking over from Joachim Rauhut, who will head Mannesmann
Engineering and Automotive, a division that is to be split off from
the company's telecom operations. Hermann Reith, an analyst with
BHF Bank in Frankfurt, said the personnel changes are unrelated to
the hostile, $137 billion takeover bid by British rival Vodafone
AirTouch PLC. Mannesmann has also set up a new group management
board in charge of overseeing its recent acquisitions, such as the
British telecommunications company Orange PLC. Mannesmann shares
were up 6.4 percent in Frankfurt trading at $278 a share Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Glaxo Buying SmithKline Beecham
</P>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- Glaxo Wellcome's planned acquisition of rival
drugmaker SmithKline Beecham would do more than create the world's
largest pharmaceutical company. The deal, announced today and worth
about $76 billion in stock, is a clear sign that the merger trend
now reshaping other industries is accelerating in the
still-fragmented drug business. Just last week, Pfizer emerged as
the likely winner in a battle with American Home Products for U.S.
drugmaker Warner-Lambert, while Monsanto is in the process of
merging with Pharmacia and Upjohn. Industry analysts predict other
blue-chip names, including Eli Lilly, Schering Plough, Novartis,
Bristol-Myers Squibb and even merger-averse Merck, won't be far
behind.
</P>
<P>
	   German Software Firm Woos Top Staff
</P>
<P>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Europe's largest software company,
Germany's SAP AG, is asking shareholders to vote at a special
meeting tomorrow on a stock plan that gives management the option
to buy company shares at a set price in the future, a rare move for
a German company its size. The proposal, disparaged by critics as
``plain vanilla'' for its relative simplicity, is aimed at stemming
a flow of nearly 50 top level employees who have left its
U.S.-based unit over the last year for competitors with more
generous stock offerings. But it also bucks a growing trend in
Germany that ties employee incentives and bonuses more closely to
actual stock performance and stays away from stock options.
</P>
<P>
	   Japan Stocks Soar; Europe Shares Up
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose to a 29-month high in Tokyo today as
Japan's central bank left its monetary policy unchanged, a move
that also boosted the yen against the dollar. European markets were
modestly higher as investors debated the merits of a $76 billion
merger in the pharmaceutical industry. U.S. financial markets were
closed today in observance of Martin Luther King Jr. Day. In Japan,
the benchmark Nikkei Stock Average rose 480.68 points, or 2.54
percent, to close at 19,437.23 points. In Europe, stocks closed
higher despite some mixed reactions to the latest round of
corporate mergers. Shares of drug companies were mostly lower
following the announcement of the merger agreement between British
drug companies Glaxo Wellcome PLC and SmithKline Beecham PLC.
London's FTSE-100 Share Index closed up 11.3 points. The Paris
CAC-40 Index closed 55.34 points higher. Frankfurt's Xetra DAX
Index surged to its second record close in a row, ending 85.68
points higher. Latin American indexes were also mostly higher
today.
</P>
<P>
	   Jailed Market Guru Might Appeal
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- An attorney for Martin A. Armstrong said today
he is considering filing an appeal to get the renowned market
forecaster out of jail. Armstrong was handcuffed and led out of
court Friday for failing to comply with an order to turn over gold
bars, antiques and company records. Judge Richard Owen told
Armstrong he had the keys to his own cell, and would be released as
soon as he agreed to provide the missing items, which include about
$14 million in valuables and at least one computer. Armstrong,
founder of Princeton Economics International Ltd., has been charged
with defrauding Japanese investors out of almost $1 billion. He has
pleaded not guilty.
</P>
<P>
	   TV Head Praises U.S. Drug Policy
</P>
<P>
	   PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- The head of the most popular television
network among teen-age girls says the government should be
congratulated -- not condemned -- for trying to insert anti-drug
messages in the plots of TV comedies and dramas. The WB network
twice sought the advice of President Clinton's anti-drug counselors
on scripts for its prime-time shows. But Jamie Kellner, the WB's
chief executive, said today the network received no financial
benefit for pushing a message that discourages drug use.
</P>
<P>
	   Hyundai Founder To Visit N. Korea
</P>
<P>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Chung Ju-yung, South Korea's richest
