<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Governor adds voice to those calling on Wallingford to honor  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   WALLINGFORD, Conn. (AP) - As more than 400 Wallingford residents
attended an annual service Monday honoring Martin Luther King Jr., Gov. John G.
Rowland pledged his support for legislation that would force town officials to
recognize the holiday.
<P>
	   Wallingford is the only municipality in the state that does not close town
offices on the holiday, despite 1986 legislation that made Martin Luther King
Day a state holiday. The town's policy has drawn sharp criticism from civil
rights leaders, politicians and some residents.
</P>
<P>
	   State Rep. Mary Mushinsky, a Democrat from Wallingford, has proposed
legislation that would force the town to recognize the holiday.
</P>
<P>
	   The governor stepped up the pressure on Wallingford officials Monday by
issuing a statement formally supporting Mushinsky's legislation, which would
require all cities and towns to close their offices on King Day.
</P>
<P>
	   "There should be no doubt in anyone's mind that the state of Connecticut,
and each one of its cities and towns, recognizes Dr. King's contributions to our
country. Every town should observe the Martin Luther King holiday by closing
government offices for the day," Rowland said.
</P>
<P>
	   As Rowland was issuing his statement, more than 400 people gathered in St.
Paul's Episcopal Church for an annual service honoring King. They sang "We Shall
Overcome," read from King's speeches and lit white candles to symbolize King's
preaching of non-violence.
</P>
<P>
	   But outside, just before the service began, a man dressed in a black Ku Klux
Klan hood and robe stood near the front steps of the church. The man told
reporters he is a member of "The Invisible Empire," a division of the Klan. He
had a minor confrontation with a man who yelled at him and then walked away.
</P>
<P>
	   Security at the church was tight because of recent Klan activity in town and
a phone call police received Monday morning telling them that Klansmen would
attend the church service.
</P>
<P>
	   Ten members of a special police tactical unit were stationed at various
spots inside and around the church, as well as in buildings near the church. In
addition, two uniformed police officers were stationed inside the church and
another three were outside.
</P>
<P>
	   Town employees were encouraged to attend the service on their lunch hour.
Civil rights leaders from various parts of the state also attended. Some
criticized the town for refusing to make King Day an official town holiday.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think it's pathetic," said Roland Cockfield, president of the
Meriden-Wallingford chapter of the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
	   "George Washington has his holiday as founder of the nation. Martin Luther
King was founder of freedom and peace. I think he should get the same
recognition," Cockfield said.
</P>
<P>
	   Mayor William Dickinson, who is at the center of the controversy, also
attended the service. Dickinson said the controversy is not about race, but
instead a dispute between himself and the town's labor unions. Dickinson wants
town workers to swap another holiday for King Day, instead of closing town
offices and giving workers a 13th paid holiday.
</P>
<P>
	   The mayor said he would not consider changing his position, despite the
governor's statement.
</P>
<P>
	   "My position is rooted in firm principle in honoring Dr. King and his
message, which is what we're doing today," he said. "The issue is not one of
racism at all. It's an issue of benefits for unions."
</P>
<P>
	   Police Chief Douglas Dortenzio said a man called police Monday morning and
said he and other Klan members planned to try to enter the church service
dressed in Klan robes.
</P>
<P>
	   "He was told by police that he would not be welcome inside this building and
that he would be arrested if he did try to come in," Dortenzio said.
</P>
<P>
	   Last week, three men, including one in a crimson Klan robe, shouted at cars.
The two other men put on white robes and hoods when police questioned them, but
then disbanded.
</P>
<P>
	   Peggy Raczkovy, 81, who has lived in Wallingford since 1941, has attended
the church service every year since the town started it 11 years ago. She said
she feels divided on the issue, just as the town is.
</P>
<P>
	   "I can see the mayor's point of view, but I feel bad about the effect it's
had on the town. It reflects badly on the whole town," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   But Superintendent of Schools Joseph Cirasuolo, who also attended the
service, said he agreed with the mayor's stance.
</P>
<P>
	   "If the town unions felt as strongly about this as they claim, the solution
is very easy - all they have to do is swap holidays," said Cirasuolo.
</P>
<P>
	   "What they're trying to do is get an additional holiday and trying to put
enough pressure on the town to get that."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
