<HEADLINE> N.J. woman who saved kids from London crash recuperating after  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - It happened so fast that all Ursula Webster could
do was shove her 8-year-old son as hard as she could out of the path of the
oncoming car.
<P>
	   She recalls the thud as the vehicle struck her, sending her flying into the
air outside the London residence of British Prime Minister Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
	   "As I was going up, I'm thinking, 'I'm dying, this is it, my life is
ending,' and I could actually feel my bones breaking," she said Monday in a
telephone interview from her hospital bed. "But when I hit the ground and was
still conscious, I knew it wasn't nearly that bad."
</P>
<P>
	   The British tabloids are hailing the Livingston woman as "The Heroine of
Downing Street" for saving her son from the speeding car that crashed into the
gates outside 10 Downing Street on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   She, her husband David and their three sons were there sightseeing because
they have virtually the same address in Livingston - 10 Downing Place.
</P>
<P>
	   Webster was in satisfactory condition Monday evening at St. Barnabas Medical
Center in Livingston following a 73-minute operation that inserted a
33-centimeter (13.2-inch) stainless steel rod in her lower right leg to
stabilize a broken bone, the tibia, said her surgeon, Dr. Michael H. Rieber.
</P>
<P>
	   "She was awake the whole time, just a little sedated so she doesn't have to
hear all the noise," Rieber said. "Everything went very smoothly."
</P>
<P>
	   The noise came from drilling holes for screws, and from reaming the bone so
the rod would fit, he said. The bone was broken in one place, but some bone was
shattered, so the rod was needed, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   At Mrs. Webster's request, the surgeon played Bruce Springsteen music during
the operation.
</P>
<P>
	   She faces four to six months of rehabilitation after the surgery, she said,
and she predicted it would be difficult with three active children.
</P>
<P>
	   "But I keep thinking this could have been so much worse," she said. "We
could have been killed."
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Webster said she and her family approached police officers at the
gates, explained that they lived at the same address in New Jersey and asked for
and received permission to go inside the ornate protective gates to take
photographs.
</P>
<P>
	   "We have the same door knocker on our house as the one at 10 Downing Street,
and we thought it would be neat to take a picture of it," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   It was as they were walking back out and thanking the police officers that
the accident happened, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   "The car skidded and went straight at the gates," said Sertac Bahri, 19, who
witnessed the accident. "As that was happening a woman tried to push her child
so he didn't get hurt. She saved the kid, but she didn't save herself."
</P>
<P>
	   Andrew was brushed by the door of the red Vauxhall Astra and her 6
1/2-year-old son Alex was grazed by the car's wing mirror, but neither was
seriously hurt. Her 3 1/2-year-old son Peter and her husband were not struck.
</P>
<P>
	   "It happened so fast that we were in complete shock," Webster said. "There
was no time to be afraid. We're all very luck we weren't killed."
</P>
<P>
	   London police filed charges Sunday against the driver of the car. Stephen
Bonnett, 26, an engineer from Chelmsford, east of London, was charged with
causing grievous bodily harm and dangerous driving, police said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bonnett was granted bail at a five-minute hearing Monday and ordered to
return to court Jan. 31 to face the charges.
</P>
<P>
	   It was not immediately clear whether he is suspected of deliberately
crashing into the gates or whether he simply lost control of the car.
</P>
<P>
	   Webster said she suspects it was deliberate.
</P>
<P>
	   "My husband saw him after the crash, and he said he had this crazy look on
his face," she said. "I think maybe he had something against" Blair or the
government.
</P>
<P>
	   Blair and his family were at the British prime minister's country residence,
Chequers at the time. Blair has asked to be kept informed of Mrs. Webster's
condition and would be writing to her, aides said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
