<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Celtic-Style Musician Killed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARGAREE HARBOUR, Nova Scotia (AP) -- John Morris Rankin, a member of the
musical family that helped popularize Cape Breton-style Celtic music, was killed
when his truck ran off a road into the ocean. He was 40.
</P>
<P>
	   Rankin died Sunday while driving his son and two other teen-agers to a
morning hockey game, the Royal Canadian Mounted Police said. The three youths
were all rescued unharmed from the frigid ocean water off Nova Scotia in eastern
Canada.
</P>
<P>
	   Rankin played fiddle and piano with his four siblings in groups known first
as The Rankin Family and then the Rankins. Their music drew from the strong
traditional Celtic roots of Cape Breton island, a part of Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
	   Over a decade that began with appearances at county fairs, the group sold
more than 2 million records and won five Juno Awards, the Canadian equivalent of
the Grammy. The Rankins broke up last summer so members could pursue independent
careers.
</P>
<P>
	   Rankin is survived by his wife, Sally, and two children, along with his
musical siblings Jimmy, Cookie, Raylene and Heather. A funeral was planned for
Thursday in Mabou, Nova Scotia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
