<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rally Targets S.C. Confederate Flag  </HEADLINE>
   By DAN LEWERENZ Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Hundreds of out-of-state visitors who came to rally
against the Confederate flag flying atop South Carolina's Statehouse snubbed
hotels and slept in churches to support the NAACP's tourism boycott of the
state.
</P>
<P>
	   An estimated 46,000 people converged on the Statehouse on Monday for the
march and rally. But the National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People tourism boycott that started Jan. 1 left few hotel rooms filled.
</P>
<P>
	   Rodney Jenkins said 150 visitors from Maryland ate and slept at Bethel
African Methodist Episcopal Church in Columbia, where he is a trustee. About 200
more stayed at Benedict College or at other churches, some sleeping on cots.
</P>
<P>
	   Jenkins said blacks in other states might not have to live under the
Confederate flag's shadow, but ``we have common causes. Across this nation,
black folks have the same problems, whether it be a flag, whether it be job
discrimination or housing. We are as one.''
</P>
<P>
	   Harris Sable, manager of the downtown Governor's House Hotel, said only a
few visitors stayed there. ``There's a very small handful -- I mean, maybe
there's four, if that,'' Sable said.
</P>
<P>
	   Those on a bus from Tennessee would not spend a penny in South Carolina,
said 16-year-old Melissa Hudson of Memphis. They brought their own food and
would sleep on the bus, she said. They bought fuel before crossing the state
line -- enough gas to get to Columbia and out of the state before they have to
fill up again.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're not going to support a state that flies that flag,'' Hudson said.
</P>
<P>
	   Sable said his hotel has had $20,000 to $25,000 worth of cancellations since
the boycott was announced in July, and has lost an unknown amount of potential
business.
</P>
<P>
	   Not all businesses suffered. A cool, windy morning led to a brisk business
in warm beverages and lunchtime lines stretched to the sidewalk at restaurants.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They just kept buying hot chocolate after hot chocolate, cappuccino,
coffee,'' said Amanda Maybin of the Atlanta Bread Company, who said the downtown
restaurant served about 200 more customers Monday than on a typical weekday.
``Considering there was nobody working downtown, we had a pretty busy day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
