<HEADLINE> Man nabbed at border could be daring getaway robber  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - A phony passport and a sword was all it took for border
officials to deny a man access from Buffalo into Canada. The real surprise came
later, when U.S. Customs officials learned the man may be wanted in New York for
a series of knifepoint robberies and a daredevil escape from a high-rise.
<P>
	   Now the NYPD is investigating whether the 21-year-old man - who goes by the
names Jaquan Muhammad and Nastali Triplett - may have used the sword he was
found with to kill a Brooklyn resident Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
	   A federal law enforcement official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Monday the accused had "personal notes" with him detailing the crimes.
</P>
<P>
	   So far, no charges have been filed against the man, whose real identity has
not been revealed by police. He was flown back from Buffalo Monday afternoon -
escorted by several NYPD detectives - and taken in for further questioning, said
Deputy Chief Tom Fahey, a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
	   Police were investigating whether the man was responsible for at least eight
knifepoint robberies since Jan. 8 in midtown Manhattan. The robber fooled police
Jan. 11 after he ran into a high-rise building, jumped out a 19th floor window
onto an air conditioning unit on a nearby rooftop, disguised himself as a food
delivery person and blended into the lunchtime crowd to escape.
</P>
<P>
	   After that getaway, police declared all-out war by splashing a sketch of the
robber all over the news. One tabloid newspaper even dubbed him "Spiderman."
</P>
<P>
	   Did the notoriety send the robber out of town? That remains to be seen,
police say. But a police source, speaking on condition of anonymity, believes
the publicity spooked the robber, prompting him to hop a Greyhound bus Sunday
for Buffalo in hopes of fleeing the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   At the border Sunday, a man on a bus at the Peace Bridge crossing was denied
access into Canada, said Janet Rapaport, a spokeswoman for the U.S. Customs
Service in New York City.
</P>
<P>
	   He was allegedly sporting a phony passport, had a sword and was carrying a
6-inch dagger and a 12-inch hunting knife.
</P>
<P>
	   Into the arms of waiting Customs officials he went. A check of the man's
personal effects proved interesting. He had several documents with various names
of them, said the federal official.
</P>
<P>
	   "And personal notes he had indicated he was wanted by the NYPD," the
official said.
</P>
<P>
	   Once in a holding cell in Buffalo, the man allegedly tried to get away
again, this time by crawling into a ceiling space after he knocked down some
tiles.
</P>
<P>
	   Back in New York, police were scheduling lineups, hoping a victim or witness
to the recent robberies might link the would-be border crosser to the crimes in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
	   Lineups could begin as early as Tuesday, police said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
