<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria Restless on Peace Talks  </HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SEVAREID Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) -- In the United States, Syria's foreign minister
handles negotiations with Israel. But the minister is more of a messenger for
President Hafez Assad, the real decision-maker, who is sitting out the talks.
</P>
<P>
	   Assad is a master negotiator of the subtle variety, reclusive and indirect.
What he wants his citizens or the outside world to know is relayed through
feelers, leaks or the state-run media. And what he has been leaking of late
indicates he may want to readjust the course of negotiations to focus on Syria's
key concern -- the return of the Israeli-occupied Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
	   Israel announced Monday that the third round of talks, which had been set to
open Wednesday in the United States, had been indefinitely postponed following
hints Syria wanted a delay. Syria has indicated it expects talks will resume
soon, though neither side has said how soon.
</P>
<P>
	   By sending signals of wariness, Assad appears to be trying to pressure the
Americans and Israelis. At the same time, Syrians have been suspicious that
Barak may use Cabinet crises, opinion polls and rallies against a Golan
withdrawal to force Syrian concessions. Neither side wants to appear to be
giving up too much too easily.
</P>
<P>
	   Syria accuses Israel of wanting to focus only on side issues, not what
Damascus sees as the crux of the problem -- setting a new border.
</P>
<P>
	   Israel seized the Golan Heights border plateau from Syria in the 1967 Middle
East war. When Assad agreed last year to resume negotiations after a 3 1/2-year
freeze, he insisted that for talks to begin, there had to be an understanding
Syria would get back the Golan.
</P>
<P>
	   Syria has made clear that other matters can be negotiated after an agreement
on the Golan. But before drawing any boundaries, Israel wants to know what sort
of security guarantees and relations it will get in return.
</P>
<P>
	   At the last round of talks, the committee dealing with border issues met
formally only once. A U.S. working document leaked to an Israeli newspaper
indicated wide gaps remain on border and security questions. But it suggested
the two sides were much closer to answers Israel is looking for on the nature of
future relations.
</P>
<P>
	   The document, considered merely a basis for future talks, cites no
differences in positions on exchanging ambassadors, promoting bilateral trade
and tourism and opening borders.
</P>
<P>
	   Syria's anger over the leaks was clear. The state-controlled Syrian
newspaper Al-Thawra accused Israel of leaking the document, perhaps ``to kill
negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
	   A pro-Syrian Lebanese newspaper responded with what it says were Syrian
amendments to the document. The amendments emphasized Syrian steadfastness,
calling for a complete Israeli withdrawal to the 1967 border and the removal of
Israeli settlements.
</P>
<P>
	   Editorials in state-run Syrian newspapers since the second round of talks
adjourned Jan. 10 in Shepherdstown, W.Va., repeatedly have called negotiations
thus far a failure.
</P>
<P>
	   In the end, though, Middle East analyst Yezid Sayigh said, games played by
both sides during day-to-day negotiations are largely for domestic consumption
and mean little in the overall picture.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We know what's on the table. We all know what the final deal has to look
like more or less. And the rest is playing games,'' Sayigh, of the International
Center for Strategic Studies, said in a telephone interview from his London
office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 1808 </TRAILER>
