<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Favorite Sons in Iowa Campaign Ads  </HEADLINE>
   By LAURA MECKLER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Iowa airwaves are filled with ads featuring hometown
senators Tom Harkin and Charles Grassley, though neither man is on the ballot.
They're vouching for Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
	   As voting nears, the presidential candidates are trotting out high-profile
supporters in TV and radio ads, and are hoping voters will follow their lead.
</P>
<P>
	   So in South Carolina, popular Rep. Lindsey Graham stars in an endorsement
for Republican Sen. John McCain. In New Hampshire, liberal icon Edward Kennedy
invites voters to stand with him for Gore. And when Barbara Bush goes to New
Hampshire this week, her son's campaign will have cameras rolling, ready to beam
her to TV sets across the state.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The governor's family is a tremendous asset in this campaign,'' said Mark
McKinnon, media strategist for the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
	   Endorsement ads are usually used as campaigns near an end -- the Iowa
caucuses are next week, followed by the New Hampshire primary on Feb. 1. -- with
popular homestate officials reassuring voters that so-and-so will be good for
their state.
</P>
<P>
	   Harkin tells Iowans that Gore will be good for farmers and Graham tells
South Carolinians that McCain will restore honor to the White House.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They are a way of signaling that people who have the best interests of the
state at heart and have been elected by the citizens of the state believe it
would be in the state's interest to vote for this candidate,'' said Kathleen
Hall Jamieson, dean of the Annenberg School for Communication at the University
of Pennsylvania, who studies political advertising.
</P>
<P>
	   That's just what Harkin, who has been campaigning for Gore, aims to do in
his radio and television ads airing now in Iowa ahead of the Jan. 24 caucuses.
He sends a message: I trust him; you can too.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's always nice to have someone in the White House who understands people
who live in rural states like Iowa,'' Harkin said.
</P>
<P>
	   Similarly, the Bush campaign recruited Grassley, Iowa's other senator, for
radio ads airing now that respond to critical ads by Bush rival Steve Forbes.
``If you're tired of mudslinging and name calling, go to the caucuses Monday,
January 24th, and join me in voting for a fresh start for America by voting for
George W. Bush,'' Grassley says.
</P>
<P>
	   The last time Grassley was on the ballot, he pulled 72 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
	   There are no plans to use Bush's father, the former president, in
advertising, though his mother may show up in an ad later this week. The
campaign is filming moments from the New Hampshire campaign trail and turning
them into quick-hit ads for the following day. Mrs. Bush, who remains popular
across the country, is a likely subject, McKinnon said.
</P>
<P>
	   But the campaign has not taped a full-fledged ad featuring Bush's parents,
and that makes sense, Jamieson said. ``It raises the question, 'Is he running in
his own right, or is he running by virtue of being the heir apparent?''' she
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Ads must be used strategically or they can backfire. Well-known politicians
also have detractors among the electorate, and a candidate doesn't want to
inherent any ill will. So while Kennedy is adored by many New England Democrats,
New Hampshire is a conservative state, and Gore's campaign is using him only on
radio. That allows the campaign to target the ads to communities where Kennedy
is likely to be well received.
</P>
<P>
	   There's little peril for McCain by featuring Graham in his ads.
</P>
<P>
	   Graham is popular in South Carolina, where he was hailed for the role he
played as a prosecutor during President Clinton's impeachment trial. He knows
his state, and was itching to talk about honor when he taped his radio and
television endorsements.
</P>
<P>
	   ``John McCain is the polar opposite of Bill Clinton,'' Graham says in a
radio ad now airing. ``He has absolute total character and candor.''
</P>
<P>
	   Democrat Bill Bradley is also trading on his endorsements. He featured a
trio of senators who endorsed him in his first ad. He now has Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan of New York in TV ads in Iowa and New Hampshire, as Bradley
tries to motivate his supporters to go and vote.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley's ads normally end with the tag line: ``It can happen,'' suggesting
there's reason to believe in his long-shot bid. But the Moynihan ad ads a line:
``It can happen,'' the screen reads, ``if you go to caucus on January 24.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
