<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women Lead Music Awards Nominees  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVID GERMAIN AP Entertainment Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Country star Shania Twain, soul singer Whitney Houston
and teen newcomer Britney Spears were among the favorites going into Monday
night's American Music Awards.
</P>
<P>
	   The three led the field with three nomination each. And all three were in
the running for favorite pop-rock female artist at the 27th annual awards show,
scheduled to air on ABC from the Shrine Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
	   Twain was also nominated in the country female and adult contemporary artist
categories. Houston was nominated for female artist and album for "My Love Is
Your Love" in the soul-rhythm and blues categories. Spears was up for favorite
pop-rock new artist and pop-rock album for "... Baby One More Time."
</P>
<P>
	   Houston was departing for Europe on Monday night or Tuesday and did not plan
on attending the show, awards spokesman Paul Shefrin said. He said her absence
was unrelated to an incident in Hawaii last week, when airport security guards
said they found about half an ounce of marijuana in her bag but she boarded her
flight before police arrived.
</P>
<P>
	   The latest incarnation of guitarist Carlos Santana's band had two
nominations for his commercial comeback album "Supernatural." In the pop-rock
categories, Santana was nominated for favorite album and favorite band, duo or
group.
</P>
<P>
	   Other nominees for pop-rock band, duo or group were the Backstreet Boys and
'N Sync. The pop-rock male artist nominees were Lenny Kravitz, Ricky Martin and
Will Smith.
</P>
<P>
	   Besides Santana and Spears' albums, the Backstreet Boys' "Millennium" was up
for favorite pop-rock album.
</P>
<P>
	   The nominees were chosen by music industry representatives. The winners were
decided by about 20,000 music fans nationwide.
</P>
<P>
	   Besides awards in 20 regular categories, the show was to feature results of
an Internet poll on listeners' favorite musical artists for each decade from the
1950s through the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
	   Performers scheduled to appear on the three-hour show included Kravitz,
Christina Aguilera, Mariah Carey, the Eurythmics and Enrique Iglesias. Comedian
Norm Macdonald was tapped to be host.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
