<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore, Bradley Begin Latest Debate  </HEADLINE>
   By SANDRA SOBIERAJ Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Al Gore and Bill Bradley agreed Monday that the
Confederate battle flag should be removed from the South Carolina statehouse,
and the vice president added that ``it's only the GOP White House hopefuls'' who
disagree because they are ``so scared of the right wing.''
</P>
<P>
	   The racially sensitive issue came up in the opening moments of a televised
debate on the federal holiday honoring the late Martin Luther King, Jr., the
last time two Democratic presidential hopefuls will meet before next Monday's
kickoff Iowa caucuses.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore also told his questioner he would not agree to participate in an NAACP
boycott of South Carolina, because ``I don't think a president of the United
States should ever boycott an individual state.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley said the flag ``offends our common humanity and it is not the future
of our country.''
</P>
<P>
	   Gore, who spoke first, also noted that some people view the flag favorably.
``We have to try to bring them into a shared understanding of why, as a symbol,
it is so hurtful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   It was the sixth debate between the two men, and in the early moments, they
reprised well-worn arguments about health care. Gore said Bradley's plan would
hurt the poor; Bradley said it wasn't so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
