<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Income gap widens for American families  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   WASHINGTON (AP) - Fueled in part by the boom on Wall Street, the income
gap between New York's poorest and richest families is now the widest in the
nation, according to a report by two Washington think tanks.
<P>
	   The average income for the poorest fifth of New York families dipped by 15
percent to $10,770 between 1988 and 1998. It rose by 15 percent for the richest
fifth to $152,350, the Center on Budget and Policy Priorities and the Economic
Policy Institute said in a report issued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The study found the richest 20 percent of New York families had average
incomes 14 times the average of the poorest 20 percent of families.
</P>
<P>
	   Nationally, wages for the poorest fifth of American families rose less than
1 percent between 1988 and 1998 but jumped 15 percent for the richest fifth.
</P>
<P>
	   Income for the poorest families - defined as two or more relatives living
together - rose an average of $110 to $12,990 during the 10-year period. For the
richest families it increased by $17,870, to $137,480, the report found.
</P>
<P>
	   The richest 20 percent of families had average incomes 20 times larger than
the poorest 20 percent of families, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
	   "The inequality is particularly striking in New York where the numbers show
the rich getting richer and the poor either stagnating or getting poorer," said
Trudi Renwick, of New York's labor-supported Fiscal Policy Institute.
</P>
<P>
	   Elizabeth McNichol, one of the study's authors, attributed the widening gap
to Wall Street's long-running bull market boosting the economy in general while
lower-paying service jobs replace better-paying manufacturing work.
</P>
<P>
	   And the minimum wage is too low to help, she said. Ten states and the
District of Columbia currently have minimum wages above the $5.15 national rate.
The Senate last year passed a $1 minimum wage increase over three years but the
House failed to act on the measure.
</P>
<P>
	   McNichol also suggested strengthening states' unemployment assistance
programs and social safety net programs for low-income workers, like
transportation and child care.
</P>
<P>
	   But Stephen Moore, director of social policy for the Cato Institute, said
the study contorted data to put a negative face on a "spectacular economy."
</P>
<P>
	   "The rich are getting richer but the poor are getting richer too in this
expansion," said Moore.
</P>
<P>
	   The study used before-tax data from the U.S. Census Bureau and adjusted the
figures for inflation.
</P>
<P>
	   The Center on Budget and Policy Priorities and the Economic Policy Institute
are nonprofit, nonpartisan organizations pushing for changes in tax laws and
other federal policies to benefit low-and moderate-income families.
</P>
<P>
	   Nationally, income was most evenly distributed in Utah, where the poorest
families saw their income increase by $1,360 and the richest rose $24,870.
</P>
<P>
	   The income gap narrowed in just three states - Alaska, Louisiana and
Tennessee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-17-00 1821 </TRAILER>
