<DOCNO> APW20000117.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria Restless on Peace Talks  </HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SEVAREID Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) -- In the United States, Syria's foreign minister
handles negotiations with Israel. But the minister is more of a messenger for
President Hafez Assad, the real decision-maker, who is sitting out the talks.
</P>
<P>
	   Assad is a master negotiator of the subtle variety, reclusive and indirect.
What he wants his citizens or the outside world to know is relayed through
feelers, leaks or the state-run media.
</P>
<P>
	   And what he has been leaking of late indicates he may want to readjust the
course of negotiations to focus on Syria's key concern -- the return of the
Israeli-occupied Golan Heights. Syria also has been angered at leaks elsewhere
suggesting that Israel is getting the better of the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
	   Israel announced Monday that the third round of talks, which had been set to
open Wednesday in the United States, had been indefinitely postponed following
hints Syria wanted a delay. Syria has indicated it expects talks will resume
soon, though neither side has said how soon.
</P>
<P>
	   By sending signals of wariness, Assad appears to be trying to pressure the
Americans and Israelis. At the same time, Syrians have been suspicious that
Barak may use Cabinet crises, opinion polls and rallies against a Golan
withdrawal to force Syrian concessions. Neither side wants to appear to be
giving up too much too easily.
</P>
<P>
	   Syria accuses Israel of wanting to focus only on side issues, not what
Damascus sees as the crux of the problem -- setting a new border.
</P>
<P>
	   Israel seized the Golan Heights border plateau from Syria in the 1967 Middle
East war. When Assad agreed last year to resume negotiations after a 3 1/2-year
freeze, he insisted that for talks to begin, there had to be an understanding
Syria would get back the Golan.
</P>
<P>
	   Syria has made clear that other matters can be negotiated after an agreement
on the Golan. But before drawing any boundaries, Israel wants to know what sort
of security guarantees and relations it will get in return.
</P>
<P>
	   At the last round of talks, the committee dealing with border issues met
formally only once. A U.S. working document leaked to an Israeli newspaper
indicated wide gaps remain on border and security questions. But it suggested
the two sides were much closer to answers Israel is looking for on the nature of
future relations.
</P>
<P>
	   The document, considered merely a basis for future talks, cites no
differences in positions on exchanging ambassadors, promoting bilateral trade
and tourism and opening borders.
</P>
<P>
	   Syria's anger over the leaks was clear. The state-controlled Syrian
newspaper Al-Thawra accused Israel of leaking the document, perhaps ``to kill
negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
	   A pro-Syrian Lebanese newspaper responded with what it says were Syrian
amendments to the document. The amendments emphasized Syrian steadfastness,
calling for a complete Israeli withdrawal to the 1967 border and the removal of
Israeli settlements.
</P>
<P>
	   Editorials in state-run Syrian newspapers since the second round of talks
adjourned Jan. 10 in Shepherdstown, W.Va., repeatedly have called negotiations
thus far a failure.
</P>
<P>
	   In the end, though, Middle East analyst Yezid Sayigh said, games played by
both sides during day-to-day negotiations are largely for domestic consumption
and mean little in the overall picture.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We know what's on the table. We all know what the final deal has to look
like more or less. And the rest is playing games,'' Sayigh, of the International
Center for Strategic Studies, said in a telephone interview from his London
office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 1822 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000117.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore, Bradley Begin Latest Debate  </HEADLINE>
   By SANDRA SOBIERAJ Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Al Gore and Bill Bradley agreed Monday that the
Confederate battle flag should be removed from the South Carolina statehouse,
and the vice president added that ``it's only the GOP White House hopefuls'' who
disagree because they are ``so scared of the right wing.''
</P>
<P>
	   The racially sensitive issue came up in the opening moments of a televised
debate on the federal holiday honoring the late Martin Luther King, Jr., the
last time two Democratic presidential hopefuls will meet before next Monday's
kickoff Iowa caucuses.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore also told his questioner he would not agree to participate in an NAACP
boycott of South Carolina, because ``I don't think a president of the United
States should ever boycott an individual state.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley said the flag ``offends our common humanity and it is not the future
of our country.''
</P>
<P>
	   Gore, who spoke first, also noted that some people view the flag favorably.
``We have to try to bring them into a shared understanding of why, as a symbol,
it is so hurtful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   It was the sixth debate between the two men, and in the early moments, they
reprised well-worn arguments about health care. Gore said Bradley's plan would
hurt the poor; Bradley said it wasn't so.
</P>
<P>
	   The proceedings were disrupted briefly by a young woman who stood at her
seat in the audience to pose a question about global warming. As security guards
move to silence her, the moderator, Travis Smiley of Black Entertainment
Television, quipped, ``I get my 15 minutes (of fame) and this is what happens to
me.''
</P>
<P>
	   Gore broke in to say the young woman had raised a good question, but Smiley
kept firm control, and told the vice president that maybe they could get to the
issue later.
</P>
<P>
	   The Confederate flag issue has come up recently because the GOP presidential
contenders, including Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Arizona Sen. John McCain,
have refused to say it should come down. Instead, they say it's an issue for
residents of the state to decide.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's only the Republican candidates for president who are so scared of the
extreme right win that they will be tolerant of the intolerant lest they offend
the offensive,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
	   Blacks account for a small minority of the vote in Iowa, but given the date
and fact that a black state lawmaker organized the event, a ``Black-Brown''
forum, the two Democrats pledged support for continued efforts to support civil
rights and combat racism.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Racial profiling is particularly pernicious,'' said Bradley, who said that
as president, he would issue an executive order outlawing the practice.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore said, he would do likewise, and send legislation to Congress to outlaw
it.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley trails Gore in the polls in the runup to next week's caucuses.
</P>
<P>
	   Both agreed that they would only appoint to the Supreme Court justices who
appreciate the value of affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I could never appoint anyone to the Supreme Court that I thought would
turn the clock back on civil rights,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore answered the question directly as it was posed: Would he appoint
someone in the tradition of liberal Thurgood Marshall, or conservative Clarence
Thomas?
</P>
<P>
	   ``Two words: Thurgood Marshall,'' Gore said. ``Affirmative action is one of
the tools we still need available to us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 1824 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000117.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Greetings' Stone Dies  </HEADLINE>
    By JOHN AFFLECK Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CLEVELAND (AP) -- Irving Stone, who started working in his family's greeting
card business at age 5 and helped transform it into American Greetings Corp.,
one of the world's largest card makers, died Monday. He was 90.
</P>
<P>
	   Stone died at University Hospitals in Cleveland. The company said he had
suffered from an extended illness but did not specify the cause of death.
</P>
<P>
	   Stone still held the title of founder-chairman and visited American
Greetings' offices as often as he could, but was not involved in managing the
company's day-to-day affairs at the time of his death.
</P>
<P>
	   "Irving Stone was a true visionary, whose leadership propelled our company
to 93 years of consecutive growth," Morry Weiss, chairman and chief executive
officer of American Greetings, said in a written statement. "The company that
once sold its products from the back of a horse-drawn wagon today has sales of
$2.2 billion with products sold in 75 countries around the world."
</P>
<P>
	   Cleveland-based American Greetings, which is in the process of buying
Cincinnati's Gibson Greetings, is second only to the privately held Hallmark in
the card business, though it is the largest publicly traded greeting card
company.
</P>
<P>
	   Stone's father, Jacob Sapirstein, founded the company in 1906 by selling
picture postcards from his wagon.
</P>
<P>
	   Stone, whose brothers Harry and Morris also were involved in the family
business, first started working for his father by stuffing postcards into
envelopes.
</P>
<P>
	   By age 9, Stone had become a partner in the company and handled the every
aspect of the business, from sales to delivery to billing, for two months while
his father was ill. He was the company's bookkeeper by age 12.
</P>
<P>
	   Stone continued to work for the company throughout high school and into his
adulthood.
</P>
<P>
	   Dissatisfied with the quality of cards the family was buying for resale,
Stone got the company to begin designing and printing its own cards in the
1930s. One of his earliest verses, "From Someone Who Likes To Remember Someone
Too Nice To Forget," has sold more cards than any other in the company's history
and is still part of the line, American Greetings said in its obituary for
Stone.
</P>
<P>
	   Stone became company president in 1960, and was promoted to chairman of the
board and chief executive officer in 1978. When Weiss, his son-in-law, was
promoted to CEO in 1987, Stone retained his position as board chairman. He
became founder-chairman in 1992.
</P>
<P>
	   Stone, who lived in the Cleveland suburb of Beachwood, was active in many
Jewish community organizations. He is survived by his wife, Helen, brother Harry
and sister Bernice and four children. His first wife, Beatrice, the mother of
Stone's children, is deceased.
</P>
<P>
	   Funeral services were scheduled for Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 1828 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000117.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
