<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl's Party Sets Emergency Session  </HEADLINE>
   By TONY CZUCZKA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BERLIN (AP) -- Germany's Christian Democrats scheduled an emergency
leadership meeting Monday as calls grew louder for party leaders to resign over
a spreading campaign finance scandal.
</P>
<P>
	   Party leader Wolfgang Schaeuble, himself facing suspicions for accepting the
equivalent of $52,000 from a businessman, set the national party executive
meeting for Tuesday, six days ahead of its next regular session.
</P>
<P>
	   The leaders will be trying to deal with a scandal that was touched off last
month by revelations that former chancellor Helmut Kohl accepted up to $1
million in unreported campaign funds in the 1990s, when the conservative
Christian Democrats led Germany's government.
</P>
<P>
	   The scandal grew last week in Hesse state, where former party officials
admitted funneling millions to party coffers from a Swiss account and falsely
reporting the money as bequests. Those irregularities implicated yet another
senior party figure -- former Hesse party chairman Manfred Kanther, once a tough
law-and-order advocate as Kohl's interior minister.
</P>
<P>
	   Hesse Christian Democrat spokesman Christian Schnee said Monday that Kanther
had decided to give up his parliament seat.
</P>
<P>
	   Over the weekend, Germany's justice minister urged the entire conservative
leadership to step down. Leaders of the Christian Democrats' post-Kohl
generation pressed for resignations themselves on Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We will have to part ways with all those entangled in this affair,''
Christian Wulff, a deputy national party chairman, told North German Radio. ``I
certainly don't exclude expulsions of party members.''
</P>
<P>
	   Schaeuble, Kohl's hand-picked successor in 1998, has been undermined by the
ever-growing revelations of apparent breaches of Germany's party financing law.
Hecklers at a weekend party rally urged Schaeuble to resign and scorned his
efforts to clear up the scandal, which is overshadowing the Christian Democrats'
campaign for Feb. 27 elections in the northern state of Schleswig-Holstein.
</P>
<P>
	   Hesse prosecutors opened a fraud probe Monday against a former party
treasurer and a party tax adviser, widening the range of formal suspects in the
scandal beyond Kohl.
</P>
<P>
	   The probe will seek to determine whether fraud or breach of trust charges
are warranted against tax adviser Horst Weyrauch and the former Hesse party
treasurer, Prince Casimir Sayn-Wittgenstein, prosecutors said. They said they
acted on Kanther's disclosure that $6.8 million flowed to the state's Christian
Democrats from abroad between 1989 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors in Bonn opened a similar probe against Kohl last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 1840 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000117.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Next Friday' Tops Box Office  </HEADLINE>
    By TOM HARRIGAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Ice Cube comedy "Next Friday" topped the box office
for the Martin Luther King Jr. holiday weekend with $17 million in earnings,
according to industry estimates released Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   "Stuart Little" was No. 2 for the Friday-through-Monday period with an
estimate of $12.6 million in ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
	   "The Hurricane" was in third place with $10.7 million, and "Girl,
Interrupted" was fourth at $9.6 million. They moved into wide circulation after
opening in limited release last month to be eligible for Oscar consideration.
</P>
<P>
	   "Next Friday," a sequel to the 1995 comedy "Friday," stars Ice Cube as an
inner-city man hiding out in the suburbs from a vengeful villain. It opened
Wednesday and was No. 1 despite playing in just 1,103 theaters, compared to
3,092 for "Stuart Little."
</P>
<P>
	   "Next Friday" earned about $4.8 million per day from Friday to Sunday. New
Line Cinema estimated Monday's pace would slip to about $2.5 million but had
hopes for the film's long-term success.
</P>
<P>
	   "The original film stayed on the list of top 100 video rentals and sales for
100 weeks, so we knew we had a strong crossover audience for this picture, not
just African-Americans," said David Tuckerman, New Line's executive vice
president for distribution, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   "Stuart Little" has grossed nearly $110 million in five weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   "We are getting a lot of repeat business, and family groups," said Ed
Russell, a spokesman for Sony's Columbia Pictures. "We anticipate better than
$140 million for the length of its run."
</P>
<P>
	   Estimated ticket sales for Friday through Monday at North American theaters,
according to studios and Exhibitor Relations Co. Inc. Final figures were to be
released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   1. "Next Friday," $17 million.
</P>
<P>
	   2. "Stuart Little," $12.6 million.
</P>
<P>
	   3. "The Hurricane," $10.7 million.
</P>
<P>
	   4. "Girl, Interrupted," $9.6 million.
</P>
<P>
	   5. "The Green Mile," $8.7 million.
</P>
<P>
	   6. "Galaxy Quest," $8 million.
</P>
<P>
	   7. "The Talented Mr. Ripley," $7 million.
</P>
<P>
	   8. "Supernova," $6.6 million.
</P>
<P>
	   9. "Toy Story 2," $6.5 million.
</P>
<P>
	   10. "Any Given Sunday," $5.7 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 1841 </TRAILER>
