<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore, Bradley Clash in 6th Debate  </HEADLINE>
   By SANDRA SOBIERAJ Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Bill Bradley challenged Vice President Al Gore
Monday night to demand the president issue an immediate order banning racial
profiling, but Gore shot back in campaign debate, ``I don't think President Bill
Clinton needs a lecture from Sen. Bill Bradley'' on standing up for blacks and
Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
	   In their sixth and final debate before next Monday's kickoff Iowa caucuses,
the two Democratic hopefuls agreed the Confederate flag should come down from
atop the South Carolina statehouse.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore went one step further, saying ``it's only the Republican candidates for
president'' who disagree because they are ``so scared of the extreme right
wing.''
</P>
<P>
	   Both men also agreed that the father of Elian Gonzalez, a 6-year-old Cuban
boy at the center of an international dispute, should come to the United States
to seek custody.
</P>
<P>
	   A number of racially sensitive issues came up in the opening moments of a
televised debate on the federal holiday honoring the late Martin Luther King,
Jr., a ``Black-Brown Forum'' that both men hoped to use to appeal to voters in
other states with a larger minority population than Iowa.
</P>
<P>
	   The proceedings were disrupted briefly by a young woman who stood at her
seat in the audience to pose a question about global warming. As security guards
moved to silence her, the moderator, Travis Smiley of Black Entertainment
Television, quipped, ``I get my 15 minutes (of fame) and this is what happens to
me.''
</P>
<P>
	   Racial profiling is the practice by which some police offers target racial
minorities for traffic stops, and Gore and Bradley both said firmly that they
are against it.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We all know what driving while black is,'' said Bradley, who has made race
relations a cornerstone of his career in public life. ``It is breathing while
black.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 1841 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000117.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush, McCain Battle Over Taxes  </HEADLINE>
   By WALTER R. MEARS AP Special Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Gov. George W. Bush questioned the credibility of Sen.
John McCain's campaign-promised tax cut Monday, while the GOP challenger said
he'd give the breaks to working Americans and end ``special benefit'' favors for
big money interests.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush and McCain renewed at a distance the argument that began when the Texas
governor said in a presidential campaign debate that the senator's proposal
would impose ``a $40 billion tax increase'' on the benefits employers provide
their workers.
</P>
<P>
	   Wrong, an architect of the McCain plan said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Mark Spitzer, a Phoenix tax attorney, said the McCain proposal is to end the
deductions employers can now take on tax-exempt benefits they give their
workers.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It does nothing to the employees,'' said Spitzer, an Arizona state
senator.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain had not disputed Bush's assertion in the Saturday debate in Des
Moines, Iowa, as the governor pointedly noted. But his campaign immediately
denied it was so.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain said later that Bush had mischaracterized his proposal.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They're talking about income taxes,'' his spokesman, Howard Opinsky said.
``We're talking about payroll taxes.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Bush campaign based the governor's assertion on Congressional Research
Service estimates of the revenue loss due to the tax-free treatment of
non-retirement fringe benefits aside from health insurance coverage and child
care, which wouldn't be affected.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush's $40 billion claim reflects those estimates extended for five years
after a new administration is installed. But those numbers are based on taxes
paid by individuals, not their employers.
</P>
<P>
	   Spitzer said the McCain campaign does not have an estimate of the revenues
that would be added by imposing payroll taxes on employers for the value of the
benefits they pay for employees.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The point was, I didn't hear an explanation about the $40 billion benefit
tax increase on workers,'' Bush, in Austin, said in a telephone interview with
The Associated Press. ``There seems to be a tax gap between what his explanation
was in Iowa and what reality is ...
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is an important debate, because it's a debate about the credibility
of tax plans,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush advocates a five-year, $483 billion tax cut, and says the only way to
be certain that projected budget surpluses aren't spent by the government is to
refund most of the money to taxpayers. McCain's alternative is a $237 billion
overall cut, the closing of what he calls tax loopholes to offset part of the
cost, and the commitment of additional budget surpluses to secure the financial
future of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain says Bush would spend more than the projected surpluses, without
putting aside a penny of it for Social Security. The Arizona senator boasted of
a new poll indicating that most Republicans would prefer a smaller tax cut with
more money set aside for Social Security and to pay down the national debt.
</P>
<P>
	   The Time-CNN poll showed 63 percent of Republicans felt that way, 29 percent
wanted more money to go into tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This poll confirms that Republicans agree with me,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
	   The latest round in their tax argument gets into the fine print of the tax
code, dealing with what are called ``employer paid non-retirement fringe
benefits.''
</P>
<P>
	   By the Bush campaign's account, the McCain tax proposal would impose income
taxes on things like employer-subsidized education, commuting costs, discounted
meals and purchases, parking and life insurance.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain said his plan would not do that.
</P>
<P>
	   ``What I'm saying is that the guy who owns the corporation isn't going to
get his tax break for his golf club membership,'' McCain said on CNN. ``He's not
going to get his spa fees written off and he's not going to get free parking.''
</P>
<P>
	   Congress already has barred tax deductions for perks like country club dues.
The IRS code says that there can be no deduction ``for amounts paid or incurred
for membership in any club organized for business, pleasure, recreation or other
social purposes.''
</P>
<P>
	   But Spitzer said there are still loopholes, and McCain wants them closed.
For example, he said, a company can give an executive pricey tickets to a
National Basketball Association game and deduct them as a corporate cost,
although the individual isn't taxed on them.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain told the Rotary Club in Rochester, N.H., that his tax proposal would
be a step toward a flatter, simpler tax code. ``Every time we pass a tax bill,
we put in a special deal, a special benefit for a big-money contributor special
interest,'' McCain said. He said he'd put an end to that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 1843 </TRAILER>
