<HEADLINE> 4-alarm fire raging in Newark  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - A raging, four-alarm fire tore through an industrial
building Monday evening and spread to nearby homes, sending plumes of choking
smoke for miles and forcing the evacuation of about 10 families.
<P>
	   No injuries were immediately reported, Police Department spokesman Matt
Greimel said.
</P>
<P>
	   The block-long commercial building near Interstate 78 and the Irvington
border began burning at approximately 4:30 p.m. It quickly drew firefighters
from surrounding communities, but they were hampered by sub-freezing
temperatures and gusting winds.
</P>
<P>
	   A fire dispatcher said that the building fire had spread to "at least three"
homes in the area.
</P>
<P>
	   New York's WABC-TV reported that several workers escaped the building.
</P>
<P>
	   "I thought we were all going to burn. But we got out OK," Maria Cuevas told
the television station.
</P>
<P>
	   "I just went outside, and I heard two explosions," said Meg Batta, who was
working in a Pathmark supermarket a block and a half from the fire. "There's
heavy black smoke all over here. If the wind shifts, we might have to close."
</P>
<P>
	   Flames were leaping from the roof of the building, which witnesses said was
a candle factory, and heavy plumes of smoke were obscuring motorists' vision on
Route 78.
</P>
<P>
	   "Lord, it was so black you couldn't see a thing," said Myrtle Turner, who
lives two blocks from the fire on Fabyan Place. "There was fire all over. It was
terrible."
</P>
<P>
	   "We saw the flames, and heard sirens and ambulances," added Audrey Anderson,
an employee of The Rainbow Shop, a dress store on Lyons Avenue in Irvington,
also a block and a half from the fire.
</P>
</TEXT>
