<HEADLINE> Group Wants Global Warming Plan  </HEADLINE>
   By KEN THOMAS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Braving an icy 28-degree evening, members of Ozone
Action rallied around their 25-foot inflatable ear of corn outside the scene of
Monday night's Brown-Black Presidential Forum, calling for a plan to combat
global warming.
</P>
<P>
	   Kate Simmons, spokeswoman for the group, which studies global warming, said
the organization was still hoping that one of the candidates -- Vice President
Al Gore or Bill Bradley -- will directly address the issue.
</P>
<P>
	   ``No candidate has presented a detailed plan for action yet,'' Simmons said.
``We've been at this for 2 1/2 weeks. Once we've moved on with Iowa, we'll go
elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
	   The group plans simultaneous events Tuesday in Ames, Cedar Falls and Iowa
City to release a scientific report on global warming.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   As a moderator was about to ask the second question of the debate, a young
woman affiliated with Ozone Action left her seat and walked toward the front of
the auditorium.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I want to know what you're going to do about global warming,'' said Kim
DeFeo, 23, a member of the organizations' Iowa field team.
</P>
<P>
	   She was immediately grabbed by security and escorted out of the auditorium.
Neither Gore nor Bradley had a chance to respond.
</P>
<P>
	   DeFeo later was taken in for questioning by Secret Service agents, who
declined to comment. Police also declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
	   DeFeo apparently had discussed with other group members the possibility of
disrupting the nationally televised debate.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We talked about it and it was a pretty spontaneous thing. She had fire in
her belly and she wanted to see what the candidates would say,'' said Simmons,
the Ozone Action spokeswoman. Simmons, too, was questioned by Secret Service.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Gore and Bradley weren't the only candidates with supporters outside the
debate site.
</P>
<P>
	   Perennial presidential contender Lyndon LaRouche, 78, had three supporters
on hand, one of whom carried a large, neon orange sign that said: ``Dump Gore's
Dixiecrat Racism. Vote LaRouche, The Third Party Candidate.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bob Baker, who works in LaRouche's Leesburg, Va., office, said the candidate
is the only one who recognizes that there is a severe financial meltdown around
the world. Baker said LaRouche is the only one who can mobilize this nation as
well as protect U.S. farmers.
</P>
<P>
	   Cecil Conry, who farms near Elliott in southwest Iowa, said LaRouche is
taken seriously, but is ignored by the media and crowded out by the Democratic
establishment.
</P>
<P>
	   LaRouche has filed paperwork to run in the New Hampshire primary Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   State Rep. Rebecca Reynolds said she favored Gore earlier in the campaign
but switched to Bradley.
</P>
<P>
	   ``His health care plan is second to none,'' said Reynolds, a registered
nurse.
</P>
<P>
	   On campaign finance reform, she said, ``I've seen firsthand the horrors that
accompany raising campaign dollars, and I support what he hopes to do.''
</P>
<P>
	   As for his chances in Iowa's caucuses next week, Reynolds said: ``I'm
constantly amazed by the high number of Democrats getting on board to support
Bill Bradley.''
</P>
<P>
	   Marissa Ollison of Des Moines said she's supporting Bradley because of his
support ``for all people, all sexual preferences.''
</P>
<P>
	   She said she's not sure how Bradley will do at the caucuses.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I just know how I'm going to vote. I'll support Bill Bradley. I don't know
what the rest of Iowa will do,'' Ollison said.
</P>
