<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Radioactive Cargo Goes Through Canal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) -- A ship carrying 44 tons of nuclear waste safely
crossed the Panama Canal on Monday. It was the first such cargo to make the
passage since the United States ceded the waterway to Panama.
</P>
<P>
	   Independent groups had expressed concern that terrorist or extremist groups
could attempt to board the British ship, especially since Panama has no army to
protect the canal. The country relies on a national police force for security.
</P>
<P>
	   But the Pacific Swan, carrying waste from a French nuclear plant to Japan,
completed the eight-hour crossing without incident early Monday, said Jorge Luis
Quijano, director of maritime operations for the canal.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The crossing was peaceful and well organized,'' Quijano said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Washington-based Nuclear Control Institute had expressed concern about
the trip, noting that environmental activists with Greenpeace boarded the
Pacific Swan two years ago just as it was about to enter the canal.
</P>
<P>
	   Panama has insisted that is it ready to protect the canal, which was handed
over by the United States on Dec. 31.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
