<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Famed Tiger May Have Been Killed  </HEADLINE>
   By ARTHUR MAX Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Forest officials have recovered a pelt that may
have come from Sita, a wild tiger that once graced the cover of National
Geographic magazine.
</P>
<P>
	   The 18-year-old female has not been seen in the Bandhavgarh National Park
since October 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   The skin, found in the home of a man who has a record of poaching and theft,
bore marks similar to Sita, but a positive identification could not be made,
said Ranjit Talwar of the World Wildlife Fund.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Whether it is Sita or not, the fact is a tiger skin as been found. That
means all is not well,'' Talwar, an expert on tigers, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   India loses dozens of tigers to poachers every year. Bandhavgarh, in the
central state of Madhya Pradesh, is known as one of the best parks for seeing
tigers.
</P>
<P>
	   While 100,000 tigers roamed freely at the turn of the 20th century, only an
estimated 5,000 to 7,000 exist in the wild today, about half in India.
</P>
<P>
	   Sita was a prolific breeder who had six documented litters. Of her 18 known
cubs, only seven survived. She was 10 1/2 feet long.
</P>
<P>
	   In the December 1997 issue of National Geographic, writer Geoffrey C. Ward
described his first sighting of Sita as she slept over the remains of a deer she
had killed.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Nothing seemed to faze her -- nothing, until a rufous-and-white tree pie
smaller than a North American magpie fluttered down onto her kill. She was up
and fully awake in a millisecond, swatting at the terrified bird with one
enormous forepaw and roaring so loudly the sky seemed to split.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 1913 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
