<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.J. Hero Recuperating After Crash  </HEADLINE>
   By WAYNE PARRY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The car came toward them so fast that all Ursula
Webster could do was shove her 8-year-old son out of its path.
</P>
<P>
	   She recalls the thud as the vehicle struck her, sending her flying into the
air outside the London residence of British Prime Minister Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
	   ``As I was going up, I'm thinking, `I'm dying, this is it, my life is
ending,' and I could actually feel my bones breaking,'' Mrs. Webster said Monday
in a telephone interview from her hospital bed in Livingston. ``But when I hit
the ground and was still conscious, I knew it wasn't nearly that bad.''
</P>
<P>
	   The British tabloids are hailing the New Jersey woman as ``The Heroine of
Downing Street'' for saving her son from the speeding car that crashed into the
gates outside 10 Downing Street on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   She, her husband, David, and their three sons were sightseeing there because
they have virtually the same address in Livingston -- 10 Downing Place.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Webster returned home Sunday and had surgery Monday to fix her
shattered leg. She was in satisfactory condition at St. Barnabas Medical Center
following the operation to insert a stainless steel rod to stabilize her broken
right tibia, said her surgeon, Dr. Michael H. Rieber.
</P>
<P>
	   At Mrs. Webster's request, the music of New Jersey rocker Bruce Springsteen
was played during the operation.
</P>
<P>
	   She faces four to six months of rehabilitation, she said, and predicted it
would be difficult with three active children.
</P>
<P>
	   ``But I keep thinking this could have been so much worse,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
	   The son Mrs. Webster pushed out of the way, Andrew, was brushed by the car's
door and Alex, 6, was grazed by the wing mirror. Peter, 3, and her husband were
not struck.
</P>
<P>
	   A man has been charged with causing grievous bodily harm and dangerous
driving, London police said. He was granted bail Monday and ordered to return to
court Jan. 31.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 1913 </TRAILER>
