<HEADLINE> Motorola Earnings More Than Triple  </HEADLINE>
    By MARIO FOX Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SCHAUMBURG, Ill. (AP) -- Motorola Inc. on Monday reported earnings for the
final quarter of 1999 more than tripled from the year ago period, beating
analysts expectations as demand for digital wireless telephones surged.
</P>
<P>
	   Fourth-quarter earnings excluding special items were $514 million, or 82
cents per share, compared with $159 million, or 26 cents per share, in the 1998
period. Analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial were expecting the
company to earn 81 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
	   "Basically, it's right on target," Pete Peterson, an analyst in San
Francisco for Prudential Volpe Technology, said. "They beat the (Wall) Street's
prediction by a penny so the Street will look favorably at this."
</P>
<P>
	   Motorola, based in this suburb northwest of Chicago, reported sales of $8.5
billion in the fourth quarter, up 2 percent from $8.3 billion a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
	   Net income for the fourth quarter was $349 million, or 56 cents per share,
compared with $159 million, or 26 cents per share, in the fourth quarter of
1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Earnings for the year were up 279 percent to $1.2 billion, or $1.94 a share,
up from $317 million, or 53 cents a share, in 1998. Sales rose nearly 9 percent
to $30 billion from $27.6 billion in all of 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Several low-growth Motorola businesses have been sold in the past 12 months
and the company recently bought General Instrument Corp., maker of cable-boxes,
for $17 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   "This quarter culminates a year in which we achieved significant improvement
in financial performance from our digital wireless phone and semiconductor
businesses and benefited from our corporate-wide restructuring actions," Robert
L. Growney, president and chief operating officer, said in the earnings
statement. "We have also made investments and formed promising alliances in
third-generation wireless, Internet, broadband and semiconductor technologies."
</P>
<P>
	   The communications and equipment maker appears to have rebounded well from a
rough stretch in which it underwent a billion-dollar restructuring and laid off
24,000 people in late 1998 and early 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   The company said sales of wireless phones increased significantly during
1999, especially in Asia. The increased demand is expected to continue into the
first and second quarters of this year, the company said.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is very bullish," Peterson said. "They were under the gun before, they
promised to make changes, they made the changes and we are seeing the results,"
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 1958 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
