<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton meets with Sharpton on King Day  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - The long-awaited meeting between Hillary Rodham Clinton
and the Rev. Al Sharpton took place Monday at a Martin Luther King Jr.
celebration, but the only person who took any flak during the event was somebody
who wasn't there - Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
<P>
	   "The only mayor of a big city that could not go into an African-American
community on Martin Luther King Day is the mayor of this city," Sharpton said.
</P>
<P>
	   The mayor's spokeswoman, Sunny Mindel, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani held a prayer breakfast at Gracie Mansion Monday morning and was
one of several Republican officials who attended a dinner Monday night given by
the Congress of Racial Equality, which is led by the conservative black activist
Roy Innes.
</P>
<P>
	   The mayor skipped a King tribute at the Brooklyn Academy of Music that he
has attended for the past few years because Mrs. Clinton decided to attend it.
</P>
<P>
	   "It became a political event once they invited Mrs. Clinton," Ms. Mindel
said. She added that the mayor spent the day working on the city budget.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Clinton also spoke at the Convent Avenue Baptist Church in Harlem. At
all three events, she recalled having met King when she was 15 in 1963, having
been brought with her church youth group to hear him speak in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
	   "He took my hand and shook it and I felt my life would never be the same,"
she said, adding that King's stirring speech that night - titled "Remaining
Awake Through a Great Revolution" - inspired her to "dedicate my life to public
service."
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Clinton noted there has been progress in blacks achieving equality, but
added: "There is still a need for affirmative action." She quoted her husband,
President Clinton, saying of affirmative action, "We need to mend it, not end
it."
</P>
<P>
	   She was accompanied to Sharpton's headquarters by former Mayors David
Dinkins and Ed Koch, along with a number of other elected Democratic officials.
The audience of about 300 repeatedly interrupted her remarks with cheers,
applause and occasional cries of "Run Hillary run!"
</P>
<P>
	   Afterwards, she met privately with Sharpton and several others, including
the parents of Amadou Diallo, the unarmed African immigrant who was killed by
four white police officers in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
	   "I had a few private moments with them and expressed my personal sympathy
and condolences and shared my hope that justice is done," Mrs. Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
	   The trial of the officers who killed Diallo is set to begin soon in Albany.
It was moved from the Bronx because an appellate court concluded the officers
could not get a fair trial there. Sharpton and U.S. Rep. Charles Rangel of
Harlem have asked the U.S. Justice Department to consider a federal
investigation of the case.
</P>
<P>
	   "If there is a role for the federal government, I would certainly encourage
and urge that that would occur," said Mrs. Clinton. But she said it was too
early to say whether federal intervention is merited.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Clinton did not agree on every issue raised at the Sharpton event, at
one point defending sanctions against Iraq despite murmurs of disapproval.
</P>
<P>
	   "She did very well," Sharpton said afterwards. "She did not show any
reluctance at all to deal with the issues."
</P>
<P>
	   Shortly before Mrs. Clinton entered Sharpton's headquarters, another
speaker, Rev. Charles Norris, said he had missed one of King's demonstrations
because he was working. Referring to his former employers, Norris said: "Miller
No. 1 was a Jew. Miller No. 2 was a Jew. I was then employed by yet another Jew
by the name of Jesus ... and will not be fired until he thinks it's necessary."
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Clinton later told reporters that before she arrived, "I heard that one
of the speakers made some divisive comments, which I soundly reject."
</P>
<P>
	   Sharpton said he had not heard Norris' remarks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-17-00 2000 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
