<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Monday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press Note: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Why Canada Shipped U.S. Plutonium by Air
<TEXT>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- Federal government departments urged that a controversial
shipment of U.S. plutonium be quietly shipped to a research reactor near Ottawa
by air, not road as first planned.
</P>
<P>
	   The surprise flight Friday from Sault Ste. Marie, Ontario, to Atomic Energy
of Canada's site at Chalk River, Ontario, took protesters off guard. It was to
have been moved by highway despite promises from environmental activists and
First Nations to block its path.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We, quite frankly, weren't thinking of air,'' said AECL spokesman Larry
Shewchuk. ``That wasn't our choice to go to air.''
</P>
<P>
	   The change, approved Jan. 10 by Transport Canada, was made ``because the
government asked us to based on the feedback they got from the public,''
Shewchuk said.
</P>
<P>
	   Flying plutonium is outlawed in the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   But Friday's flight broke no Canadian regulations, said John Read, director
general of the Transport Dangerous Goods section of Transport Canada.
</P>
<P>
	   The fuel, along with another shipment expected from Russia in the spring, is
to be used in tests to recycle bombs into reactor fuel.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
Rothmans Denies Role in 1990s Cigarette Smuggling
</P>
<P>
	   TORONTO (AP) -- Rothmans, Canada's second-largest tobacco manufacturer,
strongly denied Monday that it played a role in tobacco smuggling in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We are very concerned about contraband,'' John McDonald, spokesman for
Rothmans, Benson and Hedges said after an anti-smoking activist added heat to a
morning shareholders' meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We made the government aware of our trade practices and there's nothing
being said that suggests any improper behaviour on the part of RBH.''
</P>
<P>
	   Garfield Mahood of the Non-Smoker's Rights Association was silenced before
he could utter a question at the gathering, during which a motion was passed to
amalgamate two holding companies and split the company's stock.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If it doesn't relate to this motion, then we are not going to discuss
it,'' company chairman Senator William Kelly stated when Mahood stood to ask a
question.
</P>
<P>
	   Les Thompson, a former executive at RJR-Macdonald who was convicted last
year in connection with cigarette smuggling, has said all three of Canada's
major tobacco companies were involved.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
Ontario PM Seeks Facts on Emergency Rooms
</P>
<P>
	   TORONTO (AP) -- Ontario Premier Mike Harris is promising to find out whether
lives are being lost as a result of what critics call an escalating crisis in
emergency rooms across the province.
</P>
<P>
	   Harris made the promise Monday amid lingering questions about 18-year-old
asthmatic Joshua Fleuelling, who died in hospital early Saturday after he went
into cardiac arrest.
</P>
<P>
	   The 18-minute ambulance ride Fleuelling endured while in the grips of a
severe asthma attack is quickly becoming a flashpoint for a growing fear across
Canada that cash-strapped emergency rooms have been pushed past the breaking
point.
</P>
<P>
	   Paramedics were forced to take Fleuelling to Markham-Stouffville Hospital
because the closest hospital, Scarborough Grace, was on critical-care bypass and
closed to ambulance patients.
</P>
<P>
	   Ontario deputy chief coroner Jim Cairns has said his office will await the
results of an autopsy before deciding whether to proceed with a coroner's
inquest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 2016 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000117.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Plutonium Flight Protested  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Local officials and environmental groups are protesting a
Canadian government agency's decision to fly weapons-grade plutonium across 300
miles of southern Canada.
</P>
<P>
	   In a surprise move Friday, 4.2 ounces of plutonium was transported by
helicopter from Sault Ste. Marie on the U.S. border to Atomic Energy of Canada
Ltd.'s plant in Chalk River, Ontario.
</P>
<P>
	   The agency originally had planned to ship the plutonium by truck. But unable
to reach a compromise with groups who were planning protests along the shipping
route, it instead flew the shipment without making any public announcement.
</P>
<P>
	   The plutonium arrived safely on Friday morning, but that didn't make critics
of the shipment any happier.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The plutonium overflight was a completely unnecessary risk,'' Elizabeth
May of the Sierra Club of Canada said Monday. Sault Ste. Marie Mayor Steve
Butland said he was never informed about the helicopter transport, and New
Democrat Party environment critic Peter Mancini called the move ``a blatant
disregard for the concerns and safety of Canadians.''
</P>
<P>
	   Federal officials said the shipment broke no Canadian regulations.
</P>
<P>
	   The shipment was part of the Parallex Project, a joint American-Russian
experiment to determine whether commercial nuclear reactors in Canada can use
material from decommissioned Russian nuclear weapons as fuel.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. officials said the experiment was crucial to U.S. efforts to help
Russia dismantle nuclear weapons. They insisted it would be a one-time event,
but critics said they believed it would be the first of many shipments of
nuclear material through the United States and Ontario.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 2021 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
