<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela: Conflict With U.S. Eases  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Venezuelan officials said Monday that tensions had
been eased in the conflict with the United States over a U.S. offer to send
troops to help with flood relief.
</P>
<P>
	   The conflict began last week, when U.S. officials ordered a U.S. Navy ship
that was en route to Venezuela to reverse course after Venezuelan President Hugo
Chavez said he did not want the U.S. troops in his country. U.S. officials said
they were dismayed by Chavez's announcement, since Venezuela's defense minister
had requested the help in a letter Dec. 24.
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday, U.S. Ambassador John Maisto met with Chavez. Afterwards, Maisto
said the United States would still collaborate with Venezuela in the disaster
recovery. Venezuelan Foreign Minister Jose Vicente Rangel told reporters the
problem ``has been overcome.''
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S. forces, though, still will not be going.
</P>
<P>
	   Some 450 Marine and Navy engineers had been expected to help rebuild a
coastal road damaged by Dec. 15 flooding that killed thousands of Venezuelans.
</P>
<P>
	   Rangel said Venezuela also rejected similar offers from other countries.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We said the same thing to Brazil when they wanted to send a group of
soldiers,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 2043 </TRAILER>
