<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Slip  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks fell early Tuesday on profit-taking following
sharp gains the previous day. The dollar edged lower against the yen.
</P>
<P>
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 217.11 points, or 1.12
percent, to 19,220.12 points in the first 30 minutes of trading. On Monday, the
average rose 480.68 points, or 2.54 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar bought 104.87 yen, down 0.31 yen from late Monday in Tokyo but
above its late London level of 104.78 yen. Financial markets in New York were
closed Monday for a national holiday.
</P>
<P>
	   On the stock market, prices started lower as investors locked in profits a
day after the Nikkei closed at its highest level in 29 months.
</P>
<P>
	   Monday's finish of 19,437.23 points was the index's highest close since Aug.
8, 1997, when it ended the day at 19,604.46.
</P>
<P>
	   Traders said information and telecommunications-related issues were among
early losers. Some players were taking a cautious position as they continued to
watch the dollar's direction against the yen.
</P>
<P>
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section was down 7.82 points, or 0.46 percent, to 1,674.15. The TOPIX closed up
33.73 points, or 2.05 percent, the day before.
</P>
<P>
	   In currency dealings, the dollar moved in a narrow range in early Asian
trading Tuesday after financial markets in New York took Monday off.
</P>
<P>
	   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 106.18 yen, down from 106.80 yen
late Monday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell to 1.7650
percent from Monday's finish of 1.7800 percent. Its price rose 0.13 point to
100.30.
</P>
</TEXT>
