<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congo Loyalists Break Rebel Blockade  </HEADLINE>
   By KAMANGA MUTOND Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) -- Troops loyal to Congo President Laurent Kabila broke
through rebel lines, ending a two-month siege on a strategic government-held
town, the warring sides said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The breakthrough came early Sunday in Ikela, 400 miles northeast of the
capital, Kinshasa. The fighting prompted neighboring Rwanda to call for U.N.
peacekeepers to prevent an outright collapse of Congo's fraying cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
	   Kabila and his allies, Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia, signed a cease-fire in
July with Rwanda and Uganda, the countries that back Congo's rebels. The rebel
factions signed the pact the following month. But fighting has flared on several
fronts since then, and the warring sides frequently accuse each other of
violating the pact.
</P>
<P>
	   Congolese rebels encircled Ikela in November and cut off the main overland
and river supply routes. The siege had kept 2,000 troops loyal to Kabila,
including 800 Zimbabweans, trapped in the city.
</P>
<P>
	   The breakthrough allowed government forces to provide the troops supplies
and reinforcements after months of shortages, Congo army spokesman Leon Richard
Kasonga said.
</P>
<P>
	   The government alliance had no ``ambition to gain more territory,'' Kasonga
said. He said the troops were only preserving positions held before the
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
	   Rwandan state minister Patrick Mazimhaka said the situation in Ikela
underscored the urgent need for U.N. peacekeepers. The United Nations has
considered proposals for a 25,000-member U.N. peacekeeping force in the region,
but some Western powers have expressed fears the situation is too unstable for
peacekeepers to be effective.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 2105 </TRAILER>
