<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DEBATE NOTEBOOK: On icy evening, statements sought on global  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) - Braving an icy 28-degree evening, members of
Ozone Action rallied around their 25-foot inflatable ear of corn outside the
scene of Monday night's Brown-Black Presidential Forum, calling for a plan to
combat global warming.
<P>
	   Kate Simmons, spokeswoman for the group, which studies global warming, said
the organization was still hoping that one of the candidates - Vice President Al
Gore or Bill Bradley - will directly address the issue.
</P>
<P>
	   "No candidate has presented a detailed plan for action yet," Simmons said.
"We've been at this for 2 1/2 weeks. Once we've moved on with Iowa, we'll go
elsewhere."
</P>
<P>
	   The group plans simultaneous events Tuesday in Ames, Cedar Falls and Iowa
City to release a scientific report on global warming.
</P>
<P>
	   ----
</P>
<P>
	   As a moderator was about to ask the second question of the debate, a young
woman affiliated with Ozone Action left her seat and walked toward the front of
the auditorium.
</P>
<P>
	   "I want to know what you're going to do about global warming," said Kim
DeFeo, 23, a member of the organizations' Iowa field team.
</P>
<P>
	   She was immediately grabbed by security and escorted out of the auditorium.
Neither Gore nor Bradley had a chance to respond.
</P>
<P>
	   DeFeo later was taken in for questioning by Secret Service agents, who
declined to comment. Police also declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
	   DeFeo apparently had discussed with other group members the possibility of
disrupting the nationally televised debate.
</P>
<P>
	   "We talked about it and it was a pretty spontaneous thing. She had fire in
her belly and she wanted to see what the candidates would say," said Simmons,
the Ozone Action spokeswoman. Simmons, too, was questioned by Secret Service.
</P>
<P>
	   ----
</P>
<P>
	   Gore and Bradley weren't the only candidates with supporters outside the
debate site.
</P>
<P>
	   Perennial presidential contender Lyndon LaRouche, 78, had three supporters
on hand, one of whom carried a large, neon orange sign that said: "Dump Gore's
Dixiecrat Racism. Vote LaRouche, The Third Party Candidate."
</P>
<P>
	   Bob Baker, who works in LaRouche's Leesburg, Va., office, said the candidate
is the only one who recognizes that there is a severe financial meltdown around
the world. Baker said LaRouche is the only one who can mobilize this nation as
well as protect U.S. farmers.
</P>
<P>
	   Cecil Conry, who farms near Elliott in southwest Iowa, said LaRouche is
taken seriously, but is ignored by the media and crowded out by the Democratic
establishment.
</P>
<P>
	   LaRouche has filed paperwork to run in the New Hampshire primary Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
	   ----
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley's wife Ernestine was seen kissing and hugging people before the
debate.
</P>
<P>
	   A man who was pecked on the cheek wouldn't talk to reporters, but a woman
next to him, swept up in a big bear hug, shared her story.
</P>
<P>
	   Julie Turner, from Ridgewood, N.J., said she was Bill Bradley's first
volunteer in New Jersey. She began working on his presidential campaign in
January 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm old enough to remember government when you believed in what you could
do and how you could contribute to your country," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   To emphasize her point, she exclaimed: "Look, I have gray hair."
</P>
<P>
	   Today's generation, she said, doesn't share her feelings.
</P>
<P>
	   "Kids today don't have that. They don't trust government. Bill Bradley could
rebuild that trust," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   ----
</P>
<P>
	   Quincy Suthers, 56, a Gore supporter from Des Moines, wasn't too impressed
upon seeing NBA Hall of Famer Bill Russell in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
	   Russell was in town campaigning for Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
	   "Bill Russell really means nothing. What does he know about government?"
Suthers said. "He's just a basketball player. I like him, but he's just a
basketball player."
</P>
<P>
	   By contrast, Suthers said, "Gore brought people actually running this
country."
</P>
<P>
	   On hand for the vice president were Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, Labor
Secretary Alexis Herman and Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater.
</P>
<P>
	   "Instead of selling the steak, Bradley's trying to sell his smell," said
Suthers, who added that he thought this was the most spirited debate so far.
"Gore brought out the meat in this discussion."
</P>
<P>
	   ----
</P>
<P>
	   Russell strode into the media filing center with Bradley after the debate
and held an impromptu news conference with reporters.
</P>
<P>
	   "I suggested to him when he was in the Senate that he give me a call if he
was going to run for president," Russell said of Bradley.
</P>
<P>
	   Russell, who won 11 NBA championships with the Boston Celtics, said he first
met Bradley when he had completed his days as a basketball player at Princeton.
</P>
<P>
	   He always suspected that Bradley might run for president, but back then he
"was sizing him up as a player."
</P>
<P>
	   "Bill Bradley is my friend, and I'd like to see him be president," Russell
said. "I have nothing bad or ill to say about the other candidates."
</P>
<P>
	   ---
</P>
<P>
	   Associated Press writer Becky Bohrer contributed to this report
</P>
</TEXT>
