<DOCNO> APW20000117.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Campaign contributions out of Hollywood skyrocket  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   LOS ANGELES (AP) - Hollywood took a beating last year from Washington,
but it kept on giving - with campaign contributions skyrocketing.
<P>
	   Donors already have pumped more than $1.6 million into the coffers of the
four leading presidential candidates - nearly twice the $901,969 that the top
four money getters collected for the two-year 1996 campaign cycle - and the
first primary is still not here. Two Republicans are getting a lot of the
industry's wealth this year, following the road well worn by Democrats.
</P>
<P>
	   Andy Spahn, of DreamWorks SKG, who advises Steven Spielberg, Jeffrey
Katzenberg and David Geffen on political donations, says, "Essentially you are
talking about people who have done quite well who are creative and passionate
and who are giving back."
</P>
<P>
	   Indeed, Hollywood is well known for its political largess. Barbra Streisand
is a major Clinton fund-raiser. Celebrity couples like Goldie Hawn and Kurt
Russell chip in $25,000 to $100,000 and mix with politicians at Beverly Hills
mansions. The DreamWorks partners regularly are hosts for Democratic Party
soirees.
</P>
<P>
	   But what about the tough talk from Washington after the Columbine shootings?
Analysts and industry figures differ over whether this season's rise in
contributions is Hollywood's way of buying insurance to try to protect against
future verbal attacks.
</P>
<P>
	   President Clinton blasted the industry for contributing to a culture of
violence after two teen-agers gunned down their classmates at Columbine.
</P>
<P>
	   Senators exhorted industry representatives to sign a code of conduct
limiting sexual and violent images in their work and sought investigations into
whether Hollywood targeted youths with violent images and products.
</P>
<P>
	   "There was some real anger over the scapegoating of Hollywood by
Washington," Spahn said. "It's not as clear how that plays out on a partisan
level - some of the attacks were coming from both parties."
</P>
<P>
	   Prominent Hollywood Democrats have crossed party lines this election season,
suggesting they may be working to see that whoever wins considers the industry's
concerns. There is a $1,000 per candidate federal contribution limit.
</P>
<P>
	   Geffen, one of Hollywood's most prominent Clinton backers and a supporter of
Vice President Al Gore, gave the maximum donation to both Gore - and to Sen.
John McCain, the Arizona Republican. Norman Lear, writer and director of shows
like "All in the Family," "Good Times" and "The Jeffersons," gave $1,000 each to
Gore, former Sen. Bill Bradley and McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   Neither Geffen nor Lear donated to a Republican presidential candidate in
1992 or 1996.
</P>
<P>
	   Some donors say they're giving to several candidates as a way of encouraging
the debate of ideas generated by multiple candidates. Lear's political adviser
Lara Bergthold said he believes "the more voices the better."
</P>
<P>
	   Donors in the television, film and music industries already had given Gore
$642,865 through last Sept. 1, according to campaign finance reports covering
the period starting Jan. 1, 1999. Republican Gov. George W. Bush took in
$488,327 for the same period.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley collected $328,524 and McCain made $180,938, a strong Hollywood
showing for a No. 2 Republican candidate.
</P>
<P>
	   Entertainment industry donations comprise a small fraction of the
candidates' overall take, but they can bring benefits beyond the actual dollars.
Celebrity support attracts media attention that can translate into help from
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
	   Hollywood insiders are quick to point out that donations in other industries
also are up this year, indicating that other factors aside from Hollywood's
self-interest may be at play.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts note the compressed primary season and the presence of multiple
candidates and no incumbent. The economy is going well, freeing money to donate
while contribution caps have stayed the same.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think they are making enough money that $1,000 is not that much to them,"
Bergthold said of the Hollywood donors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-17-00 2115 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000117.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Physicist worked with Fermi on early A-bomb experiments  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ITHACA, N.Y. (AP) - Robert Rathbun Wilson, an influential nuclear
physicist who was a leader in the Manhattan Project, died Sunday.
<P>
	   He was 85.
</P>
<P>
	   Wilson's death at a senior residence in Ithaca was caused by complications
of a stroke he suffered last year, according to Cornell University, where he
researched and taught.
</P>
<P>
	   By 1940, he earned a Ph.D. from the University of California, Berkeley, and
only two years later was collaborating with Enrico Fermi at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology on experiments that would lead to the atomic bomb.
Wilson's job was designing particle accelerators.
</P>
<P>
	   "No one was more aware of the technical subtlety of accelerators, no one
more ingenious in practical design, no one paid more attention to their
aesthetic qualities," physicist Bruce McDaniel said of Wilson, in a statement
released by Cornell. "He thought of accelerator builders as the contemporary
equivalent of the builders of the great cathedrals in France and Italy, but it
was the physics potential that came first."
</P>
<P>
	   The work at MIT was a precursor to the secretive World War II effort known
as the Manhattan Project. Wilson invented an electromechanical method for
separating uranium isotopes that became known as the Isotron method, according
to Cornell.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1943, Wilson and colleagues from Princeton moved a cyclotron, which
smashed atoms, to Los Alamos, New Mexico. There he headed the Experimental
Nuclear Physics Division.
</P>
<P>
	   Two years later, the atomic bomb was dropped over Hiroshima, Japan, and
killed 140,000 people.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1947, Wilson joined the physics faculty at Cornell. Its Wilson Synchotron
Laboratory was named for him.
</P>
<P>
	   Wilson also served as director of the National Accelerator Laboratory in
Batavia, Ill., which, at four-miles-long, was the largest-ever physics facility.
He was Fermilab's director until 1978.
</P>
<P>
	   Wilson was born March 4, 1914 in Frontier, Wyo.
</P>
<P>
	   He was an amateur sculptor and his artwork is on display at Princeton and
Cornell.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite reaching the top of his highly technical field, he maintained a
simple wit about his work.
</P>
<P>
	   In a February 1986 Science Digest article, he recalled a time when
physicists did not know the scores of subatomic particles his machines would
reveal.
</P>
<P>
	   "We had only electrons and protons, and you could put those together into
atoms in various ways and make the whole universe," he said. "It was a very
simple theory that even a dope could understand. I decided then that I wanted to
go into physics."
</P>
<P>
	   Survivors include his wife of 59 years, Jane Wilson, three sons, four
grandchildren and a sister.
</P>
<P>
	   Funeral arrangements were incomplete Monday evening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-17-00 2115 </TRAILER>
