<HEADLINE> Spanish Leader Calls for Election  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain (AP) -- Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar on Monday called
general elections for March 12, paving the way for his likely return to power.
</P>
<P>
	   The popular center-right politician made the announcement after a special
cabinet meeting and confirmed a date that had already been widely expected.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In 1996, the Popular Party proposed big targets and now the task we
started must continue,'' Aznar told a press conference. ``I will ask Spaniards
again for their confidence.''
</P>
<P>
	   Recent opinion polls have been unanimous in predicting a victory for Aznar's
Popular Party, but by a narrow margin that promises anything but clear sailing
in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
	   Under Aznar, the Popular Party won its first general election in 1996 but
fell short of an outright majority, taking 156 seats in the 350-seat lower
house. Poll results published recently have indicated Aznar's party could
improve to 174 seats this time, which would still be just short of a majority.
</P>
</TEXT>
