<HEADLINE> McCain: Defends U.S. Foreign Aid  </HEADLINE>
   By ANN S. KIM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   GILFORD, N.H. (AP) -- Sen. John McCain defended U.S. foreign aid Monday and
said encouraging democracy in other countries can help prevent terrorism.
</P>
<P>
	   The Republican presidential candidate met with 150 people early in the
morning at a fire station in Gilford, where the wind chill was well below zero.
</P>
<P>
	   Bill Akerley, a 38-year-old independent, asked why the United States spends
money on foreign aid when many Americans could use the help.
</P>
<P>
	   Switching subjects, McCain said tax cuts would make things easier for
Americans because ending foreign aid would not provide much money to address
domestic problems.
</P>
<P>
	   He also said some U.S. foreign policies do work, and that by encouraging
democracy worldwide the United States can help prevent terrorism abroad and on
U.S. soil.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's in our interest not to have conflicts arise all over the world,''
McCain replied.
</P>
<P>
	   At a meeting with the Rochester Rotary Club later in the day, a voter asked
what the United States can do to help solve human rights abuses and other
problems abroad.
</P>
<P>
	   While stressing that the United States is the world's greatest power, McCain
said that power must be used judiciously and that military action often is
counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
	   He said the United States cannot bring an end to the AIDS epidemic in
Africa, but it can help draw attention to it and can look at other ways of
alleviating it.
</P>
<P>
	   Later, McCain, a Navy veteran, told several dozen people in the living room
of a Stratham home that the nearby Portsmouth Naval Shipyard, a major area
employer, should be considered in any new round of military base closings.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The Portsmouth Naval Shipyard must be in play as the five bases in Arizona
must be in play,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   His staff called it another example of straight talk, of him telling people
what they don't want to hear.
</P>
<P>
	   Later, McCain told a reporter that he didn't want to see any bases closed,
``but every military expert -- Colin Powell and Norman Schwartzkopf -- will tell
you we have too many bases.
</P>
</TEXT>
