<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Monday, Jan. 17, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore, Bradley Clash on Racial Issues
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- In their sixth and final debate before next
Monday's kickoff Iowa caucuses, presidential hopefuls Bill Bradley and Vice
President Al Gore addressed several racial issues today in hopes of appealing to
voters in other states with a large minority population. Perched on stools on a
debate stage in Iowa's capital city, both men said firmly they oppose racial
profiling, the practice by which some police target racial minorities for
traffic stops. Bradley challenged Gore to demand the Clinton administration
issue an immediate order banning racial profiling.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gay-Military Issue Ads To Be Aired
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Striking back on the issue of gays in the military, a gay
rights group is unveiling a new ad that goes after Republicans who would keep
them out of the armed forces. The ads, being shown tomorrow in New Hampshire and
Iowa, respond to a campaign by the Republican National Committee. The group
accuses Republicans of exploiting Vice President Al Gore's position on the issue
and hopes its own ad campaign will help focus attention on the merits of his
views -- that gays should be allowed to serve openly in the military.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Congo Loyalists Break Rebel Blockade
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) -- Troops loyal to Congo President Laurent Kabila broke
through rebel lines, ending a two-month siege on a strategic government-held
town, the warring sides said. The breakthrough came early Sunday in Ikela, 400
miles northeast of the capital, Kinshasa. The fighting prompted neighboring
Rwanda to call for U.N. peacekeepers to prevent an outright collapse of Congo's
fraying cease-fire. Kabila and his allies, Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia, signed
a cease-fire in July with Rwanda and Uganda, the countries that back Congo's
rebels. The rebel factions signed the pact the following month. But fighting has
flared on several fronts since then, and the warring sides frequently accuse
each other of violating the pact.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Several Hurt in Israeli Explosion
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   HADERA, Israel (AP) -- A pipe bomb hidden in a trash can exploded today at a
park in the Israeli coastal town of Hadera, wounding 21 people in what Israeli
officials said was an attempt to derail Mideast peacemaking. Most injuries were
minor. The blast came during a critical phase in Israel's peace talks with the
Palestinians and Syria. The Clinton administration was forced Monday to put off
scheduled peace talks between Israel and Syria amid sharp disagreement between
the two sides over a projected Israeli pullback on the Golan Heights.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Aims To Improve AIDS Funds
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton will ask Congress for $175 million for
AIDS treatment and prevention programs in his 2001 budget proposal,
administration officials said today. Clinton wants $125 million for Ryan White
Comprehensive AIDS Resources Act grants. The 10-year-old program, provides money
for health clinics treating low-income AIDS patients and for training for those
caring for HIV-infected individuals. The president also will ask Congress to
approve $50 million to fund state and local AIDS prevention programs
administered by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. It's the most
the administration has ever sought for prevention, which AIDS groups say is
woefully underfunded by the government.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Slip
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks fell Tuesday on profit-taking following sharp
gains the previous day. The Nikkei shed 217.11 points to 19,220.12 in early
trading. Financial markets in New York were closed Monday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Santana Wins Best-Album Award
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Carlos Santana's band won best-album honors at tonight's
American Music Awards for "Supernatural," a comeback that put the rock guitar
maestro on top of the charts for the first time in his 30-year career. Santana
took the stage to a standing ovation. The show also included an Award of Merit
for Gloria Estefan, who was honored with a musical tribute.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pack To Make Sherman Coach
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Mike Sherman, the Seattle Seahawks' offensive
coordinator and a former Green Bay assistant, will be hired as the new coach of
the Packers, a team source told The Associated Press. Sherman likely will be
introduced at a news conference tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by PAULINE MILLARD
</P>
