<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fires, Flooding Hit South Africa  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) -- Army troops and air force helicopters helped
fight wildfires Monday that destroyed more than 50 homes and left a thick pall
of smoke over Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
	   While the fires burned for the third day in dry conditions in the western
part of the country, much of the rest of South Africa was drenched with
torrential rains.
</P>
<P>
	   In rural Northern Province, a rain-soaked hut collapsed Monday, killing a
4-year-old girl and injuring her 7-year-old sister, the South African Press
Association reported. Days of steady rain in central, northern and eastern
regions caused flooding that closed roads.
</P>
<P>
	   In the Cape Town area, fires hit beachside towns, a township and surrounding
wine country. Many of the blazes were sparked by smoldering cigarettes or
carelessly maintained barbecue fires combined with very hot, dry weather,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   Weary firefighters said the fires were the worst in the region in 30 years.
The army was called in some areas to help fight the blazes, and air force
helicopters dumped water on fires raging on high mountain ridges.
</P>
<P>
	   Several fires were still burning Monday evening, but those near residential
areas were under control, fire officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
