<HEADLINE> Japan Stocks Down at Midday  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks fell Tuesday morning on profit-taking
following sharp gains the previous day. The dollar edged lower against the yen.
</P>
<P>
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 249.25 points, or 1.28
percent, to 19,187.98 at the end of the morning session. On Monday, the average
rose 480.68 points, or 2.54 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar bought 104.98 yen at late morning, down 0.20 yen from late Monday
in Tokyo but above its late London level of 104.78 yen. Financial markets in New
York were closed Monday for a national holiday.
</P>
<P>
	   On the stock market, prices opened lower as investors locked in profits a
day after the Nikkei closed at its highest level in 29 months.
</P>
<P>
	   Monday's finish of 19,437.23 points was the index's highest close since Aug.
8, 1997, when it ended the day at 19,604.46.
</P>
<P>
	   "Players are adopting wait-and-see positions with U.S. equity markets on
holiday Monday, and profit-taking is hitting Nikkei 225 issues in particular,"
said Tsuguya Onozuka, a dealer at Yamatane Securities.
</P>
<P>
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section was down 13.30 points, or 0.79 percent, to 1,668.67. The TOPIX closed up
33.73 points, or 2.05 percent, the day before.
</P>
<P>
	   In currency dealings, the dollar moved in a narrow range in morning Asian
trading Tuesday after financial markets in New York took Monday off.
</P>
<P>
	   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 105.96 yen, down from 106.80 yen
late Monday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell to 1.7600
percent from Monday's finish of 1.7800 percent. Its price rose 0.17 point to
100.34.
</P>
</TEXT>
