<HEADLINE> SmithKline Workers Await Future  </HEADLINE>
    By BILL BERGSTROM AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- SmithKline Beecham urged its 9,000 Pennsylvania
employees Monday to be patient as they await word on the impact of the company's
merger with Glaxo Wellcome on individual jobs and departments.
</P>
<P>
	   "These questions cannot be answered in the first few weeks or months," said
a notice of the merger that greeted employees arriving in the lobby of
SmithKline's U.S. headquarters in downtown Philadelphia. "The months ahead will
be challenging and stressful."
</P>
<P>
	   SmithKline and Glaxo are combining to form the world's largest
pharmaceutical company.
</P>
<P>
	   Tom Johnson, a Philadelphia spokesman for SmithKline, said: "All U.S.-based
operations will remain in their current location."
</P>
<P>
	   The companies have said SmithKline and Glaxo, which has its U.S.
headquarters at Research Triangle Park, N.C., would keep their U.S. operations
separate.
</P>
<P>
	   SmithKline's chief operating officer, Jean-Pierre Garnier, who lives in the
Philadelphia area and is to become chief executive of the combined company, has
said it would remain committed to the Philadelphia area. Those comments raised
hopes for most of the 2,000 jobs at SmithKline's U.S. headquarters in the city,
2,800 at two research operations in the suburbs, 3,600 jobs in its
nonprescription drug business in Pittsburgh and several hundred scattered sales
and marketing jobs.
</P>
<P>
	   Philadelphia Mayor John F. Street said, "We will do everything we can to
work with them to try to minimize the impact, but in the end I think that there
are going to be fewer jobs and we will probably lose a few."
</P>
<P>
	   Several employees in the lobby said they had been asked not to
comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
