<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man nabbed at border could be daring getaway robber  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - A phony passport and a sword prompted border officials
to deny a man access from Buffalo into Canada. The real surprise came later,
when the NYPD hauled him back to New York on Monday and arrested him for murder.
<P>
	   Officials were also looking into the possibility that the man, whom police
identified as 21-year-old Waftali Triplett, may be responsible for a series of
knifepoint robberies and a daredevil escape from a high-rise.
</P>
<P>
	   A federal law enforcement official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Triplett had "personal notes" with him detailing the crimes.
</P>
<P>
	   Triplett was charged late Monday with second-degree murder and criminal
possession of a weapon in connection with the Dec. 26 killing of a Brooklyn
resident, said Detective Robert Samuel, a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
	   Triplett had been flown back from Buffalo earlier Monday - escorted by
several NYPD detectives - and taken in for questioning, said Deputy Chief Tom
Fahey, another spokesman.
</P>
<P>
	   Police were also investigating whether Triplett was responsible for at least
eight knifepoint robberies since Jan. 8 in midtown Manhattan. The robber fooled
police Jan. 11 after he ran into a high-rise building, jumped out a 19th floor
window onto an air conditioning unit on a nearby rooftop, disguised himself as a
food delivery person and blended into the lunchtime crowd to escape.
</P>
<P>
	   After that getaway, police declared all-out war by splashing a sketch of the
robber all over the news. One tabloid newspaper even dubbed him "Spiderman."
</P>
<P>
	   Did the notoriety send the robber out of town? Was it Triplett? That remains
to be seen, police say. But a police source, speaking on condition of anonymity,
believes the publicity spooked the robber, prompting him to hop a Greyhound bus
Sunday for Buffalo in hopes of fleeing the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   At the border Sunday, Triplett was on a bus at the Peace Bridge crossing
when he was denied access into Canada, said Janet Rapaport, a spokeswoman for
the U.S. Customs Service in New York City.
</P>
<P>
	   He was allegedly sporting a phony passport, had a sword and was carrying a
6-inch dagger and a 12-inch hunting knife.
</P>
<P>
	   Into the arms of waiting Customs officials he went. A check of his personal
effects proved interesting. He had several documents with various names of them,
said the federal official.
</P>
<P>
	   "And personal notes he had indicated he was wanted by the NYPD," the
official said.
</P>
<P>
	   Once in a holding cell in Buffalo, Triplett allegedly tried to get away
again, this time by crawling into a ceiling space after he knocked down some
tiles.
</P>
<P>
	   Back in New York, police were scheduling lineups, hoping a victim or witness
to the recent robberies might link the would-be border crosser to the crimes in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
	   Lineups could begin as early as Tuesday, police said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
