<DOCNO> APW20000117.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A-Bomb Physicist Dies At Age 85  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ITHACA, N.Y. (AP) -- Robert Rathbun Wilson, an influential nuclear physicist
who was a leader in the Manhattan Project, died Sunday of complications of a
stroke he suffered last year. He was 85.
</P>
<P>
	   By 1940, he earned a Ph.D. from the University of California, Berkeley, and
only two years later was collaborating with Enrico Fermi at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology on experiments that would lead to the atomic bomb.
Wilson's job was designing particle accelerators.
</P>
<P>
	   ``No one was more aware of the technical subtlety of accelerators, no one
more ingenious in practical design, no one paid more attention to their
aesthetic qualities,'' said physicist Bruce McDaniel. ``He thought of
accelerator builders as the contemporary equivalent of the builders of the great
cathedrals in France and Italy, but it was the physics potential that came
first.''
</P>
<P>
	   The work at MIT was a precursor to the secretive World War II effort known
as the Manhattan Project. Wilson invented an electromechanical method for
separating uranium isotopes that became known as the Isotron method, according
to Cornell, where Wilson researched and taught.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1943, Wilson and colleagues from Princeton moved a cyclotron, which
smashed atoms, to Los Alamos, New Mexico. There he headed the Experimental
Nuclear Physics Division.
</P>
<P>
	   Two years later, the atomic bomb was dropped over Hiroshima, Japan, and
killed 140,000 people. The United States dropped a second atomic bomb three days
later on Nagasaki, Japan, killing 70,000 people.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1947, Wilson joined the physics faculty at Cornell. Its Wilson Synchotron
Laboratory was named for him.
</P>
<P>
	   Wilson also served as director of the National Accelerator Laboratory in
Batavia, Ill., which, at four-miles-long, was the largest-ever physics facility.
He was Fermilab's director until 1978.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 2259 </TRAILER>
