<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Monday, Jan. 17, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Racial Issues Top Gore, Bradley Debate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- In their sixth and final debate before next
Monday's kickoff Iowa caucuses, presidential hopefuls Al Gore and Bill Bradley
agreed the Confederate flag should come down from atop the South Carolina
statehouse. A number of race-related issues came up in the hour-long televised
debate, ranging from insensitive comments made by Atlanta Braves baseball player
John Rocker, to the controversial New York minister, Al Sharpton. Both men hoped
to use the forum to appeal to voters in other states with a larger minority
population.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Missile Test May Affect US Strategy
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- If successful, a test tomorrow of the Pentagon's
anti-missile missile could move administration officials closer to recommending
that President Clinton commit to deploying a nationwide missile defense. A
system of interceptor rockets, radars and computerized command centers could be
deployed as early as 2005, although many hurdles remain. If tomorrow's test goes
as planned, a 121-pound "smart rock" will steer itself into the path of a mock
warhead about 140 miles above the central Pacific Ocean, creating a collision
that would reduce both objects to space dust. The launch is to take place
sometime during a four-hour period that begins at 9 p.m. EST.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
McCain Defends U.S. Foreign Aid
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   GILFORD, N.H. (AP) -- Sen. John McCain defended U.S. foreign aid today and
said encouraging democracy in other countries can help prevent terrorism. The
Republican presidential candidate met with 150 people early in the morning at a
fire station in Gilford, where the wind chill was well below zero. He also said
some U.S. foreign policies do work, and that by encouraging democracy worldwide
the United States can help prevent terrorism abroad and on U.S. soil.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fires, Flooding Hit South Africa
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) -- Army troops and air force helicopters helped
fight wildfires Monday that destroyed more than 50 homes and left a thick pall
of smoke over Cape Town. While the fires burned for the third day in dry
conditions in the western part of the country, much of the rest of South Africa
was drenched with torrential rains. Weary firefighters said the fires were the
worst in the region in 30 years. Several fires were still burning Monday
evening, but those near residential areas were under control, fire officials
said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Aims To Improve AIDS Funds
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Administration officials said today President Clinton
plans to ask Congress for $175 million for AIDS treatment and prevention
programs in his 2001 budget proposal. Clinton wants $125 million for Ryan White
Comprehensive AIDS Resources Act grants, which provide money for health clinics
treating low-income AIDS patients and for training for those caring for
HIV-infected individuals. The president also will ask Congress to approve $50
million to fund state and local AIDS prevention programs administered by the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japan Stocks Down at Midday
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks fell Tuesday morning on profit-taking
following sharp gains the previous day. The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock
Average shed 249.25 to 19,187.98 at the end of the morning session.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Santana Wins Best-Album Award
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Carlos Santana's band won best-album honors at tonight's
American Music Awards for "Supernatural," a comeback that put the rock guitar
maestro on top of the charts for the first time in his 30-year career. Santana
took the stage to a standing ovation. The show also included an Award of Merit
for Gloria Estefan, who was honored with a musical tribute.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Hornets Beat Raptors 115-94
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Playing their first home game since the death of
co-captain Bobby Phills in a car wreck five days earlier, the Charlotte Hornets
rode a 25-0 surge to a 115-94 victory over the Toronto Raptors today. The run
was one point short of the club record for most consecutive points scored and it
helped the Hornets end a seven-game losing skid. Charlotte, improving to 14-2 at
home, got 25 points and five steals from Eddie Jones, 24 points and 11 rebounds
from Derrick Coleman, and 23 points from Elden Campbell. David Wesley,
repeatedly drawing loud cheers from the crowd of 20,278, finished with nine
points, nine assists and three rebounds.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Avalanche Beat Coyotes 2-0
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DENVER (AP) -- Joe Sakic and Shjon Podein scored first-period goals, and
rookie Marc Denis recorded his third career shutout as the Colorado Avalanche
defeated the Phoenix Coyotes 2-0 today. Denis, raising his career record to
7-6-3, had 27 saves and withstood the Coyotes' 5-on-3 advantage in the second
period. The victory snapped Colorado's six-game winless streak (5-0-1) against
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by PAULINE MILLARD
</P>
