<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Timberwolves 101, Pacers 100  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Malik Sealy banked in a 3-pointer as time expired to
give the Minnesota Timberwolves a 101-100 victory over the Indiana Pacers on
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
	   Mark Jackson had put Indiana ahead with a short jump shot with 1.7 seconds
to play, but Sealy took an inbounds pass from Sam Mitchell and released the
winning shot with Jalen Rose running at him. It banked off the glass and through
the net as the buzzer sounded. Wolves players and coaches raced off the bench
and mobbed Sealy.
</P>
<P>
	   The Wolves rallied from a 10-point deficit in the final quarter, sparked by
Kevin Garnett's career-high 37 points and Joe Smith's 13 fourth-quarter points.
</P>
<P>
	   The Wolves played without starting point guard Terrell Brandon, who suffered
a right calf strain in a loss Saturday to the Los Angeles Lakers. Rookie William
Avery started in his place.
</P>
<P>
	   Garnett's turnaround jumper with 2:52 to play gave Minnesota its first lead
since early in the third quarter at 91-90.
</P>
<P>
	   Reggie Miller converted a four-point play with 2:24 to go to give Indiana a
94-91 lead. Smith's free throw and Garnett's turnaround jumper tied the score.
</P>
<P>
	   Dale Davis and Garnett traded baskets twice before Jackson backed his way
into the lane and released his one-handed shot.
</P>
<P>
	   Rik Smits scored 14 of his 20 points in the third quarter for the Pacers to
give Indiana what appeared to be a comfortable lead.
</P>
<P>
	   Smits, who played only six minutes in the first half because of two early
fouls, scored 10 points during a 17-10 run to end the quarter.
</P>
<P>
	   But Smith scored 11 of his team's first 14 points in the fourth quarter,
then Garnett hit seven shots in a row.
</P>
<P>
	   Indiana fought back from an eight-point first-quarter deficit to lead by
three at halftime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
