<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador Indians Want President Out  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Groups of Indians blocked highways in several
Ecuadorean provinces Monday, the latest in a series of protests aimed at forcing
the resignation of President Jamil Mahuad.
</P>
<P>
	   Security forces quickly cleared the roads of tree trunks and rocks in the
eight provinces and there were no reports of clashes with the demonstrators,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   Mahuad has been the target of increasing calls from across the political
spectrum to resign because of his failure to stop Ecuador's economic decline.
Inflation topped 60 percent last year, the highest in Latin America, and the
economy shrank 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   In an effort to stabilize the economy, the government last week replaced the
national currency, the sucre, with the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
	   Protest organizers said the currency change was also a focus of Thursday's
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Adopting the dollar will mean that the poor will all die of hunger, misery
and poverty,'' said Antonio Vargas, president of the Indigenous Confederation.
</P>
<P>
	   Ecuador's economic woes have prompted several recent demonstrations, and the
government declared a state of emergency, allowing it to deploy troops to keep
order.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
