<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4-alarm fire raging in Newark  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - A raging, four-alarm fire visible for miles tore
through a candle factory Monday evening, threatening nearby homes, sending
plumes of choking smoke for miles and forcing the evacuation of about 10
families.
<P>
	   No injuries were reported, said Fire Chief James Langenbach.
</P>
<P>
	   The block-long commercial building housing the Mercury Candle Co., near
Interstate 78 and the Irvington border, began burning just after 3 p.m,
Langenbach said. Within an hour, the four-alarm fire drew as many as 130
firefighters from 29 surrounding fire companies.
</P>
<P>
	   Firefighters were hampered by subfreezing temperatures and gusting winds.
But the winds died down about 7 p.m., and the fire was declared under control at
8:14 p.m.
</P>
<P>
	   Langenbach said firefighters expected to be putting out hotspots into the
early morning.
</P>
<P>
	   Electricity was cut to about 50 customers shortly after the fire began, said
PSE&AMP;G spokeswoman Valorie Ferrara. Some will have power restored on Tuesday, but
Ferrara said others will have to wait an "extended period" as repairs to burned
wires are made.
</P>
<P>
	   Residents without power were staying at a Red Cross shelter established at a
nearby elementary school.
</P>
<P>
	   "I thought we were all going to burn. But we got out OK," said employee
Maria Cuevas.
</P>
<P>
	   "I just went outside, and I heard two explosions," said Meg Batta, who was
working in a Pathmark supermarket a block and a half from the fire. "There's
heavy black smoke all over here. If the wind shifts, we might have to close."
</P>
<P>
	   Flames leapt from the building's roof, and heavy plumes of smoke obscured
motorists' vision on Route 78.
</P>
<P>
	   "Lord, it was so black you couldn't see a thing," said Myrtle Turner, who
lives two blocks from the fire on Fabyan Place. "There was fire all over. It was
terrible."
</P>
<P>
	   "We saw the flames, and heard sirens and ambulances," added Audrey Anderson,
an employee of The Rainbow Shop, a dress store on Lyons Avenue in Irvington,
also a block and a half from the fire.
</P>
<P>
	   Langenbach refused to comment on a possible cause for the blaze, but said it
was under investigation.
</P>
<P>
	   The building also contained a business that made kitchen equipment, said an
employee who declined to identify himself.
</P>
<P>
	   Langenbach said cold air had not frozen firefighters' hoses, but water was
freezing upon contact with the ground.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-17-00 2319 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000117.0273 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haitian Kids To Be Reunited With Mom  </HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL NORTON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) -- The two Haitian children still lack passports,
but they have a more valuable treasure: permission to join their mother in
Florida and, possibly, begin a new life far from the privations of their native
Haiti.
</P>
<P>
	   Marc Yvens Dieubon, 9, and Germanie, 8, were typically polite and reserved
as they waited Monday for exit papers from the Haitian government. But they
turned giddy when they thought about their reunion with their mother, who is in
a Florida hospital.
</P>
<P>
	   ``You are always on my mind,'' was the message Germanie asked to send to her
mother. ``I am longing to see you again.''
</P>
<P>
	   The siblings were separated from their mother, Yvena Rhinvil, after a
smuggling boat packed with 411 would-be migrants ran aground off the Florida
coast on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
	   Rhinvil, 33, who is pregnant, was one of four people brought ashore for
medical treatment. Her children were left on the boat and were among the 407
people returned to Haiti.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They took our mother away. We cried, but nobody asked us why,'' said Marc,
who along with his sister rode in different section of the rickety vessel,
squeezed together so tightly that they had to sleep hunched over on a bench.
They hardly moved during the several days they spent at sea.
</P>
<P>
	   The siblings became the focus of an intense lobby by Haitian-Americans who
contrasted their plight with the immense attention given Elian Gonzalez, the
6-year-old Cuban boy at the center of an international custody dispute.
</P>
<P>
	   Cuba's government is demanding that Gonzalez, rescued after a smuggling
accident off Florida, be returned to his father in Cuba. Gonzalez's relatives in
Miami, backed by Cuban-American exile leaders, are demanding he be allowed to
remain in the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   The two cases underscored what critics say is a double standard between
Cubans and others who seek refuge in the United States. Thanks to a 1966 law,
Cubans who reach shore usually are allowed to stay. Haitians and others are
usually repatriated unless they successfully navigate the complex and difficult
political asylum process.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service granted the children
humanitarian parole on Thursday. INS officials say U.S. Coast Guard officers
didn't know Rhinvil had children on board before they took her from the boat.
</P>
<P>
	   Enthusiastically, Marc and Germanie showed off the English they'd learned
from Coast Guard officers.
</P>
<P>
	   ``One, two, three, four,'' they counted in proud and happy unison. Dark eyes
gleaming, they rattled off the numbers all the way to 10 in the offices of the
National Coalition for Haitian Rights, which has given them haven in an
undisclosed location.
</P>
<P>
	   The identity and location of their father isn't known.
</P>
<P>
	   Yvena Rhinvil has applied for political asylum, said Pierre Esperance,
director of the Haitian rights group. He said he was optimistic that she will
succeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 2320 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000117.0274 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No. 7 Kansas 78, Texas A&AMP;M 57  </HEADLINE>
    By MICHAEL A. LUTZ AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   COLLEGE STATION, Texas (AP) -- Kenny Gregory scored 15 points and led a
second half run as No. 7 Kansas used its superior height to beat Texas A&AMP;M 78-57
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
	   Kansas (15-2, 4-0 in Big 12) led 45-39 with 16:51 before breaking away with
a 27-9 run. Texas A&AMP;M (5-10, 1-3) was coming off a controversial 88-86 victory
over Texas Tech on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Jayhawks outrebounded the Aggies 55-32, led by Drew Gooden, who had 10
points and 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
	   Kansas has won seven games in a row since losing to Illinois 84-70 on Dec.
18. The Jayhawks' 15-2 start is their best start since they were 16-1 to start
the 1997-98 season.
</P>
<P>
	   The balanced Kansas offense didn't score at its usual 86-point per game
pace, but the defense shut down the Aggies. Tomas Ress hit a basket in the
closing seconds for 10 points, Texas A&AMP;M's only scorer in double figures.
</P>
<P>
	   Kansas guard Jeff Boschee went 0-for-5 from 3-point range, ending a string
of 38 consecutive games with at least one 3-pointer. Kansas was 2-for-11 on
3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
	   The Aggies tried to jump on the Jayhawks from the start and their
aggressiveness netted them four steals in the first 8:28. They even managed an
early 14-10 lead before an excited Reed Arena crowd of 12,175, a record for the
two-year old arena.
</P>
<P>
	   But Kansas' 11-man rotation paid off and the Jayhawks took the lead for good
on a basket by Gooden with 7:56 to go in the half. Kansas built a 36-26 edge
late in the first half as the Aggies had only three points over the final 4:12.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-17-00 2322 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
