<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Announcing New Gun Program  </HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN GALVIN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is taking a new tack in the fight
against gun violence by asking Congress for $280 million to hire 500 more ATF
agents and expand a system to track firearms through ballistics tests, officials
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The president was to announce the program Tuesday in Boston. The appearance
at the Orchard Gardens Community Center in Boston's Roxbury section also was
expected to highlight Clinton's community policing initiative.
</P>
<P>
	   After a spate of high-profile shooting attacks by troubled killers at high
schools and other places, Clinton pushed for tougher gun-control measures in
Congress. Lawmakers refused to close the gun show loophole in the Brady law or
require safety locks on handguns.
</P>
<P>
	   Outlining plans for his final year in office, Clinton last week alluded to
new projects aimed at curbing gun violence. The administration already announced
a request for $10 million to develop ``smart guns'' that fire only when held by
their owners.
</P>
<P>
	   The new plans for the budget for fiscal year 2001, which begins Oct. 1,
represent an effort to invest more in enforcement of laws aimed at combating the
illegal use and possession of firearms.
</P>
<P>
	   People familiar with Clinton's plan, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said he would ask Congress to hire more Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms
agents and inspectors and for money to improve federal investigators' ability to
track crimes through improved ballistics testing.
</P>
<P>
	   By maintaining records of unique markings each gun barrel leaves on bullets,
investigators could track firearms used in crimes to their purchasers, even if
that person had passed the weapon to another individual.
</P>
<P>
	   ``What I want us to do is to put our partisan divisions aside to complete
the unfinished business of the last century,'' Clinton said, ``including things
like ... sensible legislation to keep guns out of the hands of criminals and
children.''
</P>
<P>
	   Boston's homicide rate dropped to a 38-year low in 1999, thanks in part to a
program that allied law enforcement, the clergy, community leaders and gang
members against crime.
</P>
<P>
	   The effort, called the Boston Pilot Project, is credited with forcing the
homicide toll down from 132 slayings in 1990 to 31 in 1999. A strong economy and
declining use of crack cocaine also contributed to improved neighborhood
security.
</P>
<P>
	   Mayor Thomas Menino and Massachusetts Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, both
Democrats, and several religious and community leaders were expected to attend
the address at the Orchard Gardens, in an area where crime was down more than 65
percent last year, officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   In his Roxbury appearance, Clinton also was expected to stress the success
of his 1994 crime-fighting package, which provided money for 100,000 community
police officers. The fiscal 2000 budget includes funds for 50,000 more.
</P>
<P>
	   Later Tuesday, Clinton was addressing a Democratic National Committee
fund-raising reception at a private residence in a Boston suburb.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
