<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Seek AIDS Funds  </HEADLINE>
   By KAREN GULLO Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton will ask Congress for $175 million in
additional funding for AIDS treatment and prevention programs in his 2001 budget
proposal, administration officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton wants an increase of $125 million in spending on grants ubder the
Ryan White Comprehensive AIDS Resources Act. The 10-year-old program, named for
the Indiana boy whose battle with AIDS attracted national attention, provides
money for health clinics treating low-income AIDS patients and for training for
those caring for HIV-infected individuals.
</P>
<P>
	   The president also will ask Congress to approve $50 million more to fund
state and local AIDS prevention programs administered by the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention. It's the most the administration has ever asked for
prevention, which AIDS groups say is woefully underfunded by the government.
</P>
<P>
	   This year, CDC prevention programs are receiving $695 million and the Ryan
White grant program $1.6 billion, although budget cuts Clinton agreed to with
Congress last year could reduce those amounts.
</P>
<P>
	   While the number of AIDS deaths has dropped dramatically in recent years
thanks to new treatments, the decline in deaths slowed last year and the disease
is hitting minority groups and women hard.
</P>
<P>
	   Blacks, who make up about 13 percent of the U.S. population, accounted for
49 percent of AIDS deaths in 1998, according to the CDC. Thirty-two percent of
deaths were among whites and 18 percent were among Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
	   More than 23 percent of AIDS diagnoses reported in 1998 were among women.
</P>
<P>
	   Activists who have been calling on the government to put more money into
prevention said Clinton's 2001 budget proposal falls short.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They have gone from closing their eyes to giving prevention a passing
glance,'' said Steven Fisher, spokesman of the advocacy group AIDS Action.
``It's not enough to make a dent in the 40,000 new infections every year, half
of which are among young people.''
</P>
<P>
	   The proposal comes as the Ryan White program celebrates its 10th anniversary
this week. Since it started in 1990, the program has received $6.4 billion in
federal funding. More than 500,000 people -- many of whom have no insurance --
have received care each year through the program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
