<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Monday, Jan. 17, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore, Bradley Clash in 6th Debate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Bill Bradley challenged Vice President Al Gore
Monday night to demand the administration issue an immediate order banning
racial profiling, but Gore shot back in campaign debate, "I don't think
President Bill Clinton needs a lecture from Bill Bradley" on standing up for
blacks and Hispanics. Perched on stools on a debate stage in Iowa's capital
city, both men said firmly they oppose racial profiling, the practice by which
some police offers target racial minorities for traffic stops. A number of
racially sensitive issues came up in the hour-long televised debate on the
federal holiday honoring the late Martin Luther King, Jr.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Poll: Democrats Hold Edge Over GOP
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Private Republican polling shows Democrats hold an edge
on top election-year concerns, and 25 percent of George W. Bush's support
"prefers Democrats on the issues by a significant margin." Democrats were
favored, 44 percent to 31 percent, when the survey asked potential voters which
party cares more about them, according to the poll shown recently to about 50
GOP members of the House. At the same time, the findings suggested several ways
for House Republicans to gain an advantage, including opening a "new issue
front" on such subjects as government waste or retiring the national debt. The
GOP is trying to retain its narrow majority in the House.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ecuador Indians Want President Out
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Groups of Indians blocked highways in several
Ecuadorean provinces Monday, the latest in a series of protests aimed at forcing
the resignation of President Jamil Mahuad. Mahuad has been the target of
increasing calls from across the political spectrum to resign because of his
failure to stop Ecuador's economic decline. Ecuador's economic woes have
prompted several recent demonstrations, and the government declared a state of
emergency, allowing it to deploy troops to keep order.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
SmithKline Workers Await Future
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- SmithKline Beecham urged its 9,000 Pennsylvania
employees Monday to be patient as they await word on the impact of the company's
merger with Glaxo Wellcome on individual jobs and departments. SmithKline and
Glaxo are combining to form the world's largest pharmaceutical company. Tom
Johnson, a Philadelphia spokesman for SmithKline, said: "All U.S.-based
operations will remain in their current location." The companies have said
SmithKline and Glaxo, which has its U.S. headquarters at Research Triangle Park,
N.C., would keep their U.S. operations separate.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japan Stocks Down at Midday
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks fell Tuesday morning on profit-taking
following sharp gains the previous day. The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock
Average shed 249.25 to 19,187.98 at the end of the morning session.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Santana Wins Best-Album Award
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Carlos Santana's band won best-album honors at Monday's
American Music Awards for "Supernatural," a commercial comeback that put the
rock guitar maestro on top of the charts for the first time in his 30-year
career. Shania Twain won two awards, for favorite pop-rock female artist and
country female artist. Garth Brooks also won two awards, for favorite country
male artist and country album for "Double Live." The other double winner was
Lauryn Hill for favorite soul-rhythm and blues female artist and top soul-R&AMP;B
album for "The Miseducation of Lauryn Hill."
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Timberwolves Beat Pacers 101-100
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Malik Sealy banked in a 3-pointer as time expired to
give the Minnesota Timberwolves a 101-100 victory over the Indiana Pacers on
Monday night. Mark Jackson had put Indiana ahead with a short jump shot with 1.7
seconds to play, but Sealy took an inbounds pass from Sam Mitchell and released
the winning shot with Jalen Rose running at him. It banked off the glass and
through the net as the buzzer sounded. The Wolves played without starting point
guard Terrell Brandon, who suffered a right calf strain in a loss Saturday to
the Los Angeles Lakers. Rookie William Avery started in his place.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Charismatic is Horse of the Year
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   Charismatic, who broke a leg while straining for a victory in the Belmont
Stakes and the Triple Crown champion, was honored as the Horse of the Year for
1999 on Monday night. The strapping chestnut colt, a claiming horse in February
and a Kentucky Derby and Preakness winner in the spring, won the Eclipse Award
as racing's top performer in a split vote with Europe-based Daylami, winner of
the Breeders' Cup Turf on Nov. 6 in his only U.S. start. Charismatic finished
third in the Belmont Stakes, 1 1/2 lengths behind winner Lemon Drop Kid, while
sustaining two fractures of his left front leg. The breakdown apparently
happened with about an eighth-mile remaining. His record for the year was four
wins, two seconds and a third, with earnings of $2,007,404.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by PAULINE MILLARD
</P>
